<HEAD>Stricken Pilot Rescued After Plane on Autopilot Crashes into Atlantic</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf with 6 grafs to UPDATE with quotes from tape of
conversation between Root and controllers; picks up 9th graf, ``There was
...''</HEAD>
<HEAD>LasePhotos WX26, MH1,2,4, LaserGraphic NY29</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A small plane with a stricken pilot flew hundreds of miles down the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> on autopilot shadowed by military jets Thursday, finally running out of gas and spiraling into the ocean. The pilot then emerged from the wreckage and swam toward his startled rescuers, authorities said. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Root </PERSON>, a 36-year-old lawyer from <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, was pulled from Bahamian waters by <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> parachutists four hours after he had first radioed he was in trouble. He was first taken to <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION> and a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> helicopter then flew him to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. `` For him to survive a crash like that, it just sent us all into shock,'' said Petty Officer <PERSON> Veronica </PERSON> <PERSON> Cady </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. `` We did n't expect this story to have a happy ending.'' Coast Guard Capt. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahman </PERSON> said Root may have passed out from carbon monoxide poisoning in the cockpit of his single-engine <ORGANIZATION> Cessna </ORGANIZATION> and that water splashing in his face apparently roused him. Root was taken to Memorial Hospital in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, where he underwent three-hours of exploratory surgery for possible internal injuries. After the operation, his condition was upgraded from critical to stable, said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Wine </PERSON>. Root's family requested no information be released on his injuries, she said. Root's wife, <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON>, 35, told reporters from the porch of the family home that her husband had been awake and talking to doctors. She said she told hospital officials to send her husband the following message: `` Root, you really did it this time.'' The drama began about 8:30 a.m. when Root, who had taken off from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> about 6:30 a.m. for <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, radioed air traffic controllers in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. `` Yessir, we're having a little problem up here,'' <PERSON> Root </PERSON> told controllers, according to a tape of the conversation played by <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> television station <ORGANIZATION> WRC-TV </ORGANIZATION>. `` Seem to have a little trouble breathing,'' said Root, who also reported chest pain. `` How far am I to Rocky Mount now?'' `` You're about 17 minutes from <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION>,'' replied an unidentified controller. `` Uh,'' said the pilot. `` Niner niner one three <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION>, do you hear?'' said the controller, calling the plane's number. There was no further radio contact, and military pilots who tailed the plane reported he was slumped behind the controls as his plane flew south off the coast, occasionally getting within 100 miles of the shore. Military pilots and rescuers trained to parachute into the ocean to save ditched pilots could only watch helplessly as their aircraft tracked the plane until it ran out of gas. After more than 3 -LCB- hours of radio silence, the plane spiraled into the water and Root was rescued, 800 miles from his original destination in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and 250 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` The words you keep hearing are, ` You're kidding,''' said Ms. <PERSON> Cady </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said the plane went down about 15 miles east of the island of <LOCATION> Eleuthera </LOCATION>. `` It spiraled into the water, so it did n't make the best of all possible landings,'' said Chief Petty Officer <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Parris </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lt </ORGANIZATION>. Commander <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Poll </PERSON>, who was at the scene in a jet when <PERSON> Root </PERSON> crashed, said the plane was at about 7,000 feet when it began spiraling in like a corkscrew and spinning down at about 2,000 feet per minute. Poll said the nose and left wing hit the water at the same time and the plane swiveled on its belly on a 360-degree spin. He said it stayed afloat for several minutes and started to sink. Air Force Sgt. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>, one of four <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technicians </ORGANIZATION> who parachuted into the water, said <PERSON> Root </PERSON> was first spotted swimming away from the wreckage dressed only in pants and socks. Root was pulled onto a raft and given first aid, said <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>, based at the <ORGANIZATION> 301st </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Recovery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Homestead </LOCATION>, about 20 miles south of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` He told us his abdomen is hurting a lot and we could see he was bleeding,'' said <PERSON> Hayden </PERSON>. `` It was incredible. He had a sense of humor about it.'' <PERSON> Rahman </PERSON>, the doctor who treated Root in <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Root </PERSON> was alert and could speak well but seemed to be in shock and had abdominal injuries and fractured ribs. <PERSON> Rahman </PERSON> said there was no indication of a heart attack and Root had no history of heart trouble. `` It's definitely a miracle he's alive. He's a little confused by it all,'' the doctor said. After its distress call, the plane was intercepted by two <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> F-A-18 jet fighters when it entered <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> Naval Station airspace at 8:45 a.m., said Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. The pilots of the intercepting planes tried unsuccessfully to contact the pilot by radio, he said. The Cessna 210 Centurion can seat four to six people, counting the pilot, and cruises at about 190 mph. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Pierman </PERSON>, shift supervisor in the air traffic control tower at <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION>, told <ORGANIZATION> Raleigh </ORGANIZATION> radio station <ORGANIZATION> WPTF </ORGANIZATION> that the autopilot was set on a heading that would have sent the plane toward <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>. `` Put an airplane on automatic pilot and it's going to continue just exactly on the course that the automatic pilot is set for,'' he said. At time of crash, <PERSON> Root </PERSON> was followed by a C-130 cargo plane from <ORGANIZATION> Homestead </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION> near <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> and an HH3 helicopter from <ORGANIZATION> Patrick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, also on <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanek </PERSON> of Homestead. A flight surgeon was part of the rescue teams, she said.
