<HEAD>Soviets Plan to Launch Ads Into Space, Newspaper Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has hired a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> advertising company to sell broadcast rights and corporate sponsorships for the first British-Soviet space mission, scheduled for 1991, a newspaper reported Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> said the Soviets have hired the <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Saatchi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest advertising and marketing conglomerate, to exploit the commercial opportunities of the Juno mission. The mission, which will carry <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s first astronaut into orbit from a launching pad in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, will be financed entirely by the sale of commercial opportunities, the newspaper said. That includes the sale of space aboard the Soviets' Mir space station for scientific payloads. The Times reported that more than 10,000 men and woman responded to an advertisement <PERSON> Saatchi </PERSON> placed in several British newspapers in late June that carried the headline: `` Astronaut wanted. No experience necessary.'' If the Soviets are successful in this and other commerical ventures, a soft drink or cheesburger may be advertised on the side of a Soviet Soyuz rocket, while commericals to promote a sneaker as the official athletic footwear of the space product, the newspaper said. The Soviet space agency, Glavkosmos, two weeks ago gave <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the exclusive right to market its goods and services in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Glavkosmos has signed commerical agreements with several Western companies. In March, a Japanese televison network paid the agency 12 million <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars for the right to send a correspondent into space in 1991. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, which administers the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space program, does not accept advertising or payment from private citizens for flights. In the past, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space shuttles have carried some projects for a fee, but that practice was canceled after the Challenger explosion in 1986 that killed seven astronauts.
