<HEAD>Army, Activists Battle for Control of `Liberated' Village</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALFIT, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For nearly a year, this was a `` liberated'' village. Outlawed <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> flags fluttered from light poles, activists patrolled the streets, slogans covered the walls, and popular committees did the work of city hall. No longer. At dawn on July 5, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers stormed the village of 5,000 people, and reopened army-run government offices, which had been attacked and burned by rioters in January. `` This is a test case. We went in because <LOCATION> Salfit </LOCATION> had been portrayed as a main center of the intefadeh,'' or Palestinian uprising, said Col. <PERSON> Udi </PERSON> <PERSON> Sagey </PERSON>. He referred to Palistinian statements that the village had been `` liberated'' from <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> occupation. Of the 420 villages in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>, several dozen like <LOCATION> Salfit </LOCATION> have declared themselves `` liberated.'' <PERSON> Sagey </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> unit in the area, said he planned to reopen its medical center, reconnect the telephones, restore postal and agricultural extension services, and resume construction of a new road. `` The first goal of the intefadeh leaders has been to cut the ties between the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities and the people,'' he said. `` If the economic support to these people is greater, maybe they will be less radical towards Israeli authorities.'' He said he hoped if normal life was restored in <LOCATION> Salfit </LOCATION>, it would have an impact on neighboring villages that depend on <LOCATION> Salfit </LOCATION> for services. Since the start of the 19-month Palestinian uprising, <LOCATION> Salfit </LOCATION> was largely ignored by the army because it is isolated at the end of a single-lane road. The village is only 18 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>, but it is in rocky hills far from main highways and Jewish settlements. In January, Palestinian rioters forced the closure of all government offices and activists bedecked <LOCATION> Salfit </LOCATION> with symbols of independence: red, black, white and green <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> flags and a map of the would-be <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state on a wall in the town center. Popular committees made up of activists aligned with the <ORGANIZATION> Fatah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> faction and communist groups organized underground schools, medical services, street cleaning and agriculture. In short, <LOCATION> Salfit </LOCATION> became a microcosm for the independent state that Palestinians hope they can achieve if <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 21-year occupation is ended. `` There is no higher voice than the voice of the intefadeh,'' declared graffiti, freshly painted on a wall where the army had covered over previous slogans. <PERSON> Rafaat </PERSON>, 29, a blacksmith talking with friends at a shop on the village's main <LOCATION> Gamal </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Abdel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Nasser </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, said there has been little resistance to the army takeover because about 200 activists fled into the countryside to avoid arrest. `` We were liberated for a few months. But now there is more tension because at any moment a soldier can stop you or arrest you,'' said <PERSON> Rafaat </PERSON>, who declined to give his full name for fear of reprisal. The streets still bear the evidence of past protests: the remains of burned tires and scorched stones blocking part of one entrance to the village. <PERSON> Ahmed </PERSON>, a 25-year-old grocer, said soldiers patrol frequently, but there were some small acts of defiance. He said youths had hung about 100 flags the previous night. This was disputed by a soldier standing guard outside the new military encampment that sported an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> flag. He said there had been only two flags. `` The town is so quiet now that we go on patrol with just our berets and no helmets,'' he added. About a dozen Palestinians gathered at the <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> offices. One man said he wanted an entry permit to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> for a relative who lives in <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION>; another said he wanted a travel document to return to his job in the <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Yet another, wearing a bandage to cover a head wound he said was inflicted by soldiers, had come to get his ID card that had been taken during a search-and-arrest raid. All were kept waiting several hours even though a reporter who entered the encampment found two army offices sitting alone in their offices. `` Let them wait for awhile,'' said the guard with a shrug. <PERSON> Bassam </PERSON> <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Maadi </PERSON>, a doctor who lives in a spacious villa on the edge of town, said <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> activists and the army were watching each other carefully to see what would happen next. `` It will not stop in <LOCATION> Salfit </LOCATION> as long as the intefadeh continues elsewhere in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. It will not stop until there is some hope offered for the future,'' said <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Maadi </PERSON>, 37. During the course of the uprising, he said, three Palestinians from <LOCATION> Salfit </LOCATION> had been shot to death and about 50 wounded. About 250 had been detained at one point or another. <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Maadi </PERSON> said arbitrary actions and collective punishments had left a feeling of resentment toward <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. He said that after a Jewish settler was killed in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> in June, soldiers came to his house, broke the porch lights and smashed a front window. `` I came downstairs and opened the door. An officer hit me in the face without warning or comment. He then ordered me to go to the school where everyone was being rounded up,'' <PERSON> Abu </PERSON> <PERSON> Maadi </PERSON> said. `` If I do something wrong, I will accept punishment. But this is punishing everyone.''
