<HEAD>Sikh's Turban Causes Headache for Norwegian Military</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Norwegian defense officials have added turbans to the military dress code after a year-long battle by a Sikh immigrant who demanded the right to keep his traditional dress during military service. <PERSON> Harvinder </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, 25, became the first Norwegian soldier ever allowed to wear a turban on duty, the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Verdens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gang </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, who came from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> in 1978, was called up in July for a year of compulsory military training. He wanted to serve but refused to remove his turban, the newspaper said. <PERSON> Singh </PERSON> was sent home while military officials mulled over the problem. The supreme command decided that <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> must adapt to recruits from various cultures and ordered that standard issue turbans be prepared to fit the military dress code, defense spokesman <PERSON> Erik </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinstad </PERSON> told the newspaper.
