<HEAD>China Artificially Propagates Crested Ibis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> zoo has become the world's first to artificially breed a crested ibis, a long-billed wading bird that is near extinction, the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Daily said today. The 2-ounce bird was born Monday, ending a three-year effort by the zoo to find a way to artificially propagate the species, the official daily said. It said the 4-year-old mother delivered two eggs in mid-June, but pecked one of the babies to death. The other was removed to a breeding box for special care. The crested ibis was once found in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> as well as <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but its population has declined dramatically because of destruction to its environment, the daily said. It said only about 48 of the species survive, two in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the rest in <LOCATION> Yangxian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> of central <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Shaanxi </LOCATION> province.
