<HEAD>Blind Cowboy Depends on Horses for Independence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARTESIA, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A horse that knows when it's safe to cross intersections allows a blind former cowboy to keep his independence, but the city says the man must clean up after the animal or lose the privilege. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>, 69, who retains about 1 percent of his sight in one eye, has a year to persuade the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> to let him keep two horses, Blue Rocky and Buck, in his back yard. When <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> rides Blue Rocky through town, the horse stops at intersections and does n't move until traffic is flowing in the direction the horse is supposed to go. In 1981, the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> granted <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> a lifetime zoning variance allowing him to keep the horses in town. But inspectors reported in 1987 that <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> was n't cleaning up after the horses and was bothering neighbors with the smell. The variance was revoked and a judge fined <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> $ 100. The fine was thrown out on appeal. Last month, a judge gave <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> a year to change the council's mind or move the horses `` Now, hopefully, what we're doing is right,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. `` As far as being unfair, he's the one who's being unfair to his neighbors.'' <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> said the neighbor behind the complaints is <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON>, who wanted to sell his house next door but was afraid <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>'s horses would lower property values. <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> is not on speaking terms with <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> nor with reporters. `` I do n't want to say nothing about that crap. No, bye,'' he said, hanging up. <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON>, who likes to smoke hand-rolled cigarettes and reminisce about the days when he worked as a cowboy in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, had to stop working in 1964 because of retinitis pigmentosa, a hereditary degenerative eye disease. But <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> likes to ride Blue Rocky the two miles to downtown <LOCATION> Artesia </LOCATION>, across six intersections with stoplights. He could see better about 10 years ago, when he got Blue Rocky and started leading the horse on his walks into town. When <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> heard traffic going in the direction he was walking, that meant the light had turned green and he would cross the intersection. Now the horse decides when it's time to cross. `` He automatically stops anyhow at any intersection,'' <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> said. `` I guarantee you he wo n't go unless the traffic is going my way. Whether he can read the light is the $ 64 question.'' Other times, <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> rides his horse into the hills west of his house. `` You know, I can get kind of down and out because I ca n't work, and get on that old horse and ride five or six miles and, hey, I got a different outlook on life all of a sudden,'' <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> said. `` I'm completely independent. He shudders at the thought of losing his horses. `` Oh, I suppose somebody could take me places, but you have to go back when they want to go back _ you know, you're not independent.''
