<HEAD>Olivier's Death: The End of An Era?</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> is gone. Will the theater world ever see his like again? Said critic <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, who wrote in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> after <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> died Tuesday: `` No one will replace the splendor that he gave his native land with his genius.'' Other critics say that while another <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> may be in the wings, they feel today's entertainment industry makes it doubtful. Primarily a man of the stage, <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> became a superstar in all media. The sheer quantity of his work is among the most noteworthy aspects of a career that ended with his death at age 82, at his country home south of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. But <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> was also the consummate actor-manager _ a passionate theater advocate as important behind the scenes as a director and organizer as he was on stage as a performer. Few theater observers would dispute that first-rate <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> actors continue to abound. <PERSON> Derek </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobi </PERSON>, <PERSON> Vanessa </PERSON> <PERSON> Redgrave </PERSON>, <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON>, <PERSON> Glenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bates </PERSON>, <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> McKellen </PERSON> are just some of the generation after <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> who have been widely and often acclaimed. Then there's a still younger generation less known abroad but already staring greatness in the eye: <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Branagh </PERSON>, <PERSON> Antony </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>, <PERSON> Juliet </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fiona </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>. And although <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s death is being called the end of an era, he is survived by such stalwart knights and dames of stage as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gielgud </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mills </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rex </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, <PERSON> Alec </PERSON> <PERSON> Guinness </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiller </PERSON> and <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashcroft </PERSON>. But it's <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s level of commitment to the art form he cherished that may be in shorter supply. `` Will anyone ever again go on for so long, play so many great parts, run so many companies?'' asked <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Coveney </PERSON> in The Financial Times. `` Will they want to enough? We must doubt it until they do.'' <PERSON> Milton </PERSON> <PERSON> Shulman </PERSON> in The Evening Standard also feared such dedication was dying. `` The likes of <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>, nurtured on greasepaint, the footlights, and the effrontery of daring an audience to like you, are fast becoming an endangered species.'' The stage instead, he wrote, is `` fast becoming the casting kindergarten for film and TV.'' The trend is increasing in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> as talented young theater actors opt for the greater financial rewards of film and TV. <PERSON> Natasha </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilby </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Amanda </PERSON> <PERSON> Donohoe </PERSON> are just some of the classically schooled young English talents who work mostly on screen. Among the older generation, none has matched the initiative of <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>, who in 1963 realized an old dream of establishing a National Theater of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. `` The quality of work we do here is mostly due to him,'' veteran actor <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> told Tuesday night's audience at the National's production of `` The Voysey Inheritance. Some feel <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s death ends a kind of theatrical majesty that transcends issues of talent. In an editorial entitled `` Stage Colossus,'' The <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> wrote: `` He was the undisputed leader of his profession, its spokesman, and the brightest jewel in its crown. We shall not look upon his like again.'' <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> wrote: `` What we have lost with <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> is glory. ... You could practically see it growing around him like a nimbus.'' <PERSON> Denis </PERSON> <PERSON> Quilley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s co-star in a celebrated <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> production of <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON>'s `` Long Day's Journey Into Night,'' said in an interview, `` There are people today -LRB- like <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> -RRB- but not on the same scale.'' Would-be inheritors most frequently mentioned are men like <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Pennington </PERSON> and the protean <PERSON> Branagh </PERSON>, <PERSON> Guy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pringle </PERSON> in the TV series `` Fortunes of War,'' who combine thespian dynamism with a team spirit. Both have started theater companies _ <PERSON> Pennington </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> English </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shakespeare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, which finished a world tour in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> this spring, and <PERSON> Branagh </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Renaissance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, which had a sell-out <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> season on the West End last fall. <PERSON> Branagh </PERSON>, 28, tempted further comparisons to <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> by starring on stage and screen as <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> V </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s most celebrated achievements. <PERSON> Branagh </PERSON>'s film is due out in the fall. <PERSON> Antony </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>'s 1984 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> also was likened to <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>'s. But South African-born Sher, 40, has forsaken the spotlight to focus on writing. <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> Rigg </PERSON>, who appeared with <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Stratford-upon-Avon </LOCATION> and in his 1983 TV `` King <PERSON> Lear </PERSON>,'' says the case is n't closed on greatness. `` It's impossible to say you'll never see the likes of him again,'' she said in an interview. `` The profession is full of incredibly talented people, some in the cradle.''
