<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MICHIGAN CITY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Marines were battling for every inch of beachhead and met no resistance from about 2,000 spectators. Four amphibious landing craft from the USS Boulder bounded ashore Wednesday and disgorged 90 Marines in full battle gear. Instead of charging deadly pillboxes and lethal snipers, the leathernecks directed blank fire toward toward a pop stand, three port-a-johns and a festively colored tent where a six-piece <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> band had been playing. With bases concentrated on ocean coasts, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Marines </ORGANIZATION> rarely get to show their stuff to Midwesterners, said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Lt. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Knox </PERSON>. Spectators on the <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> beach broke into applause as the blank automatic weapons fire finally ceased. `` It was really cool,'' said 13-year-old <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Huff </PERSON>. Mayor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Behler </PERSON>, an ex-Marine, rode in the assault wave carrying a fantasy instead of a rifle. `` I wanted to dress like -LRB- Gen. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> MacArthur </ORGANIZATION> and just stand on the beach with my corncob pipe and glasses,'' he said.
