<DATELINE>PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A man climbed into a hot tub with a joke and planned to keep up the routine for three days to set a new mark for hot tub humor. `` It's great. Surf's up,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said about a half-hour into his marathon Wednesday. He plans to stay there for at least 73 hours, until Saturday morning. He started out with some elephant jokes. `` Why do elephants have flat feet?'' he asked. `` It's obviously because they jump out of trees.'' `` Most of the jokes are off the top of my head and are jokes I've collected from 19 years in the radio business,'' said <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, 36 `` Of course, after 27 hours or so you begin to hallucinate, so fortunately the Guinness people allow me to use cue cards.'' The 1989 edition of the <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION> lists him as the record-holder for time spent telling jokes in a hot tub with a 52-hour effort, but someone in <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> has topped that mark. The effort to regain the title has its risks. `` I've got to keep the temperature of the water between 85 and 90 degrees,'' <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> said. `` Any lower than 85 and hypothermia sets in without me knowing it. I can go numb, nod off. Any higher than 90, and I can boil myself without knowing it.'' Wrinkled feet are another hazard, said <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, who has survived four tub-joking marathons. He plans to solve the problem by keeping his feet out of the water much of the time. <PERSON> Parker </PERSON> has a penchant for spending long periods in odd places. `` I once sat in spaghetti for three days,'' he said. Unfortunately, <ORGANIZATION> Guinness </ORGANIZATION> lists no record for spaghetti-sitting.
