<HEAD>Paris, Texas, Celebrates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Parisians here see oil derricks instead of the Eiffel Tower and favor crape myrtles over crepes, but do n't expect them to call July 14 anything other than Bastille Day When Parisians in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> toast the 200th anniversary of their revolution on Friday, their namesakes here will, too _ Texas-style. The fete will include a barbecue, quilting contests, music, plays and `` Tour de Paris'' bike races expected to draw up to 1,500 entrants to this town of 27,000 people 200 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. City leaders and businesses started the Bastille Day celebrations 10 years ago thinking, `` Why not?'' said <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, program coordinator of the <ORGANIZATION> Paris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>. `` It started out as a downtown merchants' promotion, a sidewalk sale, real small and kind of quaint,'' she said. But as word of the festival grew, `` We just thought we'd take advantage of it.'' <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> have fraternal ties, she said. `` <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> was one of the first to recognize <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> as an independent -LRB- republic -RRB- ... and the French flag was one of the six that flew over <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' Ms. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said. As part of the celebration, about 20 high school girls will compete for the title of Crape Myrtle Queen, with the winner receiving a bouquet from the flowering trees. Hungry revelers can feast on pastries from `` Marie A.'s Cake Company,'' named for <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Antoinette </PERSON>, the haughty monarch known for saying `` Let them eat cake.'' The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> even has a commemorative cancellation mark for July 14 letters. `` It's got a little Eiffel Tower on one side and an oil derrick on the other,'' Ms. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said. `` Our logo, on little pins, is a little Eiffel Tower with a cowboy hat on top. ... They're a real big hit.'' The only thing missing will be a French dignitary, she said. `` But, they've got their own birthday party.''
