<SECOND>Charity Linked to Ex-HUD Official Not Registered to Solicit</SECOND>
<TEXT>
 Contributions
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 FOOD for <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, a pet charity of a former top official at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, has raised thousands of dollars without proper registration in several states, according to records. A check by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> of the offices of state attorneys general and other agencies regulating charities found FOOD is not registered in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> or its home state of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. The organization raised at least $ 580,000 from 1986 to 1988, much of it in those states, and half of that came from individuals or firms known to be involved with <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> programs, according to an internal agency report released in April. `` I was told we did n't have to have a license,'' <PERSON> Vasilios </PERSON> <PERSON> Damavolites </PERSON>, FOOD's treasurer, said in an interview from <LOCATION> Novi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, where the organization is headquartered. <PERSON> Damavolites </PERSON>, who is president of <ORGANIZATION> Dial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Construction </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and goes by the anglicized name of <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Damas </PERSON>, said contributions have been difficult to raise since the release of a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> report that touched on the organization and its links to former agency official <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>. `` We do n't want to operate illegally,'' <PERSON> Damas </PERSON> said. `` We're not going to do anything else until we receive the proper license.'' Despite lacking appropriate state registration, FOOD holds federal tax exempt status from the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, meaning that donations are tax deductible. <PERSON> Damas </PERSON> said information about state licenses is kept by <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Pretorius </PERSON>, who runs FOOD's relief operations from his home in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Pretorius </PERSON> could not be reached for comment. His secretary in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> said Tuesday that <PERSON> Pretorius </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Ann </PERSON>, were attending an evangelical conference in <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. FOOD for <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> was an obscure relief organization delivering food and clothing to war refugees in <LOCATION> Mozambique </LOCATION> until the release of a <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> audit in April. The report probed possible connections between donations to FOOD by real estate developers and contracts awarded under <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>'s Moderate Rehabilitation program. The <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> rehabilitation program, which gave rent subsidies to developers to renovate housing for low-income residents, was suspended after the audit's release because of charges of favoritism in the awarding of contracts. <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> said Tuesday he had instituted new controls and restarted the program. <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>'s links to FOOD date to 1985, when he helped establish the charity. He quit his position as director after he moved to <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> as assistant secretary for housing, according to the report. The report said <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> continued to work for the charity, attending at least eight fund-raisers in the 20 months after he became assistant secretary. A check of <PERSON> Demery </PERSON>'s phone logs, obtained under the Freedom of Information Act, revealed that <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> often spoke to FOOD officials during working hours. After the investigation, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> Inspector General <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> concluded that <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> may have violated the department's standards of conduct, which prohibit employees from directly or indirectly soliciting anything of value from anyone with `` interests that may substantially be affected'' by <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Demery </PERSON> says the conclusions were based on circumstantial evidence, and says he never asked for contributions from any <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> developer. FOOD for <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> at one time held a license to solicit contributions in its home state of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, but allowed it to lapse in September 1987, according to documents obtained from the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> attorney general. A reapplication made this year has been delayed until FOOD can provide notarized signatures of two officers, the documents show. Yet FOOD held two fund-raisers in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> in 1988 and 1989, the organization's treasurer said in a telephone interview this week. FOOD also held at least 10 fundraising events in six other states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> in 1987 and 1988, according to the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> audit. FOOD also filed papers with the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> attorney general in June saying that it had `` pending applications in other states'' for licenses, although <PERSON> Damas </PERSON> said he did not know which states.
