<FIRST>r w PM-Children'sTV     07-13 0591</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Children's TV,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Urged to Toughen Regulations on Kids' TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Television is sending one message to the nation's most impressionable viewers, says a senator _ `` buy, buy, buy.'' Witnesses urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> at a hearing Wednesday to restore restrictions on children's TV programs and join other nations that use television to enlighten rather than exploit the young. They said that since 1984, when the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> weakened time limits on advertising for children's shows, the only messages American kids have been getting from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> broadcasters are sales pitches. The barbs at the broadcast industry came at a hearing by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on communications on two bills that would restore the restrictions and give the federal government new authority over children's fare. `` Instead of inspiring children to learn, broadcasters are pushing them to buy, buy, buy,'' Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, an author of one of the bills, testified. <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> said commercials in children's shows have increased since 1984 and some programs urge young viewers to dial 900 telephone numbers to hear taped messages from cartoon characters. Unsuspecting parents then get hit with huge telephone bills. Dr. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON>, representing the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatrics </ORGANIZATION>, contrasted <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> television with <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, where up to six hours of instructional programming for children is offered each day. `` In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, our commercial networks may offer one hour each week,'' <PERSON> Palumbo </PERSON> said. He did not include figures for public television stations. Sen. <PERSON> Timothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON>, D-Colo., _ who is sponsoring a bill that goes further than <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>'s _ testified that in the wake of the `` deregulation frenzy'' of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years, `` broadcasters seem to have abandoned educational children's programs altogether. He said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> must pressure broadcasters to `` transform children's television from a ` vast wasteland' to a source of intellectual stimulation and enrichment for <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> children.'' <PERSON> Wirth </PERSON>'s bill includes provisions to: _ Impose tougher limits on advertising time in children's TV shows Currently, those limits are 9.5 minutes of commercials per hour on weekends and 12 minutes per hour during weekdays. _ Require TV stations, as part of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> license renewal process, to show they are providing programming `` specifically designed to serve the educational and informational needs of preschool and school-aged children. _ Require broadcasters to give advance public notice of programs designed specifically to educate and inform children The bill by <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> and Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, is identical to a measure that passed <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year, only to be pocket-vetoed by President <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. A similar measure is before the House. The <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> bill would hold commercials on children's shows to 10.5 minutes per hour weekends and 12 minutes weekdays, and require stations to demonstrate to the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> they are serving the educational and information needs of children through their `` overall programming.'' <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>, said his group supported the <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> bill, which he called a `` fair and reasonable compromise.'' He complained that broadcasters are losing young audiences to cable TV and VCRs, while production costs for children's shows are increasing. `` Further restrictions and more stringent programming requirements run the risk of knocking the children's television marketplace even further out of balance,'' <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> told the subcommittee. <PERSON> DeWitt </PERSON> <PERSON> Helm </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertisers </ORGANIZATION>, opposed both bills. He called the restrictions unconstitutional and said they do n't protect children. Helm said there was no evidence children are any more susceptible to five minutes of commercials than to 15 minutes of ads.
