<HEAD>Congress Tackles Spending, Deficit-Cutting Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is speeding up work on an assortment of deficit-cutting and spending bills with the start of the 1990 fiscal year looming closer. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the second of 13 annual appropriations Wednesday, an $ 11 billion measure for the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and cultural programs, on a 374-49 vote. The Senate has yet to approve any appropriations measures, which provide money for federal agencies. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> gave preliminary voice vote approval to a measure raising $ 5.3 billion in new tax receipts, mainly by boosting a series of levies on businesses. The panel rejected 22-11 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s pet tax proposal _ a cut in the capital gains tax that Democrats say benefits only the rich. But a deficit-slashing measure ran into problems in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The legislation would raise $ 50 million by increasing fees the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> charges investors and another $ 300 million by boosting <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> fees imposed on utilities. It would also expand the Medicaid program an estimated $ 5 billion to $ 13 billion over five years. That brought objections from Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dannemeyer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Calif </LOCATION>., who called the measure an example of `` the insidious practice of how we expand the liberal welfare state. Lawmakers returned this week from their Fourth of July recess to eight weeks of work left until the Oct. 1 start of the next fiscal year. They take a four-week break in August. They must keep the federal deficit to the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law's limit of $ 100 billion for 1990, out of a $ 1.17 trillion budget, to prevent automatic, across-the-board cuts. Two House Appropriations subcommittees, meeting behind closed doors, tried to finish spending bills for transportation programs and for labor, health, and education initiatives. Across the Capitol, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> divided programs worth $ 658 billion among its 13 subcommittees, opening the way for those panels to begin writing their own versions of the spending bills. Members of the committee complained that last spring's budget deal between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and congressional leaders would not allow increases for programs that need more money. `` I wish we could do better, but we could only cut the cake so many ways,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> voted 23-0 for a package that claims $ 2.8 billion in savings. Some $ 1.8 billion would come from a bookkeeping move _ shifting the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> `` off-budget'' so its losses do n't count towards federal red ink. Other claimed savings would come by shifting the date on which the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> reimburses the government $ 330 million for workers compensation payments from fiscal 1991 into fiscal 1990. Another $ 700 million in savings would be realized by spreading federal civilian employees retirement payments over two years, instead of in one single check.
