<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressman outraged over artworks depicting explicit sexuality and religious desecration says the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>'s decision to strip $ 45,000 from the federal arts budget is `` a slap on the wrist. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved the cut in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Endowment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> budget after attempts to first take away all the agency's money and then reduce its budget by 10 percent failed. `` I'm afraid the long and the short of it is that they will get a message they can get away with anything and take nothing but a modest slap on the wrist,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Armey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>. The action Wednesday came as an amendment to the $ 11 billion <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> appropriations bill, which was eventually approved by a 374-49 vote. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has not voted on the Interior appropriation. The fight over arts funding, heightened by recent controversial exhibits that had federal money behind them, was debated for five hours before the amendment trimming the <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION>'s budget was approved 361-65. The bill earmarked $ 144.2 million for the endowment, which provides grants to artists, writers and art exhibitors. `` We were concerned about the way the endowment was moving on certain taxpayer-funded projects,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Stenholm </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, who proposed the funding cut. <PERSON> Stenholm </PERSON>'s amendment was an alternative to one offered by Rep. <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Rohrabacher </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Calif </LOCATION>., that would have wiped out the <ORGANIZATION> NEA </ORGANIZATION>'s entire appropriation, and another by <PERS