<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Psychiatric, Bjt,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Team Calls for Safeguards for Soviets Sent to Mental Hospitals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is still hospitalizing citizens who are not mentally ill, says a team of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health experts who recommend additional reforms to prevent confinement of political dissidents. The 26-member delegation's report, released Wednesday, said broad concepts of `` social dangerousness'' have contributed to the Soviet practice of hospitalizing people who are not mentally ill. In response, the Soviet side expressed disagreement with some aspects of the study but nonetheless called it a `` valuable and useful document.'' The delegation visited the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> from Feb. 26 to March 12 to assess recent changes in Soviet psychiatry. They examined 15 patients and 12 former patients who had been released within the preceding two years. Among the 12, `` the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team found no evidence of any past or current mental disorder in nine, and the remaining three had relatively mild symptoms that would not typically warrant involuntary hospitalization,'' said delegation member <PERSON> Darrel </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Regier </PERSON>, director of clinical research at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. The delegation's report said it `` recommends that additional steps be taken to revise the Soviet Criminal Codes to remove all prohibitions against expression of political or religious beliefs.'' In addition, the report said new legislation or regulations appear necessary to limit involuntary hospitalizations solely to those who are a direct danger to themselves or others. The report also recommended increased use of defense lawyers to guard against abuse of patients, and the use of periodic reviews to ensure that hospital stays are not excessively long. According to the report, the Soviet hosts generally complied with the terms of the agreement under which the visit was made although there were some `` significant procedural obstacles'' that made completing the task more difficult. The preliminary Soviet response to the report acknowledged the existence of such obstacles but said the problem `` by no means meant that the Soviet specialists artificially created difficulties and tried to limit access to the necessary information on the patients.'' The Soviet response said efforts are being made to bring Soviet laws into conformity with international standards. In addition, it said, there has been discussion of the creation of an independent commission `` to examine any and all complaints of wrongful acts by employees of the psychiatric service, and for public monitoring of the activity of psychiatric institutions.'' The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> team made the visit against a background of allegations about misuse of psychiatric treatment in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. One report cited 346 cases of alleged psychiatric abuse between 1977 and 1983. The perception that the problem was rampant prompted the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Psychiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> to condemn <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in 1977 for the alleged practices. Faced with expulsion from the group, the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> All-Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Neuropathologists </ORGANIZATION> and Psychiatrists resigned from the WPA in 1983. But the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> delegation acknowledged there has been progress in recent years toward establishing some legal protection for patients subject to forced confinement.
