<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> says its safety record is `` second to none,'' even though its submarines have been involved at least 42 collisions with other vessels since 1983. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Cmdr. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said Wednesday that the number includes 15 incidents with other <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessels and work boats, including minor collisions with the tugboats that help a sub enter a harbor. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> was commenting on a report in the <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Press-Telegram </ORGANIZATION> over the weekend that said <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> documents revealed that the service's submarines have been involved at least 42 collisions with other vessels, including five fishing boats, since 1983. In the most serious incident, the attack submarine USS <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> snagged a towing cable of the commercial tugboat Barcona off <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> last month. The tug was sunk and one member of the three-man crew drowned. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has that case under investigation. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the Barcona fatality `` is the only one that we know of.'' The spokesman said a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> study of collisions involving submarines from 1983 to 1987 found that five collisions had occurred with other submarines, one with a destroyer and one with a rescue salvage ship.
