 A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee has approved a measure by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> to require <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> employers to provide health insurance to all their workers and their workers' dependents. The measure cleared <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on a 9-7 party-line vote Wednesday. But it's strongly opposed by the administration and other powerful groups, including many business organizations. The Kennedy bill is intended to provide coverage for the estimated 37 million Americans not now covered by any public or private health insurance. Although many of the details have been reworked, the bill is similar to one that cleared the committee last year but was not considered in either the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> or House. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> noted that the majority of businesses already insure their workers, `` yet two-thirds of all the Americans who lack basic health insurance protection are workers or members of working families.'' Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, argued against the measure in a letter to <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, saying enactment of his bill `` would result in a significant loss of job opportunities, impair our nation's economic competitiveness, and interfere with the right of employees and employers to determine between themselves the most appropriate compensation package to meet their circumstances.''
