<NOTE>Cable Association Says Baseball Growing on Local TV, Too</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Local television stations, not just cable TV networks, are increasing the number of Major League baseball games they carry, a cable TV group says. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday disputed claims that cable companies are stealing baseball from `` free TV.'' Local broadcast coverage of professional baseball has grown by nearly 40 percent over the past 15 years, from 1,190 games in 1975 to 1,647 games in 1989, the association said. The number of baseball games televised by both local broadcast stations and by regional cable sports networks has increased 7 percent since 1985, the <ORGANIZATION> NCTA </ORGANIZATION> said. `` As a result, cable's baseball coverage has served to supplement, rather than reduce, the number of games aired by local broadcasters,'' the cable association said in a report, `` Availability of Baseball Games on Broadcast and Cable Television.'' It said some broadcasters have contended that baseball on cable has reduced the number of games carried by local television stations.
