<HEAD>Oregon National Guard Called Out to Fight Gangs, Drugs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD GREEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 National Guardsmen have joined police in their battle against violent, drug-dealing gangs from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> that have wreaked havoc on <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>'s north side. Mayor <PERSON> Bud </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> and state officials said Wednesday the first of 36 <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardsmen </ORGANIZATION> reported to work late last week with the <ORGANIZATION> Portland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION>. The rest will join the ranks by the end of this week and eight others will be on call, said the guard's director, Gen. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Rees </PERSON>. The guardsmen will fill support roles, acting as <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> interpreters, taking telephone tips and doing paperwork. That will enable police to deploy more officers on the streets. <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> is beset by gang violence, with five killings blamed on drive-by gang shootings since August. There have been about four dozen gang-related shootings this year, including one Tuesday night that seriously wounded a 13-year-old boy. `` It's clearly a problem,'' said <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kantor </PERSON>, Governor <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldschmidt </PERSON>'s spokesman. `` It's not as big as <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' gang problem, but it is very serious for us and one we do n't intend to tolerate.'' Officials have not decided how long the guardsmen will remain in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, but the effort has federal financing through October. `` It's just one more increment, one more step,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, the governor's anti-crime coordinator, said at a news conference. `` The gang problem is bigger than this; the narcotics problem is bigger than this.'' Drive-by gang shootings were unheard of in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> until last summer, when the rival drug-dealing Crips and Bloods gangs began expanding from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> and other cities. Turf battles ensued and the region's first fatal drive-by gang shooting occurred last Aug. 17. `` We're not going to walk away from this saying 36 or 40 troops is enough until we have gotten rid of the drug problem in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and specifically in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> Deputy Chief <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Noelle </PERSON> said the guardsmen will free up more officers for street deployments. `` In terms of looking at raw numbers, it's not a big deal,'' <PERSON> Noelle </PERSON> said, but in terms of support work, `` it's a real asset.'' The state received $ 474,000 from the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> to use the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to fight crime. About half that money will be used to pay troops in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> through Sept. 30, <PERSON> Rees </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> specifically said the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> could be used only for support when it passed an act giving states $ 300 million for anti-drug efforts, <PERSON> Rees </PERSON> said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> is not supposed to be in the arrest or seizure business,'' he said.
