<HEAD>Questions Raised About Authenticity of Warhol's Superman Collages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The authenticity of 19 Superman collages by <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> has been called into question by two comic book experts who say the Superman cut-outs did n't appear in print until years after the date on the artworks. `` Either they were misdated or somebody has made some work that is not what it purports to be,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> art dealer who owns 18 of the collages. The discrepancy was detected by comic book experts <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheinaus </PERSON> during independent visits to a Warhol retrospective at the Museum of Modern Art in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which ran from Feb. 6 to May 2. <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Monday he was looking in the exhibition catalog at an untitled Superman collage, dated 1960-61, when he recognized the inking style of the artist who did the cartoon panel. `` I remembered that <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Abel </PERSON> did not start inking <PERSON> Superman </PERSON> until the late 1960s, maybe 1969. And I thought ` Hold it, something is wrong here!''' `` When I met Sheinaus a month later, he said, ` Did you notice anything funny about the <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> exhibition?''' <PERSON> Schumer </PERSON> said. `` I looked him right in the eye and said ` One has got to be a fraud.' `` He said, ` You wo n't believe this but there are about 15 of them.''' The series of 19 collages has been estimated to be worth about $ 5 million. Each piece was signed twice and dated 1960-61. The <ORGANIZATION> DC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Comics </ORGANIZATION> they came from _ like `` Superman's Greatest Blunder'' -LRB- 1968 -RRB- and `` <PERSON> Muto </PERSON> vs. the Man of Tomorrow'' -LRB- 1966 -RRB- _ sold for 12 cents each. Seven of the collages _ cut-outs from original comic books that were pasted on paper and splattered with red or blue paint _ were on display during the <ORGANIZATION> MOMA </ORGANIZATION> retrospective; six were loaned by <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, one by an unidentified private collector, said <PERSON> Jeanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, a museum spokeswoman. In a statement, the museum said, `` Works of art are selected for exhibitions based on careful research and on the best information available at the time. `` In any retrospective of an artist there may be questions regarding dating; however, we have no reason whatsoever to doubt the authenticity of any of the works included in the <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> retrospective,'' it said. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, a lawyer for the <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> estate, said that the discrepancy in dating was being investigated but that a preliminary examination indicated the collages were authentic. However, <PERSON> Vincent </PERSON> <PERSON> Fremont </PERSON>, a director of the estate, told the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION>, which reported on the mismatch in dates on Monday, that he did n't recall seeing the collages during the'60s and'70s. `` I've worked with <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> since I was 18, and you did n't see them being bought and sold,'' he said. `` You see what I am saying?'' <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Malanga </PERSON>, who in 1963 became <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s first studio assistant, said he saw the collages for the first time at the exhibition. `` I was fascinated because I knew almost everything <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> was doing at that time, and I thought ` Why did n't I know about these things?''' He said that later when he learned about the discrepancy in dates, he doubted that the works were <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s. `` Those pieces require someone to sit down at a kitchen table with scissors and glue,'' he said. `` <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> would not have taken the time to do something like that.'' He also noted that during 1961-62, <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON>'s comic book images were paintings not collages. <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> quit using comic book images after about 1962, when he learned <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lichtenstein </PERSON> was also using them. <PERSON> Malanga </PERSON> also noted that <PERSON> Warhol </PERSON> often had his assistants sign his works for him.
