<HEAD>Child Kills Sister Hours After Florida Gun Bill Signed Into Law</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TD2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An infant was killed with a gun her 6-year-old sister found under their parents' pillow hours after Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> signed a bill intended to protect children from accidental shootings. Ten-month-old <PERSON> Enercida </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> was shot late late Wednesday and died early today at <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Joseph </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, police said. She was the seventh victim of such an accident since June 1. `` The 6-year-old found the .38 - caliber revolver laying on their parents' bed under a pillow ... and thinking it was a toy, and fired it one time, striking the girl in the head,'' said <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> police officer <PERSON> S. </PERSON> Possible charges are pending against the girls' parents, <PERSON> Amancio </PERSON> and <PERSON> Reina </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, and police are continuing to investigate the shooting, <PERSON> Middleton </PERSON> said. But the law <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> signed Wednesday does n't take effect until October 1 and wo n't apply in this case, he said. The law requires gun owners to take reasonable precautions to keep loaded weapons in their homes and businesses out of the hands of children age 15 and younger by using trigger locks or keeping the weapon in a locked box. `` This will assist in protecting our children throughout the state,'' <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said. `` The added public awareness will prompt adults to keep guns out of reach.'' Wednesday's signing ceremony also came one day after a 9-year-old <LOCATION> Clearwater </LOCATION> boy shot himself in the finger. <PERSON> Tomy </PERSON> <PERSON> Zemko </PERSON> found the .25 - caliber pistol after climbing onto a chair to get some potato chips from atop the refrigerator in his grandmother's He was treated for a broken finger. Three children died and two were wounded in the earlier shootings, inspiring lawmakers to push for the first-of-its kind legislation during a special session last month. The law provides for adult gun owners to be charged with a felony, punishable by up to five years in prison and a $ 5,000 fine, if a child shoots himself or another child because of the owner's carelessness If a minor threatens someone with the gun or displays it in public, its owner faces a misdemeanor charge and up to 60 days in jail with a $ 500 fine. No grieving parent of an injured or fatally wounded child shot by another member of the family could be arrested until seven days after the shooting. There are exemptions for hunting and target-shooting accidents and those involving guns taken illegally. The measure also will authorize the development of a gun safety program in the state's public schools. The Unified Sportsmen of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, the state affiliate of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rifle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, helped lawmakers write legislation it could support after a stronger version it opposed was rejected during the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s regular 60-day session, which ended June 3. The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law may inspire similar legislation in other states, said <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>, state legislative director for Washington-based <ORGANIZATION> Handgun </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Lawmakers from states including <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> have contacted <PERSON> Horn </PERSON>'s organization about the law, he said.
</TEXT>
