<SECOND>PM-Harp Movers,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Men Span the Globe to Move Harps, Keep Performers Loose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Anyone can move a harp, but few can do it with the charm and wit of <PERSON> Hans </PERSON> <PERSON> Verbugt </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bruls </PERSON>. Organizers of the <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Competition </ORGANIZATION> realized this when they invited the `` Dutch boys'' to move harps here during the 10-day competition. `` They're just really fun to have around,'' said <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Hainen </PERSON>, one of four finalists. `` They're good for everyone's spirits. The two have been known to dance all night and move harps all day without losing their charm. They take seriously the task of entertaining contestants who have been eliminated. Their responsibilities, however, are not all fun and games. Carrying the harp with its 47 strings and 2,000 moving pieces is serious business. Elaborate charts are required to get the right harp in the right place at the right moment. `` Contestants are very nervous normally,'' <PERSON> Bruls </PERSON> said. `` To break a harp is one thing. If you put it down with a bump, then they start saying, ` Oh no, the tuning is gone.' Before you break it, you can really screw up the tuning.'' The men also shuffle two piano benches and several special harp chairs for contestants. `` They want their own chairs,'' <PERSON> Verbugt </PERSON> said. `` It has to be in a particular position, with this side facing out or that one. Everything has to be that way, otherwise they can not get into their proper mood.'' `` They take the load off our shoulders,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, president and executive director of the competition. `` We'd have to hire somebody who'd have to be trained how to handle harps.'' During this competition at <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Bruls </PERSON> and <PERSON> Verbugt </PERSON> have moved harps from practice rooms to the stage for 37 competitors. They also have stood on their heads to evoke smiles and held a harpist tightly when a painful finger forced her to quit the competition. Verbugt, a musicologist, and <PERSON> Bruls </PERSON>, a physicist, are the last to see a harpist before she goes onstage and the first to congratulate or console her after the performance. `` Some need a shoulder to cry on. Some need someone to laugh with,'' <PERSON> Bruls </PERSON> said. `` This stupid carrying, anyone can do it. The atmosphere you have to create, that makes it interesting to us.'' The men came upon their hobby by accident. <PERSON> Bruls </PERSON>' former girlfriend in <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION> was a harpist, and he was enlisted to help move instruments at the first <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> there in 1983. That led to an invitation to the second congress in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1985 and the third in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> in 1987. `` It's a very nice way to see the world,'' <PERSON> Bruls </PERSON> said. The two say they've noticed that it also is a nice way to meet beautiful women. Ninety-nine percent of the world's top harpists are women. `` They need special attention,'' <PERSON> Verbugt </PERSON> said with a knowing smile. Verbugt comes to harp competitions to research a book he is writing on Dutch harpist <PERSON> Phia </PERSON> <PERSON> Berghout </PERSON>. Bruls uses them to escape the stress of physics and enjoy the heavenly sounds. `` I really like the music,'' he said. `` It's the best music there is.'' In addition to Ms. <PERSON> Hainen </PERSON>, 22, of <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, the other finalists are <PERSON> Kirsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Agresta </PERSON>, 18, of <LOCATION> Bloomfield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Maria </PERSON> <PERSON> Casale </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Marie-Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavaroche </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. All four will perform solo and with orchestra Friday night in the last stage of competition. The first-place winner will receive a <LOCATION> Lyon </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> concert harp worth more than $ 17,000 and a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> debut recital March 13 at <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
