<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranians beating their heads and chests in grief flocked to <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s gold-domed tomb today to mark the end of 40 days of mourning for the founder of the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION>. The official media, including <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, said millions of people braved scorching heat and turned out for the ceremony at the Baheshte Zahra cemetery. <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> said 20,000 people `` suffered heart problems,'' were injured, or simply collapsed as temperatures soared to 104. Some were reported in serious condition even after treatment at makeshift medical facilities set up along roads leading to the cemetery, said the agency, monitored in <LOCATION> Nicosia </LOCATION>. The crowds began gathering at the cemetery at 5 a.m., more than 13 hours before a religious ceremony at the grave. Broadcasting live from the graveyard 10 miles south of the capital, <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> showed mourners being carried over the crowds, apparently after fainting. Firefighters sprayed the crowd with water. Mourners beat their heads and chests in a traditional Shiite Moslem expression of grief, stopping occasionally to wipe sweat away with handkerchiefs or the sleeves of their shirts. Loudspeakers along the roads and at the cemetery blared recitings from the Koran, Islam's holy book. Relief facilities included a central clinic with 1,000 physicians, nurses and relief workers on duty round the clock. Fifty makeshift medical centers and four rest houses also were set up to offer services to motorists and pedestrians, <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> said. It said dozens of stands offering food and refreshments dotted highways and streets connecting <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> with other cities and provinces. The government provided about 600 vehicles to ferry mourners to the cemetery, but many ended up walking as human waves blocked the streets. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> died June 3 at age 86. At least eight people were killed and thousands collapsed from exhaustion in the mayhem of his funeral June 6 when millions packed <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION>'s streets. A government insurance program covered all those who gathered at the tomb today, the end of the period of mourning in the Shiite Moslem faith. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s state-run insurance companies announced that $ 13,500 will be paid to the family of anyone who dies or is seriously injured during the ceremony today. Medical expenses of up to $ 2,000 will also be paid. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, who toppled 2,500 years of monarchy, was buried in a dusty plot alongside thousands of followers killed in the 1979 revolution and thousands who died later in the war with <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The grave has become a shrine, with hundreds of thousands of Iranians gathering around it each day.
