<HEAD>Indiana High Court Rules Teen-age Murderer Cannot Be Executed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with attorney's reaction, move
up reference to pope's appeal, CORRECTS that he made appeal in 1987, sted
1988; Picks up 10th graf, `Orr and ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG RICHARDSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, convicted of a murder committed when she was 15, can not be executed, the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled today. The court unanimously upheld <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>'s conviction in the 1985 stabbing death of an elderly Bible teacher but said she should be sentenced to 60 years in prison. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>'s case has drawn international attention, and in 1987 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> appealed for mercy on her behalf. The court based its decision on a 1987 change in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> law raising the minimum age for a death penalty defendant from 10 to 16 and on a 1988 <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision barring executions of juveniles under 16 at the time of the crime. But the court said although the law was compelling, `` this is a difficult conclusion to reach because of the gruesome nature of <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>'s acts.'' `` We won! I'm elated, relieved,'' said <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Touchette </PERSON>. `` I'm very happy for <PERSON> Paula </PERSON>. I'm just so relieved that this is over. It was not an easy case.'' <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> pleaded guilty to the stabbing death of <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelke </PERSON>, 78, a retired Bible teacher in <PERSON> Gary </PERSON>. According to court records, <PERSON> Pelke </PERSON> was stabbed 33 times after <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> and three friends broke into her home to get money and jewelry. The three other young women received prison terms ranging from 25 to 60 years for their roles in the crime. <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, now 18, is an inmate at the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> Women's Prison in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>. Roman Catholics and some European leftist groups have adopted <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> as the figurehead of their campaign against capital punishment. <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> have also pleaded on her behalf. In March an Italian group presented a petition with 1 million signatures to <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> officials urging clemency for <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON>, and in 1987 the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> wrote to then-Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> to ask for mercy for the young woman. <PERSON> Orr </PERSON> and current Gov. <PERSON> Evan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> have said they did n't want to intervene in the <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> case until the appeal was resolved. In today's opinion, the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> concluded that executing <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> would be unfair because she would be the only person under 16 ever executed in the state. The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, after much debate in 1987, changed the minimum age for a death penalty defendant but made it clear that <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> was n't to be affected by the change. But the court said exempting <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> from the change is inappropriate. `` Now that <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> law establishes 16 as the minimum age for the imposition of the death penalty, <PERSON> Paula </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooper </PERSON> would be both the first and last person ever to be executed in <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> for a crime committed at the age of 15,'' Chief Justice <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sh