<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABOARD AIR FORCE ONE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today dismissed reports that Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is unable to meet a <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> target date for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to reduce its conventional military forces. `` The idea that some Soviet spokesman yesterday said they ca n't meet these timetables _ I do n't want to believe that that's Mr. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> speaking,'' the president said in an impromptu news conference as <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> One flew to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> from a two-night stop in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, the second leg of a 10-day trip Lt. Gen. <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Starodubov </PERSON>, chief of the disarmament branch of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s policy-making central committee, said Tuesday that <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> would not be able to meet the timetable. The Soviet official said that although <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, like the Western nations, is seeking an early agreement, `` there are realities which can not be suppressed.'' `` Experience shows that even when the principal elements are resolved, we need a considerably longer period for solving the details of the document,'' <PERSON> Starodubov </PERSON> said. In <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> today, <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerasimov </PERSON> provided a more tempered response, saying his country welcomed a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort to speed up negotiations to reduce conventional forces and indicated that a deal might be possible within six months. `` We have no intention of delaying this important matter of reducing the level of mi