<HEAD>Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Urges Bill to Outlaw Flag Burning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> today urged a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel to pass quickly his bill to outlaw flag burning, but other lawmakers said nothing short of a constitutional amendment would suffice. Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., said regular legislation was the best way `` swiftly and simply'' to overcome the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling last month that protected flag burning as a form of free speech `` No matter how we cut it, a constitutional amendment is going to take some time'' and leave a gap in the law during which flag burning would remain legal, <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said. A bill could take effect almost immediately, and if it still did n't meet constitutional muster, then an amendment could be pursued, he said. `` Let's heal the wound, pass the legislation and move on,'' urged <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>. <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>'s testimony came as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on constitutional law opened a series of hearings on what to do about the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling. House Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., testified in favor of the constitutional amendment supported by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` We believe there is no quick legislative fix on this issue,'' said <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, who was joined by Rep. <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON>, D-Miss., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, said he opposed a constitutional amendment on flag burning, although he conceded most people disagreed with him. `` It is that very freedom, the right to protest even when it is offensive, that makes us different from the rest of the world,'' he said, comparing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> with the current repression against protesters in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Legislative efforts short of an amendment might be impossible, he said. `` I'm not certain it is possible to draft a constitutionally solid statute,'' he said. Subcommittee chairman <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, D-Calif., urged his colleagues to be cautious `` The flag is sturdy, flying proudly through every fierce battle of every war and through times of social upheaval,'' he said. `` The Constitution, however, is fragile and can be amended by the votes of legislators caught up in the emotional whirlwinds of the moment.'' Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Sensenbrenner </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, the ranking Republican on the subcommittee, said he believed the constitutional amendment should be quickly passed and sent to the states for ratification because of the uncertainty that a statute would hold. `` If we want to heal the wounds'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision, `` we ought to make sure the patient does n't have a relapse,'' he said.
