<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The health gap between white and non-white Americans is widening, and closing the disparity will be tough, Secretary of <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> today. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, the third member of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration to address the civil rights group's national convention, spoke a day after Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. House and Urban Development Secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> spoke on Monday. `` There is a large, and growing disparity in the health of our minority population and the white population,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said. He said the average life expectancy was up to 74.8 years in 1986. `` But the shocking news is that, for the second year in a row, the life expectancy for black Americans declined _ falling to 69.4 years, having been 69.5 in 1985 and 69.7 years in 1984,'' he said. Those figures, and the infant-mortality rate that is twice that of whites, are `` a national tragedy,'' said <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, who is black. <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration favored a plan to make Medicaid more available to infants and pregnant women and increase funding for demonstration projects on maternity care. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told delegates that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was committed to civil rights and black economic progress. Some listeners were n't impressed. `` His speech lacked any real substance,'' said <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, president of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> branch of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People. `` This administration vetoed a minimum wage bill and there is nothing kinder and gentler about that.'' The convention closes tonight with a speech by the Rev. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. In his speech to nearly 3,000 delegates Wednesday, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> did not address one of the hotter convention topics _ recent <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions that have been interpreted as setbacks for civil rights. The high court struck down contract guarantees for minority firms and made it tougher to prove bias in the workplace, while making it easier for white males to contest affirmative action. When pressed on the issue later at a news conference, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, `` The president does not feel that those decisions need to be overturned to advance the cause of civil rights.'' He said the president might reconsider if the impact of the rulings proves discriminatory. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was asked if the president planned to respond to the decisions affecting civil rights with a constitutional amendment like the one he proposed to counter a ruling that upheld constitutional protection for burning the American flag. `` He feels very strongly about civil rights, he's talking about civil rights, he's talking about decency,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. Earlier, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told delegates: `` I am committed and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is committed to fostering good and better relations with the civil rights community.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has met with civil rights leaders in the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and held ceremonies honoring the Rev. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s legacy and observing the 25th anniversary of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. He cited equal opportunity programs including the Job Training Partnership Act that he co-wrote as a senator, and educational initiatives including establishment of a $ 60 million fund during the next four years to build endowments of historically <PERSON> black </PERSON> colleges and universities. `` We are the ones who are going to give a person a job,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. On the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s decision giving states more power to regulate abortions, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he and the president wo n't take part in state-level debates on the issue. But, he added, `` both of our positions are pro-life.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> also said the administration stands behind its February nomination of former <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Executive <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> to head the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s civil rights division. Groups including the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> have opposed the black Republican. <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION> Executive Director <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hooks </PERSON> said Sunday that <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON> lacks the necessary legal knowledge. `` We know of the opposition of the <ORGANIZATION> NAACP </ORGANIZATION>, and we have talked to them about that, but we stand foursquare behind <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucas </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told reporters.
