<HEAD>Bovine Rampage Injures 50</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of cows rampaged through the capital's crowded markets, injuring about 50 people waiting to buy the animals for an Islamic celebration, officials said Thursday. Thousands of cows and goats were on sale in 20 bazaars for sacrifice during Friday's Eid Al-Adha festival. Animal slaughter during Eid is a traditional symbol of sacrifice. On Wednesday, police said, several hundred cows in the central Fulbaria bazaar and <PERSON> Gabtali </PERSON> market on the northeastern outskirts panicked because of noisy crowds. Eight people were admitted to the <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> with head injuries, doctors said. The rest were treated and released. Eid al-Adha is the second-biggest Islamic holiday, observed 40 days after <PERSON> Ramadan </PERSON>, the month of fasting. About 90 percent of <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION>'s 110 million people are Moslems.
