<SECOND>PM-Hajj,0697</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moslems End Pilgrimage to Mecca</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 More than a million Moslems today descended <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arafat </ORGANIZATION> and crossed a scorching plain to the holy city of <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> for prayers culminating their annual pilgrimage. This year's pilgrimage, or hajj, to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> was conducted under the guard of anti-terrorist security squads. The worshipers filed past the road in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> where two bombs exploded Monday, killing one person and injuring 16. Waves of men in white seamless robes _ signifiying equality in the eyes of <LOCATION> Allah </LOCATION> _ and women in long dresses and head scarves participated in the prayer, broadcast live via satellite to scores of countries. About 1.8 million Moslems came from more than 80 countries for the hajj, which every financially able Moslem is expected to make at least once. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> boycotted this year's hajj to protest restrictions on the number of pilgrims. Each nation was given a quota of 1,000 pilgrims per million people. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> alleged the restrictions were intended to limit the number of Iranian pilgrims. It also accused Saudi authorities of fabricating Monday's bomb incident to discredit <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The Saudis have not accused <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> of planting the bombs. At twilight, the pilgrims offered the Eid Al-Adha, or Feast of Sacrifice, prayers before slaughtering hundreds of thousands of sheep, cows and camels. They then streamed down <PERSON> Mount </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> to the <PERSON> Mina </PERSON> plain and on to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> for the farewell prayer before dispersing. <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mina </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> are all about four miles apart. Some pilgrims walked from <PERSON> Mina </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, but most took advantage of air-conditioned buses provided by the Saudis. In traditional messages, <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s King Fahd and his crown prince, <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON>, made no mention of the bombings. The king said it was a `` sacred duty'' for him as `` custodian of Islam's holiest shrines'' to complete renovation and modernization plans at <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> to provide pilgrims with better conditions for future pilgrimages. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> cited the construction under way as the main reason for curtailing the number of pilgrims. Limits on pilgrims first were imposed in 1988. The previous year, demonstrations by thousands of the 150,000-strong Iranian hajj contingent led to clashes with Saudi police. At least 402 people died, most of them Iranians. Scores of Iranians were arrested during the 1986 hajj when they tried to bring in explosives. Princes and dignitaries from <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, merchants and paupers from <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, Cossack and Tartars from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, mingled with other pilgrims from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION> _ all chanting in union `` Allah <PERSON> Akbar </PERSON> <PERSON> Kabeera </PERSON>, <PERSON> Walhumdillah </PERSON> <PERSON> Katheera </PERSON>,'' Arabic for `` God is so great and to Him we pay high tribute.'' The hajj is performed during the Islamic lunar months of <LOCATION> Shawwal </LOCATION>, Zul-Quideh and <PERSON> Zul-Hijjeh </PERSON>. Similar rituals performed out of the season are called `` Umrah,'' or lesser hajj. The hajj proper is limited to six days. A pilgrim may commence the rituals at any time during the three months, but the actual congregational rites were conducted this year between July 8 and July 13. Hajis are required to pray at the Grand Mosque in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> and circle its <LOCATION> Kaaba </LOCATION>, a granite cube draped with gold-embroidered black brocade. Moslems honor the <LOCATION> Kaaba </LOCATION> as the house of <PERSON> Allah </PERSON>. As they circle the cube, pilgrims often bend to kiss the sacred black stoe set in silver on the east corner of the granite structure. The pilgrims also run back and forth seven times between <LOCATION> Safa </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Marwa </PERSON>, two hills 800 yards apart, enclosed within a huge mosque. They commemorate the agony of <PERSON> Hagar </PERSON>, <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON>'s estranged wife, who ran frantically in the same spot searching for water for her son <PERSON> Ismail </PERSON>, until <PERSON> Allah </PERSON> guided her to a spring. The spring today feeds the sacred well of <PERSON> Zamzam </PERSON> in the heart of the Grand Mosque. When they go to <PERSON> Mina </PERSON>, each pilgrim throws seven stones at each of the three `` devil pillars,'' a spot where Moslems believed the devil tried to tempt <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> to disobey <PERSON> Allah </PERSON> and refuse to sacrifice his son.
</TEXT>
