<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> voted today to investigate a former minister accused of responsibility for a major agricultural scandal that defrauded the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nikos </PERSON> <PERSON> Athanasopoulos </PERSON>, deputy finance minister in the former Socialist government, is accused of arranging for a shipment of 9,000 tons of <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> corn to be issued with Greek certificates of origin in 1986 and sold to a member state of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> by a Greek state company. The European Court ruled against <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> in May this year, citing lost revenues of $ 2 million which should have been paid on corn imported from a non-member country. Sentencing is expected later this year. Legislators from the conservative <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> party claimed in Parliament that <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> will be made to pay at least $ 3.6 million in reparations. Legislators from the governing alliance of the New Democracy and the <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Left </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Progress </ORGANIZATION> carried the motion to investigate <PERSON> Athanasopoulos </PERSON> with 168 votes in the 300-member Parliament. The <ORGANIZATION> Panhellenic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, which was swept from office amid a series of scandals in June 18 elections, abstained from the vote. <PERSON> Athanasopoulos </PERSON>, who was not re-elected, submitted a memorandum denying involvement in the scandal. `` We have to note our international disgrace and the irreparable ethical damage done to our country in the eyes of our community partners,'' said one legislator. `` Where did the money go?'' New Democracy party leader <PERSON> Constantine </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitsotakis </PERSON> asked <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> about the money from the duties that were not paid. Under the law governing the culpability of Cabinet ministers, a special committee of 12 legislators will investigate the charges against <PERSON> Athanasopoulos </PERSON> and decide whether the former minister should stand trial. The coalition government has pledged to investigate and punish those involved in scandals in banking, the arms industry and alleged phone-tapping by the former socialist administration.
