<HEAD>Dukakis Outlines $491 Milion in Budget Cuts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Seeking to shock legislators into supporting a tax increase, Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> today outlined $ 491 million in cuts in the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> state budget. `` I'm today doing the worst thing I ever had to do in my political career,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said at a noon news conference, at which he blamed himself and the Legislature for the state's fiscal mess. The package of impounded funds and vetoes cuts into a $ 12.3 billion state budget for the fiscal year that began July 1. The cuts include a freezing of welfare benefits at current levels, cuts of $ 16 million in environmental affairs and $ 17 million judiciary and district attorney accounts and a reduction in state scholarship funds. The welfare move means that the state's poor receiving general relief will get no cost-of-living increase. `` All of us in state government have arrived at this unhappy moment through a combination of miscalculations, mistakes and misinformation,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` I'm disappointed in myself. I'm disappointed in the legislature I'm disappointed in all of us who have let the talkmasters and the columnists define our values, our commitment to public service, our commitment to each other.'' The <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> plan includes an across-the-board reduction in administrative costs by 10 percent. `` The first 250 million hits the bone and will cause real pain,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` The balance hits raw nerve and will be devastating to people, to families and to communities. I'm doing what I'm doing today because I have to do it to avoid fiscal chaos. I ca n't let the state go down the drain financially and I wo n't.'' Key pieces of the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> package of state spending reductions include: _ Total cuts in public education and higher education of $ 62 million _ A cut in the state human services budget of $ 97 million _ Reduction in the state AIDS program of $ 2 million _ A cut in Aid to Families with Dependent Children of $ 22 million _ $ 8 million from the state mental health budget. The Legislature has already given initial approval to a tax increase to balance the previous year's budget. Now the issue of a tax increase for this year looms. Using the line-item veto and his power to impound funds, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he also plans to eliminate the office of <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Knapp </PERSON> and cut two-thirds of the 2,100 additional state employees planned for in the budget, leaving prison guards as one of the few categories to be increased.
