<HEAD>NATO Proposes Arms, Aircraft Reduction Package</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 13 grafs to UPDATE with proposal submitted, comments
from NATO and Warsaw Pact spokesman. Pickup 11th graf pvs, `At a...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> today presented the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact with new proposals on reducing conventional arms and aircraft in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, two months ahead of schedule in a bid to accelerate a disarmament agreement. The early presentation provided `` further evidence of ... our desire to achieve early results,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Edes </PERSON>, the head of the <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> delegation speaking on behalf of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference. Presenting the proposal today instead of in September, as originally planned, gives the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact time to frame a response during an eight-week recess in the talks. Negotiations broke today and resume Sept. 7. Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> outlined details of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> proposal Wednesday. He said <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> was recommending a ceiling of 5,700 combat aircraft and 1,900 combat helicopters for each alliance. The inclusion of an aircraft cutback complied with a long-standing East bloc demand. According to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> data, the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact countries have about 9,600 combat aircraft versus about 6,700 <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> aircraft. The Western proposal is based on a blueprint for deep reductions in conventional arms and troops in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> first unveiled by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at an alliance summit in May and subsequently endorsed by <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> members. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called for military cutbacks that would fix the same ceiling of 275,000 troops in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for each superpower. According to <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> statistics, that would require the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to remove 30,000 troops from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> while the Soviets would have to pull out more than 10 times that, or 325,000. The proposal also foresees deep cuts in armaments, with a proposed ceiling of 20,000 tanks for each side and reductions in combat aircraft and artillery. The decision to make the proposal was reached by a panel of senior <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION> on Friday, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION> said. It complied with <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc appeals that the presentation be speeded up. The head of the Soviet delegation, <PERSON> Oleg </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grinevsky </PERSON>, welcomed the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> proposal but said he was `` sorry'' it did not go further. `` At first glance the proposal tabled by <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> today has no new elements,'' <PERSON> Grinevsky </PERSON>, said in a news conference. `` Rather it is a more detailed elaboration of the positions that were stated in <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, and only in respect of aviation and helicopters at that,'' <PERSON> Grinevsky </PERSON> said. At a meeting in <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, last weekend, leaders of the Soviet-led <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> praised <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> proposal and said an initial accord on reductions could be reached as early as next year. However, the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc summit did not produce any new concrete proposals on arms control of its own. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal called for reaching agreement in six months to a year, and for reductions to be carried out by 1992 or 1993. In a statement issued at the end of the two-day <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> summit, the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pact </ORGANIZATION> said, `` The situation of the negotiations is such that the first understandings may be achieved already in 1990.'' Last week, the head of the Polish delegation to the <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> talks called on <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> to submit the proposal before the recess rather than waiting until the third round of talks opens in the fall. The Soviet military bloc has a proposal on the table to reduce six kinds of weapons 10 percent to 15 percent below present levels by 1994, then add a further 25 percent reduction by 1997 before moving to purely defensive forces in the year 2000. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has also begun unilateral troop withdrawals from <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> that are to reduce the number of Soviet troops in the region by 50,000 by 1990.
