<HEAD>Longest-Serving Governor Won't Seek Fifth Term</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf with 2 grafs with Thompson saying he might seek
another office, new quote; Picks up 5th graf pvs, `The 53-year-old...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Illinois Gov. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, the longest-serving incumbent governor in the nation, announced today he would not seek a fifth term in 1990. Near tears and with his voice wavering at times, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> told reporters that his decision was based on family and career reasons. `` My wife and daughter said they would support another term, but I was n't ready for that,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` My family and their happiness and security is the most important thing to me at this time.'' He added that he would `` enjoy the challenge of the private sector.'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> also said he might seek another government office. `` That's entirely possible,'' he said. `` I do not intend to retire from politics _ only from this office.'' The 53-year-old <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, a moderate Republican who has served 12 years, was mentioned as a possible presidential candidate early in his career and as a vice-presidential candidate last year. More recently, speculation has centered on whether <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> would leave state government to accept a federal appointment or a partnership in a <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> law firm. The speculation became increasingly intense over the past few months, particularly within the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>. Both Secretary of State <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> and Lt. Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON> are interested in running for governor, but both have said they would not challenge <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. Democratic gubernatorial hopefuls have also awaited <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s move as a guide to their own strategies <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> first burst into the national spotlight during his four-year tenure as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> from 1971-75, when he sent several prominent allies of the late Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Daley </PERSON> to prison on corruption charges. Passing up an offer to run against <PERSON> Daley </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> instead claimed the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> gubernatorial nomination in 1976 and defeated a Daley-backed Democrat, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Howlett </PERSON>, by 1.39 million votes _ the widest margin in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> history. His first term lasted only two years because <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> was in the process of switching its gubernatorial elections to non-presidential election years. He was re-elected to a four-year term by another record margin in 1978 and then twice turned back challenges by Democrat <PERSON> Adlai </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevenson </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> _ in 1982 by the narrowest margin in state history, and again in 1986 to become the state's only four-term governor. Though titular leader of the state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> and a key backer of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> has frequently been at odds with his fellow Republicans on fiscal and social issues. His political reputation is one of a pragmatic, non-ideological bridge-builder, evidenced by his support among traditionally Democratic groups such as organized labor and his warm relations with some conservative <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> Democrats. <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s most successful year in office may have been 1985, when he played a key role in passage of landmark school reform legislation, won approval of a massive infrastructure renewal program and landed the much sought-after Diamond-Star auto assembly plant. Those promising achievements gave way to frustration in his fourth term as his efforts to gain approval of a state income tax increase were blocked by <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON>. Earlier this month, he wound up signing a two-year tax increase drafted by <PERSON> Madigan </PERSON> and approved with mostly Democratic votes over the objections of <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s fellow Republicans. That set the stage for a potentially bruising battle over renewal of the tax in the months following the 1990 election.
