<HEAD>Norway Wants Treaty With Soviets on Military Accidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> will propose a bilateral agreement with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> covering warnings on military accidents, a report said Thursday. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> began drafting the treaty two years ago and made it a high priority after a recent Soviet navy accidents off northern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, according to the newspaper <PERSON> Klassekampen </PERSON>. `` <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> is ready to enter an agreement with the Soviets about warnings on military incidents,'' acting <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Oeyvind </PERSON> <PERSON> Nordsletten </PERSON> told the newspaper. He did not say when the pact would be presented. <LOCATION> Oslo </LOCATION> complained of Soviet slowness in providing warnings and details of accidents aboard two <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear submarines near <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> territory. On April 7, a Soviet submarine sank in the <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. On June 26, another Soviet sub suffered a reactor breakdown off northern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nordsletten </PERSON> said the draft treaty is similar to those the Soviets recently signed with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The treaty also would require warning when ships or aircraft from the countries approach each other, he said. There is heavy air and sea traffic off northern <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> from Soviet miltary bases on the <LOCATION> Kola </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, just across the Norwegian-Soviet border. `` One example of an incident that might have been covered was when a Norwegian <ORGANIZATION> Orion </ORGANIZATION> surveillance plane was damaged by a Soviet fighter that flew too close over the <LOCATION> Barents </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> in 1987,'' he said. Last fall, the two nations agreed to inform each other of civilian nuclear accidents, such as the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear power plant disaster in 1986.
