<HEAD>Group Says US Lacks Comprehensive Controls on Toxic Runoff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation needs a comprehensive plan for controlling poison runoff into waterways from city streets, farms, mines and other sources, an environmental group said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said some state and local governments have taken effective measures to reduce the pollution, but the problem is growing worse in many areas because of inadequate national standards. `` Poison runoff is the leading source of pollution of at least half of the nation's rivers, lakes and coastal waters, yet this problem has received a small fraction of government funds and attention,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Adler </PERSON>, director of the group's clean water project. <PERSON> Adler </PERSON> said the runoff, containing poisonous quantities of lead, zinc, copper, phosphorus and agricultural pesticides and other toxic substances, poses a `` potentially major'' health hazard for swimmers and fish and other wildlife. This runoff has been more difficult to control than water pollution from factories and sewage treatment plants because it is diffuse and is given less federal attention, he said. <PERSON> Adler </PERSON>'s group announced the publication of a book, based on two years of study of poison runoff, that provides case studies of ways to combat the problem. Among its conclusions is that farms are the single largest contributor to the problem because of the use of fertilizers and pesticides that pollute surfrace and ground water, soil erosion that carries excess nutrients and soil particles into rivers and streams and pollution from livestock. `` We're going to have to start thinking about regulating farmers,'' <PERSON> Adler </PERSON> said. The book also said logging, mining, grazing, and construction also contribute to the problem.
