<DATELINE>HAMBURG, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION> residents turn out to celebrate the 104th anniversary of the `` Birth of the Burger'' Saturday, but there's a sizzling debate over the true origin of that most American of meals. <PERSON> Seymour </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, boosters spurn the Hamburgers' claim that the meat patty was first served in this <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, suburb at the 1885 Erie County Fair by entrepreneurs <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Menches </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Tepp </PERSON>, organizer of a 100th anniversary bash for the burger in <LOCATION> Seymour </LOCATION> on Aug. 5, says he can prove the hamburger was first fried and sold by <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Naygreen </PERSON> at the <LOCATION> Outagamie </LOCATION> Country Riding Fair in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> in 1889. `` We've done a lot of research, and we have factual, hard evidence _ pictures, newspaper clippings and even a living descendant,'' <PERSON> Tepp </PERSON> says. <PERSON> Violet </PERSON> <PERSON> Gauerke </PERSON>, daughter of `` Hamburger <PERSON> Charlie </PERSON>,'' says her father was 15 when he got the idea to flatten out meatballs and stick them between slices of bread to make them easier to eat. `` He was known all over the country for it,'' she says. <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> is unimpressed. `` We believe that we were the first,'' he says. `` And that's all that matters.''
