<HEAD>FEC Says Gore Didn't Get Favored Treatment from Banks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> did n't get favored treatment from banks that loaned him $ 1.6 million for his unsuccessful run for the Democratic presidential nomination, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. Most of the loans were taken out around the time of a group Southern primaries in March 1988. The <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> senator had pinned much of his hopes for winning the nomination on those primaries. Election commission auditors initially questioned whether some of the banks making the loans had gotten enough collateral and assurances of repayment. Four of the banks are in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, and the other is in the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s campaign argued that the loans had been repaid in full, which should serve as the ultimate proof of the soundness of the decision to lend the money.
