<HEAD>Police Hiring Plan Gets OK from Senate Panel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel Thursday approved a $ 127 million bill to pay for 700 additional District of <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> police in an effort to stem the burgeoning murder rate in the nation's capital. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> already has approved the plan for the federal government to pick up the tab for the extra officers. By Thursday, 229 people had been killed in the district this year, compared with 159 at the same time in 1988. A record 372 people were killed last year. Police blame more than 60 percent of the slayings on drugs. Before the Governmental Affairs committee approved the five-year plan, Sen. <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, D-Mich., said he might introduce an amendment requiring the city to pay for part of the program The city already has agreed to pay about $ 2 million in recruiting and training costs. However, <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> may drop plans to have the city pay for the officers if he's convinced the district is also making efforts to hire police, said <PERSON> Levin </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustitus </PERSON>. The city is adding 200 officers in the current fiscal year, while 300 more are to be hired in the fiscal year that starts Oct. 1. The panel also approved an amendment by Sen. <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., that requires the city to share routine arrest information and other police data with the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and other federal law enforcement groups Because of a 1968 law establishing a balance of power between the federal and local police departments, the district is the only jurisdiction in the nation not to share such information.
