<HEAD>Proposed Soviet Law on Emigration Boosts Applications</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposed liberalization of emigration laws has nearly quadrupled the number of Soviets seeking to settle in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said Thursday. About 33,000 Soviets moved to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1988. This year, Soviets are registering their intent to emigrate at an annual rate of 120,000, and that could reach a quarter-million by 1990, said <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, consul-general at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has a policy of giving all Soviets who seek to emigrate to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> the chance to do so,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. `` That dates back to a very recent time when we were engaged in a major human rights struggle with Soviet officials to free up emigration. They are doing so at rates that we did not expect but are delighted to see.'' `` I think that once the new emigration law comes into effect and a pattern is established, it could double next year and come awfully close to a quarter million,'' he said. That many Soviet emigres could overwhelm the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> immigration system, since 200,000 would approximately equal the number allowed into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from rest of the world, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. `` That creates an imbalance that we are going to take a good hard look at from a policy perspective,'' said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>. `` The policy is under review <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' by the administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said if the Soviets enact the proposed changes in their emigration law, he will urge <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to pass a one-year waiver of the Jackson-Vanik amendment, thereby reducing the tariffs on Soviet goods exported to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The law, passed in 1972, was sponsored by the late Sen. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and then-Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanik </PERSON> Soviet officials involved in drafting the liberalized emigration law want it enacted as speedily as possible, said <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> human rights department. `` The draft law ... establishes freedom of entry and departure. Exit or entry on a permanent or temporary basis will be free,'' <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> told a news conference. `` The law is on par with international practice in this area.'' The key change will be dropping the requirement that Soviets seeking to emigrate obtain an invitation from an immediate family member abroad. Instead, Soviets will need only an invitation from a friend, relative or commercial enterprise saying the emigre will be supported, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials familar with drafts of the law. The draft addresses two other often-criticized points in the law, which deny visas to people who have conducted classified research and require would-be emigres to secure statements from relatives that they leave behind no outstanding financial obligations, <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> said. Terms of secrecy will expire after five years, and the cases of so-called `` poor relatives'' will be handled by family courts, he said. Foreign Ministry officials have tried to impress upon members of the new legislature, the Supreme Soviet, `` the necessity of the speedy adoption of this law,'' <PERSON> Reshetov </PERSON> said. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consul-general said Soviet citizens were lining up for visas in anticipation of the new legislation. Of the 33,000 Soviet citizens who entered the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1988, said <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, 20,000 first went to <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> on Israeli visas and then on to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and the remainder went directly on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> documents. So far in 1989, Soviets are registering with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials at the rate of 60,000 a year, and at the same rate at the <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, which handles consular affairs for the Israeli government. In any recent week, he said, 1,200 to 1,500 Soviets registered at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, of whom 40 percent were Armenian, 25 percent Jewish, 15 percent ethnic Russians, 5 percent to 8 percent Ukrainians and 5 percent Balts. Others were Azerbaijani, Turkish, Georgian or Tadzhik or another nationality. Of the comparable number that register weekly at the <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> for Israeli visas, he said, about 95 percent are Jewish.
</TEXT>
