<HEAD>Group Says Secret Grant Approval System Unfair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A public group charged Thursday that the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> uses a secret system `` ripe for abuse'' to evaluate grant applications from scientists, and urged the agency to make the process more open. Public Citizen, a non-profit advocacy organization, told <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> that the system violates `` the letter and the spirit of various federal laws that are designed to make federal agency decision-making fair and accountable.'' <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Glitzenstein </PERSON>, a lawyer for Public Citizen, said at a news conference that the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> for 14 years maintained a system of record keeping that blocked grant applicants from learning what had been put into their permanent file. That meant unfounded allegations about a scientist were kept secret, even if the information played a role in denying his grant application, <PERSON> Glitzenstein </PERSON> said. `` The scientist can not learn about the allegation, can not respond to it, and has virtually no ability to appeal the denial,'' he said. `` Anytime you have system based on secret reviews, you have a potential for abuse.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> is distributing about $ 1.8 billion to about 16,000 research projects for the 1989 fiscal year, officials said. The petition sent to <PERSON> Bloch </PERSON> also alleges that the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> has an inadquate system for dealing with potential conflicts of interest that may affect approval of an applicants grant. Applicants, <PERSON> Glitzenstein </PERSON> said, are n't allowed to know who is reviewing their proposal, which means reviewers could include scientists who compete with the applicant. That system also is `` ripe for abuse,'' <PERSON> Glitzenstein </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> changed its filing system last summer to allow future applicants to have have some access to grant-review records, but those before 1988 remain closed, he said. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Grotke </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> assistant general counsel, said the agency would consider the petition but is under no legal obligation to act. The agency, he said, has tried to develop a fair system to review grant applications. Individual scientists or research teams apply for grants to finance projects. The <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> distributes the applications to experts in the field who evaluate the proposals and make recommendations. <PERSON> Glitzenstein </PERSON> said Public Citizen became involved after a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> geologist, <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ervin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kalb </PERSON>, learned that two of his applications in the 1970s had been denied after reviewers discussed an incorrect and unfounded rumor that <PERSON> Kalb </PERSON> worked for the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kalb </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> NSF </ORGANIZATION> settled a lawsuit on the issue in 1987. The agency gave <PERSON> Kalb </PERSON> $ 20,000 in cash, apologized and agreed to correct its records, <PERSON> Glitzenstein </PERSON> said.
