<HEAD>Fahd Calls For Islamic Unity As Pilgrimage Ends</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Khomeini, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALY MAHMOUD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 King Fahd of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> called for Islamic unity Thursday as 1.8 million Moslems ended the annual pilgrimage to their holiest shrines guarded by anti-terrorism squads deployed after two bombings. Fahd made no mention of the explosions Monday that killed a Pakistani pilgrim and wounded 16 other people near the Grand Mosque in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, the birthplace of the prophet <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON>. `` Our prayer is ... that the coming feasts will see the sons of the Islamic nation in solidarity, united and cooperating for the good of our causes and efforts to strengthen security, spread peace, establish justice, and restore rights,'' he said in a message broadcast by Saudi radio and television. As twilight descended around <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION>, the army of pilgrims prayed before they slit the throats of more than 1 million sheep, cows and camels for Eid al-Adha, or the Feast of Sacrifice. The meat traditionally went to poor Saudis. But since the discovery of oil virtually eliminated poverty in the kingdom, most is flown to poor Moslems in 26 countries. The faithful then streamed down <PERSON> Mount </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> to the scorching Plain of <PERSON> Mina </PERSON> and went on to <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> for final prayers during the pilgrimage, or hajj. Waves of veiled women and men in white seamless robes, signifying equality before <PERSON> Allah </PERSON>, took part in the prayers televised live by satellite to scores of Islamic countries. Monday's bombings were the only incidents to mar this year's pilgrimage, and came amid an intensifying war of words with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> over the Saudis limit of 1,000 pilgrims for every 1 million population in Moslem countries <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> boycotted the pilgrimage, as it did when the limits were introduced last year and cut its usual contingent of 150,000 by two-thirds. Saudi security authorities have detained an undisclosed number of suspects in the bombings. The Saudis have not accused any group or country, although <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> newspapers pointed to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Iranian leaders denied involvement and accused Saudi authorities of trying to discredit them. <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> has used the bombings to strengthen its calls for the overthrow of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s royal family, which it accuses of being anti-Islamic, underscoring the historic rift between the world's 1 billion Moslems. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s estimated 50 million people are overwhelmingly of the Shiite sect. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s 12 million people, like most Moslems, mainly are from the mainstream Sunni sect. The Saudis cited vast renovation and construction projects in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> and other holy sites for reducing the number of pilgrims. They severed relations with <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> in April last year, citing terrorism and subversion. Relations between the two countries, soured by Saudi support of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> in the Iran-Iraq war, worsened during the 1987 hajj when the Saudis charged Iranian pilgrims started riots that killed more than 400 pilgrims, mostly Iranians. The Saudis have spent billions of dollars modernizing the holy cities and providing all manner of services for what has become a logistical nightmare. Pilgrims once trudged in the sweltering heat on foot or by camel to make the hajj. Now, they are transported free in 7,500 air-conditioned buses, hundreds of trucks and scores of helicopters. The hajj, which must be made at least once by all Moslems who can afford it, is the world's largest religious congress. It brings together Arabian princes, merchants from <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, paupers from <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Each year, Moslems from <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> and other states join in chanting `` God is so great and to him we pay high tribute.'' At <LOCATION> Mina </LOCATION>, each pilgrim throws seven stones at each of the three `` devil pillars,'' a spot where Moslems believe the devil tried to tempt <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> to disobey <PERSON> Allah </PERSON> and refuse to sacrifice his son. It was 120 degrees Thursday when swarms of hajjis rushed to a Mina gorge to `` stone the devil.'' Many were hospitalized for sunstroke. During the hajj, pilgrims must abstain from sex and may not quarrel, cut their hair, or even kill a fly.
