<HEAD>French Mount Massive Effort to Protect Foreign Leaders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit-Overview, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rooftop marksmen, airborne television cameras and a security force of 30,000 protected the leaders of 34 nations Thursday as they kicked off the bicentennial celebration of the French Revolution. Extra radar installations and even ground-to-air missiles were in place for the three-day celebration and for the summit of the world's seven leading industrialized democracies, which begins Friday. `` It's going well, very well,'' said <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanot </PERSON>, chief of police at the summit site in western <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. `` Anyhow, you ca n't be a pessimist in this business.'' The guns and guards were focused first on <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>' main boulevards, where red, white and blue flags flew and noisy motorcades carried leaders to an array of bicentennial events _ not always to the pleasure of pedestrians. On the Rue du <LOCATION> Faubourg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Honore </LOCATION>, the elegant street on which the Elysee Palace of President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> is situated, police shoved Parisians back into their shops as motorcades sped by. `` I thought this was our city,'' one resident grumbled. Parts of the city were closed to drivers through the weekend. Although many residents fled the city to avoid the mess, police said 1,000 cars were towed Thursday alone. Popular low-lying `` fly boats'' for tourists were forbidden from plying the <LOCATION> Seine </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> running through <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. A 200-foot-long blimp, which can carry a crew of 10, relayed live television pictures from two cameras to ground command centers. The dirigible, estimated to cost $ 7 million, was used earlier this month for surveillance during the visit of Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. Mirage fighters and Crotale ground-to-air missiles backed up the blimp, and six radar systems were added to the four normally installed around <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to ensure that uninvited guests did not enter the skies, security officials said. At the <ORGANIZATION> Arch </ORGANIZATION>, the gleaming arch-shaped building where the seven summiteers will meet, police also planned air protection, said <PERSON> Hanot </PERSON>. He said that in addition to 4,000 police in and around the steel fence ringing the site, 200 sharpshooters were to be stationed on the rooftops of the jumble of skyscrapers in the area. During the summit, traffic will be halted along the five-mile route from central <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to the Arch for an hour each in the morning and the afternoon to allow the foreign leaders to travel, said police.
