<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The leaders of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> on Thursday urged <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> to help organize a summit meeting as soon as possible between developed and developing nations. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> endorsed the proposal but said he would not seek a decision on the issue at a summit meeting of the leaders of seven major industrialized nations that starts here Friday. In a communique issued on the eve of the annual economic summit, Presidents <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Abdou </PERSON> <PERSON> Diouf </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> joined with Indian Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> in saying: `` We believe that steps must be taken to organize a summit-level meeting as soon as possible with a view to discussing global economic and environmental questions of mutual interest.'' <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> told the four that he was `` ready to take the steps necessary to bring about the project,'' said presidential spokesman <PERSON> Hubert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vedrine </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Vedrine </PERSON> said <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> did not intend to ask the other nations participating in the economic summit _ <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> _ to decide on the request for a major conference among the developed and undeveloped nations. `` This is not something for the immediate future,'' <PERSON> Vedrine </PERSON> told a press conference. The four leaders, representing nations in <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, said the proposed conference should mark the beginning of a consultative process between leaders from the developed and developing world. The call for a summit among the leaders of the developed and undeveloped nations was the first publicized result of some 20 bilateral meetings as well as informal lunchtime conversations among the leaders of 34 nations gathered here for the summit and the bicentennial celebration of the French Revolution. During their 15th annual economic summit this weekend, the participants are expected to address the problem of the $ 1.2 trillion debt that has stunted the developing world's growth for more than a decade. Both <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON> are expected to push for partial forgiveness of Third World debts in exchange for guarantees of repayment of the balance. Officials said <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> discussed the issue with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> at a luncheon at the Elysee Palace for almost three dozen heads of state and government attending the French Revolution bicentennial events. <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON>, who sat next to <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON>, raised the issue with the British leader. The developing nations' leaders made their pitch for the ear of the richer nations at a time when the industrialized countries are steeped in a sense of economic optimism, with the economic woes that dominated previous summits apparently under control. Summit host <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, to whom the communique was addressed, has cast himself as a champion of poorer nations and announced in May that <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> would forgive debts totalling $ 2.5 billion owed by 35 African nations. In his response to the four leaders, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> expressed `` his appreciation of this idea, which is in line with his ongoing action in view of restarting the ... dialogue'' between the world's rich and poor nations, his spokesman said. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, too, announced earlier this month it would forgive the debt of the poorest nations of sub-Saharan <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>.
