<HEAD>Fernald, Brookhaven, Oak Ridge, Livermore Added to `Superfund' List</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it will add 52 military installations, nuclear fuel facilities and nuclear laboratories to its list of the nation's worst hazardous waste sites It gave no sign how much the required cleanups will cost. `` Many of these facilities are much larger and more complex than other Superfund sites, with wide varieties of of hazardous and radioactive wastes,'' <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON> said in a news release announcing the additions. Because they are federal facilities owned by various agencies, mostly the Defense and Energy departments, the cleanups mandated by Superfund legislation will come out of the agency budgets, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said. `` You will see -LRB- budget -RRB- demands ballooning in future years as remedies are selected and the cleanup process, the expensive part of the process, kicks in,'' <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON>, the assistant <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> administrator in charge of the Superfund said. The list includes such facilities as the Feed Materials Production Center in <LOCATION> Fernald </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, the Oak Ridge Reservation in <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Brookhaven </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> nuclear military plant in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Lawrence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livermore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Picatinny </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arsenal </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, a 100-year-old munitions testing and storage depot, is also listed. Most of the sites slated for addition to the National Priorities, or Superfund, list are military installation. The 52 sites announced Thursday are in 26 states. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> had the most sites _ 10 _ followed by <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, each with four. Of the 52 sites, 41 belonged to the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION>, nine to <ORGANIZATION> DOE </ORGANIZATION>, one to the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and one to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. All the DOE sites contain both hazardous and radioactive waste, except the <ORGANIZATION> Bonneville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ross </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Complex </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Vancouver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>. Those eight DOE sites are <ORGANIZATION> Brookhaven </ORGANIZATION>, in <LOCATION> Upton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Livermore </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Livermore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>; the Fernald center; the Mound Plant in <LOCATION> Miamisburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Aiken </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; Monticello Mill Tailings in <LOCATION> Monticello </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>; and the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION> So far the priorities list has 1,224 hazarous waste sites, 889 of which are final and 335 are proposed. Federal sites account for 115 of that total, with 41 final and 74 proposed. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> says the list will evenually include more than 200 federal facilities. Once a site is proposed for inclusion, that proposal is open for public comment, usually about 60 days. The list then becomes final. According to <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials at a news briefing, the first step once a site makes the list is a period of study and negotiations lasting up to two years to determine a cleanup course. Federal law requires that actual cleanup work begins no more than 15 months later. States and concerned citizens of the states, as well as the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>, may intervene to make sure the cleanup proceeds as scheduled. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> officials noted that the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> had $ 500 million in cleanup money in its budget proposal for fiscal 1990, but they refused to comment on whether the funds would be adequate. `` We have not engaged in budgeteering relating to these cleanups,'' said Cannon. <PERSON> Cannon </PERSON> did say there were <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> estimates that the cleanup of DOE facilities would cost between $ 80 billion and $ 115 billion. The problem with time and cost estimates, he said, is `` we do n't know what the ultimate remedies are going to be. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> says that to speed up the negotiations over the individual site cleanups it is asking to increase the number of its specialized Superfund fieldworkers from 34 to 116.
