<HEAD>Children in Peace Theme To Honor French Declaration</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-France-Bicentennial, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A choir of children from 15 countries, including three from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, highlighted a theme of international peace Thursday at the start of celebrations for the bicentennial of the French revolution. The children sang, played games and cast laurels, toys and flowers before 32 world leaders assembled at Trocadero, across the Seine from the Eiffel Tower, to honor <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s 1789 declaration of human rights. President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, seated between President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Felix </PERSON> <PERSON> Houphouet-Boigny </PERSON>, smiled as the children ran toward the world leaders and put down the laurels. `` We wanted to symbolize peace,'' said <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Phoenix </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boys </ORGANIZATION>' Choir. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> brought three boys from <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> and helped train the 48-member choir, titled `` Little Singers of the World.'' It was assembled by the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> Children's Fund. `` The children brought things from their world and shared them with those here today,'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said. The children sang `` Song of Joy,'' a piece of composed for the celebrations. The choir also included three Soviet children, and youths from <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rwanda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Togo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LO