<FIRST>r w AM-FMStations     07-13 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-FM Stations,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Gives Smaller FM Stations a Boost</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday approved new rules that will allow thousands of FM stations serving small communities to double their signal strengths and reach larger audiences. The commission, in a 3-0 vote, said so-called Class A FM stations could boost their power from the present limit of 3,000 watts up to 6,000 watts. The commission said the increased power will allow these stations to provide better service to their listeners without causing interference problems with other stations. The commission also revised the distances by which Class A stations must be separated from other stations in order to limit interference. The current separation is about 65 miles -LRB- 105 kilometers -RRB-, while the new separation will be about 71 miles -LRB- 115 kilometers -RRB-, effective Oct. 2. `` The area covered will be 40 percent greater,'' said <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, an official in the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s mass media bureau. Existing stations that do not meet the revised separation requirements will be `` grandfathered,'' and will be allowed to relocate their antennas or request permission to use directional antennas, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. There are more than 2,000 Class A FM stations nationwide, the most numerous of the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION>'s seven classes of FM stations and those which have the smallest service areas. The largest FM stations have signals with 100,000 watts or more. The commission said the small communities to which Class A channels were originally allotted have grown over the years, while the coverage of these stations has remained unchanged. <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> expressed concern about the commission being hit with a wave of applications from stations that need permission to boost their signal strength. He said the current backlog was six months in processing such applications and that it could increase to 18 months under the crush of new filings. He said he hoped <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will allocate additional funds to the agency to handle the expected glut. `` But we should not forgo good policy decisions because it will strain bureau resources,'' <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> added. He acknowledged that some FM stations had asked that the rules be applied in a `` blanket'' fashion, rather than on a selective basis. <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> said a blanket approach would have caused too many interference problems. `` We have not granted all the latitude that was requested,'' he said. To allow many stations to increase their power without delay, the commission said it will publish a list of existing Class A stations that will be able to boost their signal without interfering with other stations. It estimated that about 500 stations will be on the list. Licensees who can increase their power with simple technical changes will be allowed to do so on or after Dec. 1, the commission said, provided that the changes will not subject workers or residents to hazardous levels of radio frequency energy radiation.
