<HEAD>House Panel Approves Medicaid Expansion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee on Thursday approved expansions in the Medicaid health-care program for the poor that would cost the federal government about $ 4 billion over five years. The expansions would bring into the federal-state program many of the pregnant women, infants and children who are not now covered and have no private health insurance. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also unanimously approved a non-binding resolution calling for the <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> program covering catastrophic illnesses to be made voluntary, saying <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> can not ignore the outrage among the elderly over the program. Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the panel's health subcommittee, said, `` I think we need to make some changes in the catastrophic care program because so many people are upset. `` I do n't believe there's any other issue I've had people talk to me about,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Moorhead </PERSON>, R-Calif. Rep. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilirakis </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>., who proposed the resolution, called the program a `` catastrophic catastrophe,'' under which many elderly citizens are being forced to pay for coverage they already have through their former employers and other The measures were approved 30-13 as part of a huge deficit-cutting package for fiscal year 1990, which begins Oct. 1. The package now moves to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The Medicaid expansions would add about $ 183 million to the projected $ 38 billion cost of the program in the next fiscal year. One change would require states to phase in over five years coverage of pregnant women and infants with incomes of up to 185 percent of the federal poverty level. The requirement would begin at 130 percent of poverty by April 1990, which is what the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has proposed, but would rise to 185 percent by July 1, 1993. A similar expansion has been proposed in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The committee shot down an attempt by Rep. <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Callahan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ala </LOCATION>., to protect states like his own where the median income is low and a large proportion of residents live below the federal poverty line He said that under the proposed expansion, more than half of <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>'s newborn children would become eligible for Medicaid at a prohibitive cost to the state, which shares in the cost of the program. Another expansion would phase in coverage of children in families with incomes below the federal poverty level, beginning July 1, 1990, with children born after Sept. 30, 1983. As long as these children remained poor, they would be covered by Medicaid. The committee also approved a change in the way physicians are paid under the Medicare program, replacing the current fee schedule with a new one based on such things as the skill, training and time required to perform a service. The fee structure is intended to correct inequities in the current system that reimburses specialists like surgeons and ophthalmologists at higher rates than general practitioners and internists whose services are mainly `` cognitive.'' The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has approved a similar plan, but included another change that would set an annual target for Medicare spending on physicians. Under the target, physician reimbursement rates could be lowered to recoup overspending of the target. The different versions are expected to be worked out in a conference committee later.
