ursday's ceremonies. Major world leaders also shunned <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s funeral <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> denied <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was behind the bombings in <LOCATION> Mecca </LOCATION> on Monday that killed one person and wounded 16 during the pilgrimage. `` If exporting the revolution means exporting explosives, and creating havoc among other nations, then this accusation is far from the hands of the Islamic republic,'' he said. `` Exporting mischief and corruption belongs to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and ... other aggressive governments,'' he declared. `` The hands of the <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and its underlings ... are stained with the blood of innocents. They are the terrorists. The Islamic republic is absolved of these allegations.'' Thursday's scene was similar to the mass outpouring of grief at <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s funeral, when at least eight people died and 11,000 were injured as frenzied crowds struggled to catch a glimpse of his shrouded body. But this time the authorities were better prepared and organization was more evident, with medical tents, a fleet of 600 buses, centers for lost children and enough food for 10 million. This time, mourners were also covered against death and injury by a special government insurance scheme. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s state-run insurance companies announced that the equivalent of $ 13,500 will be paid to the family of anyone killed or seriously injured in the service. Medical expenses of up to $ 2,000 also will be paid. <ORGANIZATION> IRNA </ORGANIZATION> said 7,000 workers toiled since the funeral to erect the monument over the grave and levelled a a 43-acre area around it to accomodate the hundreds of thousands who gather there every day.
