<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Old-style swat teams have n't worked, so <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> scientists are trying new tactics to curb flies where the nation's farms meet the cities. `` We've seen instances all over the country where urban encroachment in agricultural areas has caused problems for homeowners and agricultural producers,'' said <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bram </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. Cities are sprawling into the countryside at an estimated rate of 900,000 to 1.5 million acres a year, he said Thursday in an agency report. And to the newcomers, flies and barnyard odors are n't part of their idyllic country dream. Some flies can travel great distances from manure piles or other barnyard breeding places to find targets. The stable fly can migrate up to 135 miles. <PERSON> Bram </PERSON> is the national program leader for insects affecting humans at the agency's research facility in <LOCATION> Beltsville </LOCATION>, Md. `` We have to learn how to increase non-chemical fly control and how to make the save chemicals we have work better,'' he said. `` It goes beyond relying on screen doors, sprays and swatters.'' Possible tactics include non-chemical baits in traps to lure flies; natural predators such as wasps that prey on flies while in their pupa stage of development; and natural organisms such as fungi and bacteria that attack flies in cattle feedlots. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> attack is directed at four main kinds of flies: _ Stable flies, which have biting mouth parts and feed on blood _ House flies, which secrete digestive enzymes onto their food, then suck up both enzymes and food _ Horn flies, which bother only livestock on pastures and rangeland _ Face flies, also pests of livestock, but an annoyance to homeowners in the fall Stable flies and house flies from farms are the major problem species for homeowners, said <PERSON> Gustave </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, an entomologist and research leader at the agency's <ORGANIZATION> Midwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Livestock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insects </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> laboratory, <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Neb </LOCATION>. `` In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the stable fly is estimated to cost $ 400 million annually in damage to cattle,'' he said. `` It's hard to put a dollar value on the damage caused by the house fly. But worldwide, this fly may rank in the top 10 insect problems because it can transmit a lot of diseases.''
</TEXT>
