<HEAD>Siberian Coal Miners End Strike After Gov't Agrees to Better Conditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 12,000 striking Siberian coal miners agreed Thursday to return to work after the government agreed to provide better work and living conditions, mine officials and strikers said. The two-day strike began Tuesday at all five mines in <LOCATION> Mezhdurechensk </LOCATION>, prompting <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Coal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> officials to rush to the western Siberian town of 107,000 to settle the dispute, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> newspaper Pravda said. Strikers said Thursday they were satisfied with government concessions that included better night-shift pay, said <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON>, a member of the government commission negotiating with the strikers. Strikes are becoming more common in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where they once were considered a Western phenomenon brought on by capitalist exploitation of workers. Strikes used to be brutally repressed and hushed up, but this year miners' strikes have generally ended within days with government concessions. Night-shift workers at the Shevyakov mine began the strike Monday, and it spread Tuesday to about 12,000 workers citywide, Pravda said. The newspaper described the strikers' demands sympathetically, including calls for round-the-clock cafeteria service, meat and sausage for underground workers, free soap, one free towel per month and a quilted jacket in winter. The strikers' 30 demands included economic independence for the mines, extended vacations for underground workers and improved food and housing, the labor daily <ORGANIZATION> Trud </ORGANIZATION> reported. Calls for greater financial independence of individual mines and for increased night-shift pay were among those immediately granted, said <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolmagorov </PERSON>, a worker at the Shevyakov mine. Requests for better food supplies and housing will take more time, <PERSON> Kolmagorov </PERSON> said by telephone from the mine's strike headquarters. `` People are back at work,'' <PERSON> Ivanov </PERSON> said. `` All their demands are legal and are being decided. Most of them are satisfied, but some will take time.'' Trud said the demands resulted from long years of neglect by authorities interested only in coal production and not in the miners' needs. <PERSON> Mezhdurechensk </PERSON>, about 1,600 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, produces 30 million tons of high-quality coal per year, Trud said. In a bitter letter Trud published in January, <PERSON> Mezhdurechensk </PERSON> miners complained that 10,000 families are waiting for apartments; hospitals and clinics are as crowded `` as anthills,'' with patients waiting a week or more to see a doctor; and schools are overcrowded. The situation was aggravated when the ministry recently took away two housing complexes from miners to accommodate other workers, Trud said. A top Soviet official said in May that new legislation is being drafted that will give unions the legal right to strike. Similar strikes were reported in March and April in the Urals Mountain city of <LOCATION> Vorkuta </LOCATION> and the Siberian city of <ORGANIZATION> Norilsk </ORGANIZATION> but both ended without incident.
