<HEAD>Gorbachev Tells Party to Face Up to Complaints</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials who lack the gumption to respond to the passionate demands and complaints of Soviet citizens should quit, President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in a speech reported Thursday. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> offered that blunt opinion to <ORGANIZATION> Leningrad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders Wednesday just before they sacked their local party chief, <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Solovyov </PERSON>, a candidate member of the ruling Politburo. `` Passions are boiling on the streets, but in many party organizations there is silence,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said in his speech, which was released by the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> Thursday. `` It is necessary to quickly blast out this silence, this dangerous silence! `` It is necessary to face life, to go into life. Whoever does n't have the strength, whoever can not find his place, let him leave,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said `` Before anything else, we must think of the party, of perestroika, of socialism.'' Perestroika, or restructuring, is <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s campaign to overhaul Soviet society and the economy. Although <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> never mentioned <PERSON> Solovyov </PERSON> by name, he was clearly referring to him. When Soviet election law was reformed to allow multiple candidates, <PERSON> Solovyov </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> leaders engineered their parliamentary races to run unopposed. Then they suffered humiliating defeats when angry citizens crossed their names off ballots, denying them the required 50 percent approval. <PERSON> Solovyov </PERSON> also ignored calls for his resignation and the issues raised during the election campaign, which brought thousands of Leningraders into the streets for public meetings. In his speech, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> charged that the <ORGANIZATION> Leningrad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> regional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> failed to pay attention to the roots of people's complaints, in particular their demand for practical results from perestroika The party, he indicated, must defend itself through its actions. As an example, he cited local authorities for failing to improve a particular factory's working conditions. He said the conditions were like those facing laborers in the time of <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> the </PERSON> <PERSON> Great </PERSON>, who founded <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> in 1703. `` They've been talking about ventilation for two years, and they can not put it right. The dust is terrible, the conditions unbearable. It's shameful! `` Well, comrades, for this, you need billions?'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> asked rhetorically. `` So people look at this and say, ` Perestroika has been going on for four years, and nothing has changed. This is where we get irritation, indignation and criticism,'' he said. `` Where is their -LRB- official -RRB- union? Where is their party organization?'' Local authorities often blame <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for failing to solve purely local problems `` which the central government does n't handle, and should n't handle,'' he said. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> also told his audience not to fear new ideas _ a failing he had previously found in <PERSON> Solovyov </PERSON>. In April, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> reprimanded the <LOCATION> Leningrad </LOCATION> party chief for complaining that the party was becoming `` a discussion club.'' The current period of change, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said Wednesday, brings forth diverse opinions, `` which many people perceive as a threat to what we have achieved, as a threat to perestroika. Comrades, we must preserve our strength of spirit, our tolerance, our realism in evaluating the progress of perestroika, in predictions for the future.''
