<HEAD>In Ways and Means Committee, It's Bankers 1, Consumers 0</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted Thursday to speed up elimination of the tax deduction for interest on consumer loans in order to keep a tax break for bankers and corporate executives. The quicker loss of the interest deduction will affect about 24 million couples and individuals. The other part of the bargain is expected to benefit a few dozen people, committee aides said. The panel, working on a broad package of tax changes, rejected an effort to delay the new surtax that older Americans pay for catastrophic health insurance. That change would have been financed, in turn, by cutting the tax on capital gains. That combination of changes, proposed by Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Archer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, was defeated on a 25-11 vote. All Democrats and Republican Reps. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gradison </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> McGrath </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> opposed it. However, committee aides said the panel appears ready to make some significant change in the financing of catastrophic insurance, since many older Americans have been vocal in their opposition to the present law. Aides also indicated there still is considerable sentiment among members to make some reduction in the capital-gains tax, even though chairman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, D-Ill., has ruled out a reduction on the grounds that his Democratic troops wo n't support it The committee completed action on the assembly of $ 5.3 billion worth of deficit-reduction revenue increases that it is under orders from the <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> to produce for the budget years that begins Oct. 1. However, work will continue next week on a variety of other tax proposals, including catastrophic medical insurance, capital gains and child care. By a voice vote, the panel overturned a decision taken 24 hours earlier and eliminated from the package an increase in taxes on snuff and pipe and chewing tobacco. The three products would have been taxed at $ 2.67 a pound; snuff now is taxed at 24 cents; pipe tobacco at 45 cents and chewing tobacco at 8 cents. In place of those increases, the committee voted to speed up collection of taxes from dividends received from mutual funds. Instead of being liable for taxes on the date a dividend is received, a shareowner would have to pay from the time the dividend is declared. The biggest single revenue-raiser, affecting corporations that use employee stock-ownership plans to avoid takeover and banks that lend to them, was scaled back. It was to finance part of that retreat that the committee agreed to a quicker end to deductions for interest on consumer loans. Under the 1986 tax reform legislation, those deductions have been reduced year by year on their way to complete elimination. This year only 20 percent of interest paid on loans for automobiles, education and credit cards is deductible. That had been scheduled to drop next year to 10 percent. Under the committee's action, the interest deduction would die at the end of this year. The committee wants to reduce two existing tax benefits connected with ESOPs, under which workers are given shares of the companies where they are employed. Under the committee's action Thursday, a banker that lends to an <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> will be allowed to continue avoiding tax on half the interest earned from such loans only if the <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> owns 30 percent or more of the corporation. The same 30 percent test would be applied before a corporation could take a tax deduction for certain dividends paid on <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> stock. A second change would make the new rule effective on July 10 _ more than a month later than the committee originally had agreed to. This change would allow dozens of corporations that are in the processing of setting up ESOPs to qualify for treatment under the old rules. Most of the provisions in the committee's deficit-reduction plan are technical changes that generally affect only corporations.
