 The chairman of a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> narcotics subcommittee, attacking the anti-drug campaigns of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administrations as `` phony,'' proposed a $ 120 million program Thursday to help local police establish and expand drug intelligence units. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, D-Mass., introduced legislation to provide direct aid to local police departments for computers, electronic intelligence-gathering equipment and added personnel for anti-drug task forces `` It's time we gave police officers ... the kind of support they deserve,'' <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` We would be expanding the kind of police work which prevents drug-related crime from happening in the first place.'' The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Relations narcotics subcommittee said $ 63 million would go to state governments _ at least $ 500,000 to each state _ for drug intelligence units and equipment. About two-fifths of that money would be passed on to cities with fewer than 100,000 people. The rest of the money, $ 57 million, would go directly from the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to big cities. <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> said the Drug Intelligence Act would `` provide an extra boost to local police departments at a time when their budgets are the tightest but their needs in fighting a real war on drugs are the greatest.'' `` Police drug intelligence units that already exist in major cities are important components in the war on drugs,'' he said. `` But even where these units exist, they need upgrading and more equipment.'' <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON>, deriding the anti-drug efforts of <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> administrations through the 1980s, said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has spent only $ 500 million of the $ 2.7 billion <ORGANIZATION> Congres