<HEAD>House OKs Fee for Ham Radio Operators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee voted Thursday to levy licensing fees on ham-radio operators and satellite-launching companies and to increase fees on communications businesses to help reduce the federal budget deficit by $ 50 million. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> also voted to outlaw obscene dial-a-porn messages on interstate and intrastate telephone calls and to restrict access to indecent dial-a-porn messages. It adopted a new fairness doctrine that requires broadcasters to air opposing views on controversial public issues. The committee attached the dial-a-porn and fairness doctrine motions to a budget reconciliation bill. The $ 50 million in increased fees were to help <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> meet the $ 110 billion deficit limit established by the Gramm-Rudman deficit-reduction law for fiscal 1990. Under the committee's bill, existing licensing fees charged by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> will go up an average of 12.6 percent. Seventeen communications areas that were exempted will have fees for the first time, ranging from $ 30 for an amateur radio license to $ 70,000 for a permit to launch a satellite, said committee spokesman <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON>. FCC fines that have not been changed since 1934 also will be increased, <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said. He said the `` vast majority'' of the $ 50 million will come from new fees, with about a third of the money coming from private radio operations such a rural radio, national paging services, offshore radio and mobile and cellular phones. Minimum fees in nearly all cases will be $ 30, as opposed to $ 5 currently. The $ 70,000 for satellites is the maximum. Other fees include a $ 6,760 fee for a telephone company that requested an <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> hearing. The dial-a-porn provision is in response to a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling last month that invalidated a 1988 law that had outlawed the $ 2 billion dial-a-porn business. The court said indecent speech was protected by the constitution but that obscene speech was not. The court since 1973 has defined obscenity as a work that is patently offensive, purient and has no serious literary, artistic, political or scientific value. <PERSON> Connolly </PERSON> said the committee's action `` takes the ruling of the court and works with those constitutional restraints. It bans obsecne speech ... and it regulates indecent speech.'' The bill requires telephone companies to block dial-a-porn calls to their customers' lines unless a customer formally asks to have access to the service. The fairness doctrine was added only after the committee voted 35-8 against an amendment by Rep. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, to strip the provision from the bill. <PERSON> Tauke </PERSON> said the fairness doctrine, a set of guidelines the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> repealed in 1987, was unnecessary, unconstitutional and made the bill `` veto bait'' at the White House. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> committees both passed fairness doctrine bills in April. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has indicated he would veto a fairness doctrine law, and fairness doctrine proponents were not assured of enough votes to override a veto.
