<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tens of thousands of Hungarians on Thursday mourned longtime <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Janos </PERSON> <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>, who died last week more than a year after being eased from power by reformers. `` We came to thank him for what he did for us and the <LOCATION> Hungarian </LOCATION> people,'' said <PERSON> Viktor </PERSON> <PERSON> Segre </PERSON>, who said he and his wife, <PERSON> Eva </PERSON>, waited more than three hours to view <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s red and black shrouded casket lying in state at the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Budapest </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>, 77, died on July 6. He is to be buried Friday in a state ceremony attended by <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>'s new leadership and delegations from the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact. On Thursday, mourners, many weeping and carrying flowers, gathered in the late afternoon to pay their respects to <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>, who took power as Soviet troops crushed the 1956 anti-Stalinist uprising. In the 32 years before he was ousted by a new generation of reformers in 1988, <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> was conciliatory or ruthless by turns as he searched for consensus in party ranks. But <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> gained respect at home and abroad by the 1970s after launching economic reforms and ushering in a new spirit of tolerance that was in stark contrast to the early years of his rule and many neighboring communist countries. <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s legacy of stability and reform efforts appeared to have drawn many to the austere center of communist power in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, bedecked on Thursday with wreaths and floral displays in his memory. `` He gave us peace and a sense of security,'' said <PERSON> Eva </PERSON> <PERSON> Segre </PERSON>. `` He got the country going again after 1956 and won international respect for <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>.'' `` Comrade <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> was a great man,'' said an elderly woman, who asked not to be identified. She said she waited four hours and `` would have waited longer if I had to.'' The line of those waiting to file through the hushed gallery of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> building stretched more than four city blocks. Hundreds clutched small bouquets of carnations and roses and many carried large wreaths. In May 1988, <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> lost his post as party general secretary. A year later, he was removed as honorary party chairman and stripped of his membership in the policy-setting <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which criticized him for mistakes during his long rule. Although he ushered in economic reforms in the late 1960s and early 1970s, <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON> was increasingly blamed for an economic decline after the reforms stalled. Many in the party leadership viewed him as an obstacle to renewal in the country. The Communist Party's re-evaluation of the 1956 uprising as a popular revolt and the rehabilitation of <PERSON> Imre </PERSON> <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON>, the prime minister who led it, eroded the legitimacy of <PERSON> Kadar </PERSON>'s rule for many. <PERSON> Nagy </PERSON> was executed in 1958 and was buried in an unmarked grave. His remains were reburied in an elaborate ceremony June 16 that was attended by hundreds of thousands of Hungarians. Under the leadership of a new generation of reformers, <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> has embarked on an ambitious program of economic and political reforms designed to move the nation toward a market economy and closer ties to the West.
