<HEAD>Nurses Strike Puts Hospital Group at One-Fifth Patient Load</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Patients of the state's largest hospital company had to cross picket lines to see their doctors Thursday as 1,300 nurses began striking for higher wages and guaranteed hours. The strike left <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Puget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sound </ORGANIZATION> with a non-union staff capable of handling only one-fifth of the normal patient load at its three hospitals. About 130 patients were moved to other hospitals and 72 remained, said <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Nudelman </PERSON>, the health maintenance organization's executive vice president and chief operating officer. Negotiations broke off shortly after midnight Thursday, and picketing began at 6 a.m. at Group Health hospitals and clinics in five Puget Sound counties that include this city and <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>. Picket lines were up at all Group Health centers except its specialty medical center, which provides urology, oncology, internal medicine and other services, <PERSON> Sosne </PERSON> said. The cooperative also runs 23 family medical centers and four specialty medical centers. All the centers will be open and staffed by physicians and other staff, <PERSON> Nudelman </PERSON> said. Group Health began hiring non-union nurses and preparing to lay off non-nursing staff in preparation for what's expected to be a long strike, <PERSON> Nudelman </PERSON> said. The layoffs were intended to save money. <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosne </PERSON>, president of Local 1199 of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION>, said the talks broke off because <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> refused to compromise on key issues, particularly staffing decisions. <PERSON> Nudelman </PERSON> said the cooperative's latest offer was still on the table, and that a phone call was all that was needed to reopen talks. `` Our wage and benefit package would make Group Health nurses the best paid in the state of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` It would also give our nurses significant input into decision-making that directly affects their workplace.'' The latest contract offer would boost yearly pay for a first-year nurse to $ 27,706 from $ 23,000, based on a 40-hour work week. A nurse with 15 years' experience would earn about $ 41,000, up from $ 33,000. The nurses were seeking raises of 16 percent in the first year and 14 percent in the second. Management's offer amounts to 23.5 percent over two years. Also at issue in the talks is the company's practice of cutting nurses' hours when there are few patients in the hospital. The nurses are seeking contract provisions to protect their income. The company, a health maintenance organization, has about 370,000 members. An HMO is a type of medical insurance plan that offers members treatment for a fixed monthly payment, rather than reimbursing them on a per-visit basis.
