<DATELINE>SILVER CITY, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Biologists on Thursday used long-handled nets to scoop an endangered species of trout from a creek polluted with ash from a nearly beaten wild fire. Firefighters mopped up blazes in five other Western states. The <LOCATION> Gila </LOCATION> trout, lured into a clear section of <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Creek </ORGANIZATION> a day earlier, were collected along a three-quarter mile stretch and put in holding tanks on the sides of mules or horses to be taken eventually to an Apache fish hatchery. `` They are hoping to remove at least 300 of the fish from the creek and more if possible,'' said <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman. The creek was becoming choked by ash from a lightning-caused fire in <ORGANIZATION> Gila </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> that burned more than 10,000 acres before being contained on Monday. The blaze began June 30 and burned 50 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Silver </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. The fire should be controlled in two to four days, Ms. <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> said. Fires in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> were largely contained Thursday. Firefighters mostly mopped up and monitored hot spots. Ash kicked up by the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> blaze had settled in <LOCATION> Diamond </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION>, choking off oxygen and possibly boosting the water's alkalinity The netted fish were to be transported in 250-gallon aerated tanks aboard two trucks to a hatchery run by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATIO