e than a week In <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, a fire near the <LOCATION> Ventana </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wilderness </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Padres </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> was 70 percent contained. More than 1,500 firefighters were on the firelines at the blaze, which burned 3,087 acres. Three other fires were contained. Five of six fires that have blackened nearly 9,000 acres in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> have been declared contained. The sixth, a 2,000-acre blaze fire in north-central <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Collins </LOCATION>, was 95 percent contained, officials said. In <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>'s northwest corner, the Fort <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> fire, which destroyed 10,000 acres of the 22,000-acre <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Robinson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> State </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION>, was contained with full control expected by Friday, said Fire Chief <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Gartner </PERSON>. The blaze destroyed 14 structures and injured nine people, none seriously. <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> firefighters battled a 225-acre fire next to the <LOCATION> Mogollon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rim </LOCATION> in east-central <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> and expected to contain it on Saturday. Every other major fire in the state was declared contained Wednesday. Some 3,000 acres burned.
