<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sri Lankan soldiers and police will take charge of law and order from Indian troops in the northeast, who then will be treated as an occupational army, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Ranjan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> said Thursday. He said the takeover will occur July 29, the deadline President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> set for the pullout of 40,000 Indian troops deployed in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> is refusing to withdraw them. A moderate Tamil leader who supported the deployment of Indian soldiers in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> and a party colleague were killed in a <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> home Thursday, officials said. In his comments Thursday, <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> said President <PERSON> Ranasinghe </PERSON> <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> would stick to the pullout deadline. `` Sri Lankan army and police will come out of their barracks to maintain law and order in the north and east, because after July 29 the Indian troops will be treated as an occupational army,'' <PERSON> Wijeratne </PERSON> said. On Wednesday, Indian Prime Minister <PERSON> Rajiv </PERSON> <PERSON> Gandhi </PERSON> said a pullout of the troops could only be decided through negotiations and had to be accompanied by increasing powers for the Tamil government in the Northeastern Province. The message was tantamount to refusing to withdraw the troops by <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON>'s deadline. In a reply Thursday, <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> said military action by the Indian armed forces was `` unnecessary and prejudicial to a settlement by discussion and negotiation.'' He said his government was willing to hold talks on the issue but the pullout and political issue were `` totally unconnected.'' Indian soldiers were deployed in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s Tamil-dominated north and east on July 29, 1987, under an agreement between the two countries. The Indian-mediated accord was aimed at ending a rebellion by Tamil insurgents. The rebels were to give up their weapons in exchange for limited autonomy in regions where they dominated and Indian soldiers were to ensure peace. But the peace plan fell apart after the largest rebel group, the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>, backed out and began fighting the <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION>. Smaller Tamil groups surrendered and were voted to power in the province's local elections last year but now accuse the government of not giving them enough power. The moderate Tamil leader who was killed was identified by an <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official as <PERSON> Appapillai </PERSON> <PERSON> Amirthalingam </PERSON>, the 62-year-old leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said another party member was also killed and three people were injured. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> news agency said <PERSON> Amirthalingam </PERSON> and his colleague were killed by three gunmen belonging to the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Eelam </ORGANIZATION>. The three gunmen were later shot and killed by <PERSON> Amirthalingam </PERSON>'s bodyguards, the news agency said. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION> exchanged sharply worded letters after <PERSON> Premadasa </PERSON> asked <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> on June 1 to pull out its soldiers by the second anniversary of the agreement. The request followed talks in May between his government and the <ORGANIZATION> Tamil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION>, the first direct contact between the two sides since the insurgency began in 1983. Under the 1987 agreement, Indian soldiers took over law and order in the north and east and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lankan </LOCATION> troops were confined to their barracks. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> became involved in the troubles of the island nation off its southern coast because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils for the rebel cause. Sri Lankan Tamils launched a war for a separate nation complaining of discrimination by the majority Sinhalese community. The predominantly Hindu Tamils comprise 18 percent of <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>'s 16 million people, and the <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinhalese </ORGANIZATION> make up 75 percent Also Thursday, officials announced that more than 40,000 public transport workers ended a crippling monthlong strike after reaching a wage agreement with the government. Bus drivers, clerks and mechanics of the state-owned transport company walked off their jobs on June 12, demanding higher wages. But the government said the strike was sponsored by Sinhalese militants using the wage issue to fuel civil unrest. The militants say the government has been too soft on the Tamils. Transport Minister <PERSON> Wijepala </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendis </PERSON> said in a statement that the government would increase workers' monthly salaries by $ 5.60 and give monthly back pay of $ 1.50 retroactive to January 1982.
