<HEAD>Senate Approves Immigration Overhaul</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS day in lede to Thursday, ADDS two grafs listing opponents
and those not voting, which will serve in lieu of a roll call.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday approved an overhaul of the immigration system that would limit new arrivals to 630,000 in each of the next three years and expand the number coming from <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` This bill not only carries forward and increases the present emphasis on family reunification, it also opens opportunities for new immigrants with new skills,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., one of the bill's sponsors The bill, approved 81-17 after two days of debate, now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. It was originally designed to cap immigration at 600,000 in each of the next three years but was expanded by 30,000 visas before final passage. The ceiling represents 136,000 more visas than were issued in 1988, but but critics say the bill still could reduce visas for all but the closest relatives of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens and permanent residents of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> approved a similar bill in 1988 but it died in the House. The measure now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and the measure's co-sponsor, Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Wyo </LOCATION>., saying they are optimistic about the prospects this Lawmakers voted 78-21 to expand the cap by 30,000 visas a year following an emotional appeal from Sen. <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa., who recalled how his father fled `` the boot of the czar'' in 1911 and arrived in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> `` with no rubles in his pocket He had to come steerage.'' `` There is nothing magic to me about the number 600,000,'' <PERSON> Specter </PERSON> said. But senators fought back 52-46 a move by Sen. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Boschwitz </PERSON>, R-Minn., to expand by 40,000 the number of brothers and sisters of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizens that would be allowed into the country annually `` My heart is on the side of what Sen. <PERSON> Boschwitz </PERSON> is doing,'' Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, D-Ill., said But he added that `` there is a saturation point with the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public and I want to be prudent as we move ahead.'' <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said it was `` time to face the unfortunate but hideously cold reality that there are many more people who want to come here than there is room or intent to accommodate them.'' Following intense floor skirmishing, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> did approve an amendment from Sen. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelby </PERSON>, D-Ala., that would force the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> to halt its practice of including illegal aliens in its official count Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, said that under the current system `` states like <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> would gain a -LRB- congressional -RRB- seat at <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s expense'' because their populations are swollen with illegal aliens. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> called the amendment `` flatly unconstitutional,'' but lawmakers refused 58-41 to kill it and eventually adopted it on a voice vote. The legislation would reserve 120,000 visas annually for those entering on a basis other than family ties. That category includes 54,000 visas subject to a point system giving credit for those with special skills needed by American industry but who do not have employers ready to sponsor them. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 12-2 to delete the provision that would provide extra points to individuals who speak English. <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> appealed to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in vain to restore the point system but lawmakers rejected the idea, 56-43. `` English is the language of success,'' he declared. He said those who are unable to understand English will have a tough time obtaining jobs and urged lawmakers not to be swayed by sentimental portrayals as immigrants as the heart and soul of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> dream. `` The heart and soul disappears when you ca n't get work,'' he said. <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, however, quoted a news clipping that said 13 of the 16 valedictorians in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s publish high schools this year were born in foreign countries and the majority apparently did not have English for a mother tongue. <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> expressed frustration that the sentiment-tinged debate appeared to be going against him. `` You have snorted and ripped and rolled around in it and you have just given birth to a mouse,'' he declared. Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved, 358-44, and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> separate legislation to ease immigration of certain Soviet and Southeast Asian refugees. It would temporarily re-establish the legal status of Soviet Jews and evangelican Christians as well as certain categories of Vietnamese, Laotians and Cambodians as persecuted, without individuals having to prove it in their own cases. That would aid them in obtaining standing as refugees. The measure is opposed by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, which contends it unnecessarily establishes special preferences for certain refugees and makes it more difficult to administer the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> refugee program fairly. Those voting against the measure were Sens. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Breaux </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-La </LOCATION>.; <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Bumpers </PERSON>,