<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> supplied the key to help unlock the biggest birthday party in French history Thursday as swanky dinners and the opera took center stage after the president's four-day trip to <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and more than 30 other world leaders were treated to a swirl of festivities celebrating the 200th anniversary of the French Revolution. The events ranged from a solemn ceremony commemorating the drafting of the French version of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Declaration of Independence to an offbeat parade capping the celebration Friday that will feature Russians dancing with a bear on ice, Britons marching under artificial rain and a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> band moonwalking up the famed Champs Elysee. To guard against terrorist attacks, 30,000 police were deployed around the city with rooftop marksmen and even ground-to-air missiles added to the security dragnet. Amid the hoopla of the birthday bash, more weighty issues were being discussed as well. The president's other reason for being in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> was to attend his first economic summit of the leaders of the world's seven richest nations. The 15th annual economic conference among the leaders of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> was to feature for the first time a major emphasis on ways to clean up the global environment. With his historic trip to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> still very much on his mind, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> indicated he would be urging the other summit leaders to step forward with assistance packages of their own to further economic and political reform behind the Iron Curtain. Speaking to report