<HEAD>Child Kills Sister Hours after Gun Bill Signed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A baby died Thursday after being shot by her 6-year-old sister hours after Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> signed a bill to protect children from accidental shootings in the home. Nine-month-old <PERSON> Enereida </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> was the fourth <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> child killed this summer in an accidental shooting. She was shot late Wednesday after her sister, <PERSON> Llasmin </PERSON>, found a .38 - caliber revolver lying under a towel on their parents' bed, police <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> was horrified by the news, said his press secretary, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Peck </PERSON>. `` It just underscores the whole problem, when a child is shot just hours after he signs a bill to stop these things from happening,'' <PERSON> Peck </PERSON> said. Although the law signed by <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> does n't take effect until Oct. 1, <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> authorities could bring charges under existing laws. `` We will gather all the information and turn it over to the state attorney's office for review under the culpable negligence statute,'' said police spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON>. Under the new law, no grieving parent of an injured or fatally wounded child shot by another member of the family could be arrested until seven days after the incident. The law provides for adults to be charged with a felony, punishable by up to five years in prison and a $ 5,000 fine, if a child shoots himself or another because of the owner's carelessness. If a minor threatens someone with the gun or displays it in public, the gun owner faces a misdemeanor charge and up to 60 days in jail and a $ 500 fine. The law requires gun owners to prevent loaded weapons kept in homes and businesses from falling into the hands of children 15 and younger by using such precautions as trigger locks or keeping a weapon in a locked box. Three children died in early June in similar household shootings, inspiring lawmakers to push for the legislation during a special session intended to deal with other issues last month.
