<LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Covenas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cano </PERSON> <PERSON> Limon </PERSON> is operated jointly by <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ecopetrol </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> wants foreign oil companies out of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. In another development, the national police said antinarcotics police arrested a captain and two lieutenants of the national police on suspicion of drug trafficking. The three police officers were arrested Wednesday as they landed in a helicopter in the southwest state of <LOCATION> Valle </LOCATION>, the police said. The police had $ 259,000 in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency with them, the police said. The chief of the national police, Gen. <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> <PERSON> Padilla </PERSON>, began raids on drug laboratories two hours after taking over in January from a general who was fired by President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> for allegedly trafficking in cocaine. <PERSON> Gomez </PERSON> has fired more than 1,000 policemen for their associations with known drug traffickers or other criminals.
