<HEAD>House Wants to End Tongass Forest Timber Deals</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Changes references to ``lumber'' to timber throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> approved environmentalist-backed legislation Thursday that would cancel 50-year deals under which two timber companies have been harvesting trees from <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> at bargain basement prices. The legislation, which passed 356-60, also establishes more wilderness areas in the forest in southeastern <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and creates buffer zones around many streams and tributaries to protect fish from logging operations. The timber contracts have been a `` raid on the taxpayers,'' said Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., who led debate in favor of the bill `` We say get your hands out of our pockets.'' `` The timber companies keep the bureaucrats employed and the bureaucrats keep the timber companies wallowing in federal subsidies,'' said <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. `` I'm terribly disappointed,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, who led the fight against the bill in the name of jobs for his state's residents `` It goes to show the influence of the environmentalist point of view.'' The legislation is directed at <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> Pacific-Ketchikan and <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pulp </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a Japanese firm, and <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said 6,000 jobs could be lost if the companies go out of business. Proponents of the bill, however, said it throws the door open to competition from independent timber companies, owned by Alaskans, which could create more jobs for the state population. `` If we cancel these contracts, it does n't drive the timber industry out of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Mrazek </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, co-sponsor of the bill. `` It simply puts these companies on same footing as other companies.'' Young, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> and many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, including <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Kika </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, favored a version of the bill that would have called for renegotiation rather than cancellation of the timber contracts. The <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> oversees the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which is part of the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. But that version, offered as an amendment, failed on a 269-144 vote. The bill now goes to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, where <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said he expected an outcome more to his liking. If the legislation is not changed, it will be vetoed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> has said he would recommend a veto of legislation that called for termination of the contracts. The House bill eliminates the $ 40 million that now goes annually for such activities as road-building to aid the timber companies in Tongass and requires an amount to be set each year in the federal budget. Proponents said that could save the government $ 205 million over the next five years. It also would end the requirement that the government make 4.5 billion board feet of the forest's timber available each decade. The bill would designate 23 areas as wilderness, barring timber harvesting and development on 1.8 million acres. The legislation also would ban logging within 100 feet of salmon streams. In an effort to establish a stable economy in southeast <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1947 authorized the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to later sign the unprecedented 50-year contracts with timber companies. The contracts with the two firms expire in 2004 and 2011. The forest is the size of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> combined and stretches over most of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s 500-mile long panhandle. It's one of the few remaining temperate rain forests, with an annual precipitation of averaging 150 inches. It and the Olympic National Park in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> are the last remnants of a rain forest that used to stretch from northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>.
