<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Off-Hollywood Adv19   07-13 1102</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Off-Hollywood, Adv 19,1143</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed PMs, July 19 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>North Carolina Growing Fast in Movie Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is another in occasional series of articles on the proliferation of moviemaking outside <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>. Tempted by friendly officials eager to please, filmmakers are flocking to out-of-state locations, spending billions of dollars that once would have stayed in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By ROBIN P. TEATER</NOTE>
<NOTE>Associated Press Writer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The stars are hanging out in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, and they're not just in the sky. Projects featuring such movie actors as <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunaway </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Duvall </PERSON>, <PERSON> Natasha </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Debra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Winger </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolte </PERSON> are solidifying <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> as a hotbed for moviemaking. `` They're major caliber people and major caliber projects. Both of those are looking at Academy Award-type situations,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Film </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. In the past few months, two movies with those actors have been shooting in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>: `` The Handmaid's Tale'' in <LOCATION> Raleigh </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, and `` Everybody Wins'' in <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION>. `` I think we started out with major films and higher caliber pictures than had been the general rule in the South,'' <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> said. Starting with such movies as `` Being There,'' starring <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sellers </PERSON>, in 1979 and `` Brainstorm,'' starring <PERSON> Natalie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>, in 1983, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> has also made <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Spielberg </PERSON>'s `` The Color Purple,'' `` The Year of the Dragon'' and many others. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> is one of the fastest growing moviemaking locations in the country, and is second to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in the number of sound stages and studios, <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> said, with 18 sound stages and four studios with plans for a fifth. `` We also have the largest resident work force of crew and technical people on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, after <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' he said. Still, even though 42 states have film offices and actively compete for business, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> remains the film leader of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, with <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> close at its heels. Though not always cheaper, it's easier to make a movie outside <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. One-stop, state-controlled film offices are preferred to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s patchwork approach, where local governments issue permits with fluctuating fees and have requirements that are 70 years old. And the long-held belief that <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> could re-create anything from the Tara plantation in `` Gone With the Wind'' to the <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> in `` One From the Heart'' has been abandoned by filmmakers who want greater realism. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s moderate climate and diverse landscape are attractive to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> producers. `` It's the best,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroud </PERSON>, location manager for `` The Handmaid's Tale.'' `` Everyone makes it so easy for you, and the bureaucracy is nil. This really is the ideal place to film _ I think the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, in general.'' The movies `` Bull Durham,'' a delightful romp about life in minor league baseball, and `` Winter People,'' a drama about intense relations starring <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> <PERSON> McGillis </PERSON> were both filmed in 1987. `` ` Winter People' is a depression-era, very cold, snowy film. ` <ORGANIZATION> Bull </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Durham </ORGANIZATION>' is just the opposite,'' <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> said. `` But they were both shot in November and they both got what they want.'' Since <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> can offer a variety of `` looks,'' film company have fewer location moves. `` The Handmaid's Tale,'' which is being filmed entirely in the state, needed seasonal changes and also the look of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> college, which it found at <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Based on the acclaimed novel by <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwood </PERSON>, the book is a daring move into the future and tells the tale of what happens after a right-wing religious revolution has swept <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, imposing a dictatorial regime and ruthlessly executing any dissenters. In 1982, the science-fiction movie `` Brainstorm'' filmed in six different locations without leaving <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lure </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> mountains served as the backdrop for much of the musical `` Dirty Dancing,'' which <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> calls one of the most successful made in the state. `` It cost them -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Vestron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- $ 2.3 million to shoot that here,'' <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> said. `` They've been back here twice since. That movie has generated more than $ 750 million. That's a tremendous return. That's the kind of thing that really sells the state.'' <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>'s return also has been tremendous. Since the state's film office was established in 1980, it has spent only $ 1.05 million to attract moviemakers _ none of it on advertising like many states do, such as <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Arkansas </ORGANIZATION> even offered a 5 percent rebate. `` The film industry is really very small,'' <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> said. `` If <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> is a good place to shoot, everybody will know it. We have put our emphasis on making sure the people who come here get what they were promised they'd get.'' Films, TV movies, commercials and videos have pumped $ 1.6 billion into the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> economy over the past nine years, including $ 297 million generated by 19 productions in 1988. Producers say they can make a movie cheaper in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> _ a right to work state _ partly because they have a choice of whether to use union or non-union actors and technicians. Money can be saved by hiring non-union extras for movies with large casts, but many films made outside <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> use union crews because their Hollywood-based production companies must honor contracts with talent and craft unions. `` The cost of an average movie in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> is $ 18 million,'' <ORGANIZATION> Arnold </ORGANIZATION> said. `` <PERSON> Dino </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurentiis </PERSON> -LRB- whose studio was based in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> -RRB- two years ago said the average cost in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> is $ 9 million. `` It has grown at a rate that it's been comfortable for the state to accommodate. It's been very beneficial.'' The economic impact is mostly indirect, through money film companies spend on hotels, food, supplies, equipment and location fees. When <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>'s `` Firestarter'' was filming in 1983, <LOCATION> Orton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plantation </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Wilmington </LOCATION> was used as major location. `` They needed to burn that to the ground in a final scene,'' <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> said. `` What they had to do was re-create the facade, and they spent $ 80,000 ... to burn it in one whack.'' A service station operator pumped $ 6,000 worth of gas in one day for production company trucks and cars when `` Brainstorm'' was being shot. The direct impact, though, comes by way of income taxes. The movies made in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> have created 53,000 jobs, including actors, extras, crew people and drivers. `` Basically, a film company will come into a community and drop literally millions of dollars _ it's a great economic boost,'' <PERSON> Stroud </PERSON> said. `` You do n't have to go out and browbeat a community to get involved,'' said <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>. `` In general, the citizens are very excited about making movies.''
</TEXT>
