<FIRST>s i BC-NorthKoreaToday Adv23   07-13 1176</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-North Korea Today, Adv 23,1215</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>North Korea Opening Up, But Holds Fast to Regimentation</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This is main story in package of three.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is gradually ending decades of secrecy and claims to have achieved paradise, but it is a paradise where all 20 million angels march in lockstep. Here is a report from the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> bureau </ORGANIZATION> chief in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, who visited <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> recently.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The hermit of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> is emerging and what is seen is a regimented society that, in contrast to more liberal communism elsewhere, trains its 20 million people to obey every command of the state. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> claims to have achieved Paradise on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. Its leaders declare with pride that the nation has no taxes, no prisons, no want, no social unrest. Well-informed outsiders, however, say the country has trouble feeding itself, is burdened with foreign debts and is rapidly falling behind the vibrant capitalist economy of rival <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Western journalists got a rare glimpse of a closed society during the World Festival of Youth and Students, held July 1-8 in <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>. The meeting of 15,000 young people, most of them from left-leaning organizations, was the first major international event in the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> capital and the city was carefully prepared as a showcase. <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> had a well-scrubbed look of prosperity. Tree-lined avenues were festooned with banners and flags, and balconies of well-kept apartment buildings were draped with flowers. Stores in the capital, which foreign residents said usually were poorly stocked, bulged with goods and shoppers. Visitors were given tours of kindergartens with chandeliers and indoor swimming pools, of hospitals outfitted with new Japanese and West German equipment, of homes with color televisions and refrigerators. They found another, jarring, element everywhere: total control of the populace and the pervasive personality cult of President <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON>, the 77-year-old `` Great Leader,'' and `` Dear Leader'' <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>, his son and presumed successor. Above their hearts, North Koreans wear badges with the elder <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>'s portrait. Nearly every room of every office and home has a picture of the senior <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, and many have portraits of both Kims. Billboards and monuments recite and depict heroic deeds of the man who has led the North since the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> was divided in 1945, after the defeat of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in World War II. `` This is our happy land and it's all due to the Great Leader and the Dear Leader,'' said <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ho </PERSON> <PERSON> Sok </PERSON>, manager of a collective farm outside <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>. `` Some people call this Paradise on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>.'' Visitors heard the same statement again and again from other <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>, the national showcase, visitors see neat apartments of three or four rooms with central heating, hot water and basic appliances. The average factory worker is paid only about 100 won a month, $ 45 at the official rate, but enjoys free housing, education and medical care. Life is harder in the countryside. Many cottages do not have running water or private toilets, but in areas around the capital, stucco apartment buildings of two or three stories are being built to replace them. Several foreigners with extensive knowledge of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> said it has enormous problems. Many basic foods are rationed and, the foreigners said, the government often can not supply the average monthly meat allotment of 4.4 pounds per family. They said no fruit and few vegetables are available in winter. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Byong </PERSON> <PERSON> Hun </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Kim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Il </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, denied food was in short supply. He said the reason for rationing rice was to build up reserves to feed <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> after reunification. A foreigner who has made 18 visits to <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> said the government forces people to donate from their savings for the purpose, it says, of helping poor people in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. Some of the rules are difficult to fathom. Bicycles are banned in <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> even though cars are seldom seen on the broad boulevards. The few traffic lights at intersections were turned off. North Koreans said vehicles are scarce because the nation lacks petroleum deposits. This country's creed has become `` juche,'' a philosophy of self-reliance. Everyone does `` voluntary'' work for the government once a week. Tens of thousands were mobilized to help build stadiums and apartments when the North tried, in vain, to become co-host with the South of the 1988 Summer Olympics. The facilities were used for the youth festival. Where a person lives and works is not his business, but the state's. Although many homes have televisions, few have radios, apparently to prevent people from listening to foreign broadcasts. Several rural homes visited had wall loudspeakers used by local officials to broadcast instructions and ideological teachings. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has almost no private telephones. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Chol </PERSON> <PERSON> Sin </PERSON>, vice chairman of the Committee for Cultural Relations with <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION>, denied claims by <ORGANIZATION> Amnesty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> and other human rights groups that <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is a major abuser of human rights. In <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, `` everyone has housing and free medical care and there's no unemployment,'' he said. `` How can countries with unemployment criticize us for human rights?'' The regimen appears to accomplish its aim. Several students stopped randomly at <ORGANIZATION> Kim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Il </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> said they never would question government policy. `` In our country, students absolutely support the party,'' said Pak Song Ok, a 21-year-old studying the philosophy of `` juche.'' Economists said <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> will not follow other communist nations in experimenting with capitalist-style reform even though the growth rate is only 2 percent to 3 percent a year, compared to about 11 percent in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. `` We will not liberalize our economy and not put much stress on material incentives,'' said <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hwa </PERSON> <PERSON> Chon </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Kim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Il </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. He said workers receive some extra pay for exceeding quotas and farmers may grow vegetables in private plots around their homes, but the main rewards for hard work remain political: citations as model workers or appointments as deputies in local legislatures. The economist illustrated allegiance to the self-reliance creed by opening his shirt to show that even his T-shirt was a domestic product. Foreign debt has accumulated _ despite `` juche'' _ to somewhere between $ 5 billion and $ 8 billion, according to foreign observers. Dealing with <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is a gamble, one foreign businessman said, because the government sometimes pays bills promptly and sometimes neglects them. Another said his company accepts only barter deals or cash in advance. Other foreigners said <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> finances imported technology for factories and limousines for high officials by selling gold and other precious metals. In its hesitant opening to the oustside world, the government has enacted a joint venture law and begun several projects, mainly with communist countries or overseas Koreans. A 105-story, pyramid-shaped hotel now dominates the <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> skyline. It is to be finished in 1990 for what <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> hopes will be a flood of tourists with wads of foreign currency.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday July 23</NOTE>
