<FIRST>s i BC-NorthKorea-Leader Adv23   07-13 0715</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-North Korea-Leader, Adv 23,0734</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Kim Il Sung Is Father, Teacher and Saint to North Koreans</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-North Korea Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 He is the `` Great Leader'' whose deeds are praised, whose portrait and words are everywhere. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> has nearly deified himself in his self-made world of regimentation and mass obedience. President <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>, who is 77 and has ruled <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> since the peninsula was divided in 1945, has crafted an unmatched cult of personality. Four-year-olds at Changgwang Kindergarten in <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> sit around a detailed model of his birthplace, singing and chanting of his exploits. Children in another room carol, `` We wish good health and long life to <PERSON> Comrade </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshal </PERSON> <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON>.'' At a nearby middle school, a 15-year-old recites to her English class: `` Thanks to the Great Leader and the Dear Leader, we have no worries about food or housing and we all lead happy lives.'' The Dear Leader is the president's son and heir apparent, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Jong </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON>. A chair and desk in the library of <ORGANIZATION> Kim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Il </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> are a shrine, covered with a white cloth. <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> sat there during a visit to the university in 1970. Stuffed animals he donated fill a display room at the university, which also contains a shotgun the Great Leader provided so students could add to the collection. At the main entrance of every school, institution, store, office and factory is a larger-than-life portrait of <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> in appropriate context. Hospitals show him counseling doctors; schools portray him receiving the adulation of children; in bookstores, his image bends over weighty tomes. Visitors to a factory or school are told how <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> stood on a nearby hill to order it built, then provided `` on-the-spot guidance'' now and then. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Hung </PERSON> <PERSON> Son </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>'s largest textile mill said <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> had visited it 48 times. `` Only under the wise guidance of Great Leader <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON> have we achieved prosperity,'' he declared <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ho </PERSON> <PERSON> Sok </PERSON> of the Haksan collective farm outside <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> said <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> had visited 18 times to teach farmers which crops to grow and how to manage the enterprise. `` Parents only give children life, but the Great Leader takes care of all the people,'' he said. A huge stone monument that dominates the farm entrance is emblazoned with the words he uttered during his visits. Nearly every room of every home has a portrait of the Great Leader, often accompanied by one of the Dear Leader. Adults wear badges with <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON>'s picture just above the heart. From billboards and statues, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> observes the streets and subway stations of <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>. An Arch of Triumph replica 200 feet high honors his achievements as a young revolutionary. More than 40,000 people a day visit the shrine of Mangyongdae, the thatch-roofed farmhouse on <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>'s outskirts where <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> was born in 1912. Equal numbers go to the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Revolution </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Museum </LOCATION>, which has 100 rooms and 140,000 items relating to his revolutionary accomplishments. Accounts in the museum say <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>'s great-grandfather helped sink a `` <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pirate ship'' that was scouting possible invasion routes in 1866. They say his father was a leader in fighting the Japanese, who ruled <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> from 1910 to 1945, and died young after imprisonment and torture. The Great Leader himself, it is said, left home at 13 to join the resistance and founded <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s first Communist organization a year later. Works by and about <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> fill <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>'s bookstores. One volume is titled `` A Great Man.'' It begins by saying history has recorded the stories of many great men, but `` none can match those of General <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON>, genius of mankind produced by <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in the 20th century.'' His appearance in public can ignite a near-frenzy of celebration. At opening ceremonies of an international youth festival in <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON>'s arrival on his dais was the signal for fireworks to explode, doves to be released, trumpets to sound and thousands of Koreans to genuflect worshipfully. An economist, <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hwa </PERSON> <PERSON> Chon </PERSON>, was asked about the high cost of building memorials to the Great Leader and replied: `` We never count the money for monuments. The hearts of the <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> people built them.''
</TEXT>
