<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, July 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>North Korea: Regimentation on Grand Scale</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-North Korea Today</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PYONGYANG, North Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Expert precision singing or dancing by tens of thousands is no trick for <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> because regimentation, to them, is the story of life. An international youth festival opened with ceremonies involving 70,000 youngsters from the host country, including a dazzling display of rapidly changing pictures by 50,000 card flashers. Most of the 20 million citizens were mobilized to make sure communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s first major international event would be a success. Nearly everyone in <LOCATION> Pyongyang </LOCATION> helped build <LOCATION> Kwangbok </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, a high-rise apartment complex for 25,000 families, which was finished in two years and housed festival delegates. Office workers `` volunteer'' for public service work once a week. Kindergarten teachers initiate a lifelong course in patriotism, absolute loyalty to the system and reverence for President <PERSON> Kim </PERSON> <PERSON> Il </PERSON> <PERSON> Sung </PERSON>. Ideological training and service to the state dominate the education system. Workers have political study sessions at least once a week. Songs, books, television, movies and loudspeaker announcements beamed into homes reinforce the message. For those not convinced an entire nation could be trained to obey, the youth offered some examples: _ Thousands of pedestrians along the airport road waved whenever a carload of foreigners passed _ Several hundred folk dancers in a city square stopped dancing and applauded when told through the loudspeaker of a passing bus that it carried foreigners _ A foreigner entered a department store and one order from his North Korean interpreter opened a path in the crowd so the visitor could be served first _ Buses and military trucks took thousands of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Koreans </LOCATION> to each festival event to make sure all were well-attended _ When festival delegates rallied at a school against <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s suppression of pro-democracy students, about 1,000 North Koreans suddenly appeared and began dancing in the schoolyard, leaving no room for a
</TEXT>
