<HEAD>Sandinista Directorate Remains Intact</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Nicaragua 10 Years Later, b0515-516 of July 12</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The members of the Sandinista directorate have not changed since the overthrow of dictator <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> a decade ago. Their unity has surprised foreign diplomats, who had expected a split among the nine Commanders of the Revolution. No such problem has arisen, although some former guerrilla leaders and sympathizers have gone over to the anti-Sandinista resistance. Members of the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> directorate control the executive, legislature, police, army and other key posts. Some well-known officials, such as Vice President <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON> and Foreign Minister <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Escoto </PERSON>, are not among the nine. These are the directorate's members: _ <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, 43, president and likely Sandinista presidential candidate in general elections scheduled for Feb. 25 His leadership style _ hard work, and a decision-making process that is open to many opinions _ has done much to hold the directorate together. _ <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, 47, defense minister Opponents refer to `` the government of the <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> brothers,'' reflecting the widespread attitude that together _ as in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> and <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> in the same posts _ they represent the real power in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. _ <PERSON> Bayardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Arce </PERSON>, 39 As vice-coordinator of the Sandinista executive commission, <PERSON> Arce </PERSON> is <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>'s deputy for ideology. He is described as an ideological hard-liner and the main link between the Sandinistas and Salvadoran guerrillas. _ <PERSON> Tomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Borge </PERSON>, 58, the directorate's senior member, who helped found the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> in July 1961 and is known as a hard-liner As interior minister, he is in charge of police and state security. _ <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Carrion </PERSON>, 37, minister of economy, industry and commerce <PERSON> Carrion </PERSON> was born into one of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s wealthiest families. _ <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunez </PERSON>, 38, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, the unicameral legislature _ <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Hernandez </PERSON>, 49, minister of external cooperation since 1985 and planning minister before that _ <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Tirado </PERSON>, 49, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Tirado </PERSON>, born in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, joined the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> in 1963 and became a Nicaraguan citizen in September 1979. _ <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheelock </PERSON>, 42, agriculture minister and son of a wealthy landowning family
