<HEAD>Economists Predict Moderate Growth in '90</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy should n't fall into a recession any time soon but growth will continue to slow through 1990, making profits more elusive for some businesses, a private research group predicts. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>'s Economic Forum, which is made up of 15 economists, said Wednesday it expects slower economic growth to restrict productivity gains and raise production costs for many companies. In addition, the economists predicted the recent strengthening of the dollar, if sustained, could reduce prices and curtail demand for U.S.-produced internationally traded goods, the forum said. `` The combination of downward pressure on prices and upward pressure on costs makes lower profits inevitable,'' the forum said in a statement. `` How far corporate earnings are squeezed depends on the strength of economic activity.'' The forum, however, said it was not looking for a recession. The <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> group predicted tighter profit margins for the paper, chemicals and automobile industries. But it said the outlook was more encouraging for industries such as retail, apparel and textiles; packaged foods; petroleum; banks and thrifts; airlines and health care.
</TEXT>
