<HEAD>Comex Board Appoints New President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Staloff </PERSON>, a senior officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, has been named president and chief executive officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, the Comex announced. <PERSON> Staloff </PERSON>, 44, who also is president of the <ORGANIZATION> Philadelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, replaces eight-year veteran <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brody </PERSON>, who resigned at the end of June to pursue other business opportunities. <PERSON> Brody </PERSON> had been the youngest person ever to named to the presidency of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> futures exchange when he was appointed in 1981 at age 27. <ORGANIZATION> Comex </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanemann </PERSON> on Wednesday called <PERSON> Staloff </PERSON> `` a financial sector all-star.'' `` His record in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> is one of successful innovation and effective management ... from the creation of the world's first foreign currency option to the development of the <ORGANIZATION> Phildelphia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s computerized trading system,'' <PERSON> Hanemann </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Staloff </PERSON> worked for the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> exchange from 1971 to 1978, and again from 1980 to the present. The Comex is the world's most active metals futures market.
