<FIRST>r f PM-EEC-CompanyLaw     07-13 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-EEC-Company Law,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>European Commission Unveils New Draft Company Statute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> has unveiled a new draft European company statute aimed at easing business in the future single European market. The new draft, announced Wednesday, is a watered-down version of the initial proposal, which <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> had strongly opposed. <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Market </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Bangemann </PERSON> said, however, the statute aims to ensure that workers will be involved in corporate decision-making, although this had raised <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s main objection. `` There will be no European company without a definition of the place of workers in it, and in which way they participate in decisions,'' <PERSON> Bangemann </PERSON> said. The proposal, which has to be approved by the 12 member countries of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, gives companies the choice of creating a European company, <ORGANIZATION> Bangemann </ORGANIZATION> said, without forcing them to and without replacing national company statutes. Companies could create a European company through a merger, a holding company or a common subsidiary, provided that at least two of them have their headquarters in different member countries, <PERSON> Bangemann </PERSON> explained. The new proposal lowers the minimum capital of a European company to 100,000 European currency units, or around $ 110,000, to allow small and medium-sized companies to choose the new European statute. The draft also contains tax incentives by allowing companies to offset losses in one member country against profits in another, although <PERSON> Bangemann </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> did not want the provision to be reserved only for companies choosing a European statute. The provisions on employee participation would allow <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> countries, rather than companies, to choose which model to adopt. This is a change from an earlier proposal which gave companies the choice. The Commission, the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>'s executive body, is offering three options: appointing workers to supervisory boards following the West German example; workers' committees as used in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>; or other models chosen in consultation with the companies concerned. <PERSON> Bangemann </PERSON> said member countries could allow companies to choose between the three models or limit the choice to one model. He said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, for example, could limit the choice to the first option to remain in line with West German law.
</TEXT>
