<HEAD>TVA to Refinance $6.5 Billion in Treasury Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Authority </LOCATION>, operator of the nation's largest electric power system, said it will refinance $ 6.5 billion in debt to the federal <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> by issuing bonds in the public market for the first time in 15 years. The agency expects to save $ 100 million a year in interest costs by refinancing. Of <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>'s total $ 18.1 billion in long-term debt, $ 16.7 billion is held by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, an agency of the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, and the average interest rate on $ 6.5 billion of the debt is 12.25 percent, according to <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Malec </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> chief financial officer. <PERSON> Malec </PERSON> said Wednesday the agency expected to pay about a 9 percent average interest rate on the newly issued debt. <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION> said it was compelled to go to the public market to raise the money because the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> will not lend money for refinancing. <ORGANIZATION> TVA </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Knoxville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, provides electricity to about 8 million people in parts of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>.
