<SECOND>PM-Oil Drilling,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Approves Expansion of Protected Coastal Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An effort to sharply limit oil drilling off the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> coast, spurred by the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> disaster, is headed to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> with a strong voice of approval from the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>. The House on Wednesday approved the most extensive ban on offshore oil leasing of the decade, widely expanding prohibitions for one year against drilling off large portions of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> coasts. `` Those people who have allied themselves with the oil industry understand how dramatic a statement this is now,'' Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., said before the vote The one-year moratorium was part of the $ 11 billion <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> appropriation bill, which was approved 374-49. There was no separate vote on the oil leasing provision. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has not voted on the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> appropriation and several senators plan to introduce similar prohibitions. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration opposes the expanded prohibitions. Under the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> bill, leases for offshore oil drilling would be banned in areas off the coasts of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, a stretch of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> between <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> and, for the first time, off part of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s coast. The appropriations bill sets spending by the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and related agencies for fiscal 1990, and the provision prohibits appropriated money from being used to lease or approve oil drilling or exploration in the areas during the year. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> and other legislators are seeking to permanently ban drilling in some areas of the outer continental shelf. `` This moratorium will provide needed breathing room to enact the stronger safeguard I have proposed of a 10-year moratorium,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Courter </PERSON>, R-N.J. Support for limits on offshore oil exploration has grown since the March disaster in which the tanker Exxon Valdez spilled 1.6 million gallons of oil into the pristine Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> water off the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> coast. Smaller tanker accidents over one weekend last month spilled oil into water off the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> coasts. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the major industry trade group, called the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> vote `` a tragedy for our nation.'' `` In an emotional reaction to tanker oil spills, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> has taken an action that will inevitably boomerang,'' the institute said in a statement. `` Tanker traffic bringing imported oil into <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> waters will have to increase as domestic oil production continues to decline.'' In a June 29 letter to <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Appropriations leaders, administration budget director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> said the oil leasing provision and the bill's total budget, which is $ 2.45 billion more than <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> requested, are the main reasons the White House opposes the bill. The administration also objects to a `` buy <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' provision that requires offshore oil and gas rigs to be constructed with at least 50 percent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> labor and materials.
