<SECOND>BC-Japan-Pepsico,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pepsico Chairman Says ``Guerrilla Warfare'' Needed Against Coke</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Calloway </PERSON> said Thursday his firm needs to resort to guerrilla tactics to make an appreciable dent in <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>'s share of the Japanese soft drink market <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> dominates <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s cola market with a 92 percent share, compared with <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION>'s 6 percent, according to food and beverage industry statistics. `` When you have as strong a share as <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>, that calls for guerrilla warfare,'' <PERSON> Calloway </PERSON> said. That means `` chipping away at the convenience store chains, store by store, vending machine by vending machine,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> also owns the <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION>, Pizza Hut and <ORGANIZATION> Taco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> restaurant chains, and the snack food company Frito Lay. <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cola </ORGANIZATION> has been successful in other countries, such as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, where it has 21 bottling plants and contracts for 20 more. But gaining market share in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> `` is trench warfare, store by store, pizza by pizza. It's that kind of business,'' <PERSON> Calloway </PERSON> told reporters over a hotel-catered lunch of consomme <PERSON> Mille </PERSON> <PERSON> Fanti </PERSON> and filet steak au poivre. <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> was a sponsor for the worldwide tour of pop superstar <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who performed in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> in 1987 and 1988. Those visits boosted <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cola </ORGANIZATION> sales in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> briefly to 12-15 percent of the cola market, but they fell back each time. `` <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> says <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is its most profitable market,'' <PERSON> Calloway </PERSON> said. `` That says you're up against a pretty formidable force.'' He said problems remain with brand recognition and the complex Japanese distribution system. `` We're not going to go out and do something crazy,'' he said. `` There is no silver bullet, no bomb we can drop.'' But he said <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> would keep up steady efforts at market penetration, including increasing local retail outlets and investing in vending machines. <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> also is expanding into non-carbonated drinks such as fruit juices, sports drinks and coffee, <PERSON> Calloway </PERSON> said. `` We're not the market leader so we ca n't afford to do a lot of advertising and marketing. We have to do it in a controlled manner. If I went out and matched <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION>'s spending here, unless you have the distributors and the vendors, it wo n't help.'' <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION>'s other ventures in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> have fared better. <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION>, a joint venture with the trading giant <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, has cornered 98 percent of this country's fried chicken market, according to <PERSON> Shinsuke </PERSON> <PERSON> Ohkawara </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION>, who accompanied <PERSON> Calloway </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fried </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicken </ORGANIZATION> has 834 outlets in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, the largest Western-style restaurant chain in this country, and projected sales of $ 863 million this year, <PERSON> Ohkawara </PERSON> said. By the end of the year <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> will have 18,000 restaurants worldwide, the largest restaurant chain in the world, and directly own or operate 40 percent of them, with the rest franchises or joint ventures, <PERSON> Calloway </PERSON> said. By contrast, the McDonald's fast-food chain has some 11,000 outlets worldwide, with 20 percent of them directly operated, he said.
