<HEAD>Midway Expansion May Open Jobs For Striking Eastern Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An expansion of <ORGANIZATION> Midway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, which is trying to acquire jets, routes and gates from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, may provide jobs for strike-weary workers, the chairman of the Chicago-based carrier said. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON>, Midway chairman and chief executive officer, said Wednesday the carrier should sign a $ 206.5 million agreement next week for 16 Eastern planes, two Canadian routes and 13 gates at <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, which Midway plans to develop into its East Coast hub. By the mid-1990s, <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON> said Midway hopes to have more than 1,000 employees in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> and operate routes from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. `` The former <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> workers are high-quality professionals that we would give top priority to hire under the appropriate circumstances,'' said <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON> in a visit to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, where Midway operates its principal maintenance facilities. Midway has hired nine former <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots since machinists, pilots and flight attendants at the Miami-based airline went on strike March 4. The Midway deal is part of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s strategy to significantly downsize operations from its pre-strike level of more than 1,000 flights. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifland </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> must approve the agreement. Eastern, which filed for bankruptcy protection March 9, has already sold its profitable Northeast Shuttle to billionaire <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> for $ 365 million and has announced plans to sell at least 20 more jets. While Eastern considers relocating its headquarters to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON> said Midway's expansion plans could more than double flights into <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. If the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> deal is approved, Midway may have up to five flights a day to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON>. The airline, which acquired bankrupt <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> as it expanded to a national carrier during the past decade, also holds several of <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION>'s former Latin American and <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> routes, which <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON> said may be used after the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> hub is established. Midway currently flies via <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Nassau </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bahamas </LOCATION>, and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virgin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> service would put Midway in direct competition with <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, the Northeast's largest carrier, which first sought <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> gates and routes. `` <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> is a formidable competitor and we have our work cut out for us to move into their territory,'' <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON>, who predicted more airline bankruptcies before the industry settles, said the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> expansion will be steady but not overly aggressive. `` We're generally a conservative company,'' said <PERSON> Hinson </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> co-pilot. `` We are not out to roll the dice.'' Often dubbed `` the darling of deregulation,'' Midway was the first carrier chartered after government control of the industry ended in 1979 and began as a small <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> carrier catering to full-fare business travelers. By the early 1980s, it was losing more than $ 20 million annually and began courting regular passengers soon after acquiring <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> in late 1984. Midway operates more than 220 regular and commuter flights to 51 cities from <LOCATION> Midway </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> south of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The carrier inaugurated <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> service this spring and made a $ 900 million order for 37 jets from <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> with an option for 37 more. For the first quarter, Midway reported record earnings of $ 2.9 million, but profits have been erratic in recent years, dropping more than 40 percent last year. On Wednesday, Midway announced a tentative labor agreement with the Teamsters, representing more than 450 mechanics, stock clerks and aircraft cleaners.
