<SECOND>PM-Shuttle Ads,0414</SECOND>
<HEAD>Five Companies in Running for Soviet Space Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Five <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies are vying to place ads costing more than $ 1 million on the side of a Soviet space shuttle scheduled for launch next month, according to a company with exclusive rights to sell the advertising. San Francisco-based Soviet-Pacific Enterprises would only identify the five as a major oil company, a television network, an international courier, a consumer-goods produce and a food company. The ads, printed on thin plastic-like film stuck on the spaceship with an adhesive, will disintegrate within 45 seconds of launch because of the heat generated as the craft cuts through the earth's atmosphere Talks with the five companies are now in the final stages, said <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, marketing director for Soviet-Pacific. `` But we're looking for just one sponsor,'' he said. <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON> said his company does n't want the space ship to `` look like an <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> 500 race car with 500 different advertisements.'' For a payment estimated at more than $ 1 million, the company that is picked will be allowed to place two 10-by-21-foot signs on the side of the Soyuz shuttle, scheduled for launch Aug. 30. It also can display its corporate logo or advertisements around the Baikonur launch site and send a camera crew to film the August lift-off. The Soviet space agency, Glavkosmos, and <PERSON> Licensintorg </PERSON>, the commercial-space and licensing agency in the <ORGANIZATION> USSR </ORGANIZATION>, have imposed only one restriction, said <PERSON> Hollis </PERSON>. They wo n't allow sponsorship by liquor or tobacco companies. More than 100 million people in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> are expected to view a live broadcast of the blastoff, presenting an ideal opportunity to a company that wants to introduce a new product in that nation. Less than 45 seconds might seem short for a million dollars, but a company spokesman pointed out that a 60-second spot during a Super Bowl broadcast costs more than that. Glavkosmos has signed commerical agreements with several Western companies. In March, a Japanese televison network paid the agency $ 12 million for the right to send a correspondent into space in 1991. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, which administers the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space program, does not accept advertising or payment from private citizens for flights. In the past, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space shuttles have carried some projects for a fee, but that practice was canceled after the Challenger explosion in 1986 that killed seven astronauts.
