<HEAD>EEC Clears Film Distribution Venture of U.S. Film Makers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> commission </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it had cleared a film distribution venture by three <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies after they agreed to amend their pact to comply with <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> antitrust rules. The commission said that the agreement between <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> MGM-UA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> to create a joint venture, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pictures </ORGANIZATION>, to distribute their films in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> had contained exclusivity clauses which restricted competition. These clauses were changed so that the venture now only has the right of first refusal on the parent companies' films. This means that if <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> chooses not to distribute a film, the parent company could distribute it on its own or through a third party. The companies also agreed to maintain `` appropriate records'' and to establish an arbitration procedure to solve problems such as film allocation and access to screen space, the commission said. The commission's clearance lasts for five years, after which it will review the companies' agreement. It said the changes to the agreement were designed to ensure that the parent companies remained autonomous and that the films were distributed as widely as possible.
