<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oats </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> plans to lay off more than 550 workers nationwide by next spring, the company says. An <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> pet food plant that employs 390 people will be closed by next spring, and 170 management workers nationwide will be laid off in the next few weeks, <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement Wednesday. The management layoffs will trim 42 employees from <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> headquarters The rest of the cuts will be among sales, manufacturing and distribution workers in the company's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grocery products division, said spokesman <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Botrell </PERSON>. The layoffs were announced to employees Wednesday, <PERSON> Botrell </PERSON> said. The company said in a statement that the plant in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, which produces Ken-L-Ration and Puss-N-Boots dog and cat foods, will be closed in phases between the end of this year and next spring `` It's always difficult to make these types of decisions when it affects loyal and dedicated employees,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Smithburg </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive, said in a statement. `` But for competitive reasons, we felt it necessary to take these steps.'' <ORGANIZATION> Quaker </ORGANIZATION> said the actions would force the company to take a one-time charge of $ 104 million, or 80 cents per share. A change in accounting methods for grocery products inventories will force another 20 - to 25-cent-per-share charge Those charges, coupled with a $ 21 million, 20-cent-per-share loss by the European pet foods group mean the company will take losses of more than $ 1.20 per share in the fiscal year ended June 30. The company said the plant closing was due to declining popularity of semi-moist and canned pet foods made in <LOCATION> Marion </LOCATION>. The products will continue to be made at plants in <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and in <LOCATION> Lawrence </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kan </PERSON>. The company also announced that <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marineau </PERSON> had been appointed to the post of executive vice president for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grocery products. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Callahan </PERSON> will take <PERSON> Marineau </PERSON>'s old position as executive vice president for international grocery products.
