<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> today reported a 14 percent increase in its second-quarter profit, partly reflecting good returns from investments in its soft drink operations, bottling joint ventures and marketing. <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> said its after-tax income came to $ 345.5 million, or 98 cents a share, in 1989's second quarter, up from $ 303.1 million, or 82 cents a share, in the same period a year earlier. Revenue for the latest quarter rose 5 percent to $ 2.4 billion from $ 2.3 billion. International shipments of concentrate and syrup continued to grow at a greater rate than domestic shipments, <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> reported. Concentrate and syrup shipments outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> advanced 15 percent for the quarter, compared to 3 percent at home. The biggest jump was in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, for which the company credited successful marketing activities in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and continued infrastructure development combined with the increased affordability of Coca-Cola products in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. In the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the company said, growth was led by the continued momentum of its diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> and caffeine-free diet <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> brands. `` Our investment in bottling joint ventures, soft drink infrastructure, and marketing continue to provide substantial worldwide volume, market share and profit gains,'' <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goizueta </PERSON> said in a news release. `` These investments produce consistently attractive returns and support our expectations for strong bottom-line performance for the remainder of the year,'' <PERSON> Goizueta </PERSON> said. For the first half of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Coke </ORGANIZATION>'s income was $ 605.3 million, or $ 1.70 a share, which was a 17.9 percent increase over $ 513.6 million, or $ 1.39 a share, in the first six months of 1988. Revenue rose 5.5 percent to $ 4.4 billion in the first half from $ 4.2 billion a year earlier.
