<SECOND>BC-EEC-Compact Discs,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Slaps Provisional Anti-dumping Duties On Asian Compact Disc Players</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Thursday imposed provisional anti-dumping duties on imports of compact disc players from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> because they may threaten the survival of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> industry. The duties, which range from 6.4 percent to 33.9 percent, hit major Japanese consumer electronics companies including <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sanyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Matsushita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Major South Korean companies affected include <ORGANIZATION> Goldstar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Samsung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION> The duties, which take effect next week but must be ratified by the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION> within three months, followed a two-year investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> after it received a complaint by the main <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> producers of compact disc players. These are NV Philips of the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bang </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Olufsen of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Grundig </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. In a statement, the commission said that the CD player imports `` seriously held back the development of the Community industry, the main inventor and the major developer of the product.'' It added that most of the Japanese and all of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> companies involved `` adopted marketing and pricing policies in clear violation'' of international trading rules on dumping, or selling at below market price. The commission calculates whether dumping occurs by comparing the price on the exporter's domestic market with the price charged in the 12-nation trade bloc. The commission said that it found CD player dumping `` margins'' of between 1.54 percent and 45.54 percent in the case of the Japanese exports and of between 20.1 percent and 32.5 percent for the Korean exports. It said that the low prices of the imports caused `` an important price depression'' which resulted in `` severe'' losses for <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> producers, which lost about 30 percent of their annual revenue. The EEC inquiry covered the period June 1, 1986 to May 31, 1987, although sales of the players started in 1984. The commission did not give a total value of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> market for CD players although it said that the imports in 1987, which made up about two-thirds of the market, were valued at 300 million European currency units, or about $ 33 million. Imports surged 23-fold to about 2.3 million units in 1987 from 97,924 units in 1984 of which more than 90 percent came from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. This compared with a fivefold increase in <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> producers' sales, the commission said. It did not give figures for sales by <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> producers. The market share of Japanese and South Korean exporters rose to more than 75 percent in 1987 from just under 50 percent in 1984, while the share of the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> industry fell from more than 50 percent to 18 percent in 1987, the commission said. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> investigated 14 producers of CD players but imposed duties on 11 of them. The duties on the companies are as follows: <ORGANIZATION> Matsushita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industrial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 33.9 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Pioneer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 28.8 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Sanyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 27.8 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Yamaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 23.7 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Victor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> -LRB- JVC -RRB-, 20.9 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Kenwood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 19.3 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 17.5 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 15.9 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Onkyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 8.5 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Funai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 8.4 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Teac </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 6.4 percent. Duties also were imposed on four South Korean companies: <ORGANIZATION> Inkel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 20.1 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Goldstar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 32.5 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Samsung </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 23 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Haitai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 21.3 percent. An official, who asked not to be named, at <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belgium </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NV </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION>'s Belgian subsidiary, said that <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION> was not so concerned by the duties because its factory in <LOCATION> Colmar </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> had been producing between 75 percent and 80 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION>'s CD players for the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> market since 1988. He said that the factory was not established to avoid paying duties but was in line with <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION>'s policy of making products in the company's local markets. <ORGANIZATION> NV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philips </ORGANIZATION> was unavailable for comment.
