<HEAD>Honda Car Company to Invest in Britain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the Japanese carmaker, will invest 300 million pounds, or $ 486 million, in a new plant in southwest <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> that will create 1,300 new jobs, Industry Secretary Lord <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> will extend its engine plant in <LOCATION> Swindon </LOCATION>, southwest <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, to a full car manufacturing plant capable of producing 100,000 cars a year, <PERSON> Young </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lords </ORGANIZATION>. The new plant is part of an arrangement in which <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> will take a 20-percent stake in <ORGANIZATION> Rover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, the British carmaker with which it has had joint ventures over the last 10 years. <PERSON> Rover </PERSON> said it will acquire 20 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s manufacturing operation in <LOCATION> Swindon </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> and other Japanese carmakers have expressed an interest in expanding in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> ahead of 1992 when the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> becomes a barrier-free market. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement brings the total investment commitments in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> by the three major Japanese car companies to 1.8 billion pounds, or $ 2.9 billion. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the new plant is to begin manufacturing at the end of 1991, `` with a limited volume of <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> cars,'' which will substitute for imports from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> on the European market. `` One year later, a full range of production operations will start with output rising rapidly to 100,000 cars -LRB- per year -RRB- in 1994,'' <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said. He said this will include cars built for the <ORGANIZATION> Rover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, with which <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> has had various joint ventures for 10 years. Rover will continue to build cars for <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> at its plant in <LOCATION> Longbridge </LOCATION>, northwest of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON>, chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Rover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, said the deal with <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> `` will help both companies, while preserving their separate identities, to develop long-term strategies to meet the demands of an increasingly global market.'' <ORGANIZATION> Rover </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> is owned by <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, which bought the former state-owned carmaker from the government in July 1988. Young called <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement a `` vote of confidence'' in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and said it signaled a `` renaissance of the <LOCATION> U.K. </LOCATION> motor industry.''
