<HEAD>Big Three Car and Truck Sales Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMs version planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales of the Big Three automakers' cars and light trucks rose 8.9 percent in early July compared with last year when incentives had been rolled back and sales fell from a torrid June rate, the companies said Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said they sold vehicles at an average daily rate of 33,504 during the July 1-10 period this year compared with a rate of 30,766 during the same time last year. Car sales were up 10.3 percent and truck sales were 6.8 percent higher. The sales rate during June last year was particularly strong, even for what proved to be the second-best sales year in auto history. But the incentives that spurred those deals began coming off in early July 1988. This year, incentives are available, but they are n't catching as many consumers' eyes. In fact, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> this week boosted customer and dealer incentives in an effort to shrink swollen inventories of 1989 cars as the model year enters its last three months. While the sales news for the early July period was good, it brought the automakers' sales so far this year only a little closer to last year's pace. Through July 10 this year, the Big Three had sold 5.9 percent fewer cars and trucks this year than last year, falling to a daily rate of 35,308 vehicles from 37,524 last year. Car sales were off 7.8 percent for the year and light truck sales were down 2.6 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> was the only one of the Big Three to post a car sales decline during early July, as sales dropped to a daily rate of 2,921 this year, 5.8 percent lower than the 3,100 daily rate a year ago. For the calendar year, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales were down 14.6 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s trucks sold at a rate 1.6 percent higher in early July this year than they did a year ago. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s truck sales were down 0.7 percent. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> posted an 11.3 percent gain in car sales, going to a daily rate of 10,615 during early July this year compared with a rate of 9,534 during the same time last year. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales for the year were down 9 percent from last year's level. The company's truck sales ran 13.2 percent ahead of last year's pace in early July but were down 2.8 percent for the entire year <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> posted the heftiest gain in car sales, rising to a daily rate of 6,923 during early July this year, up 16.9 percent from the 5,919 car-a-day rate during the same time last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales so far this year were running 2.5 percent behind last year's pace On the truck side, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> dealers were selling 3.6 percent more vehicles in early July this year over last year, but 3.8 percent fewer so far during the year.
