<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Italian Firm Denies It Attempted to Corner Soybean Market, Sues CBOT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Tops with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Ferruzzi subsidiaries filing
lawsuit against exchange. Picks up 2nd graf pvs, ``Soybean futures ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two subsidiaries of an Italian agribusiness giant today filed a federal lawsuit seeking to block further implementation of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s order limiting soybean futures holdings, a CBOT official said. The lawsuit was filed against the exchange in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmichael </PERSON>, CBOT spokesman. He said the exchange would `` vigorously'' fight the lawsuit. The parent of the two firms, <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, has denied it attempted to corner the soybean market, charging instead that a <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s order calling for liquidation of large positions in the exchange's July contract `` undermines the reliability'' of such contracts. Soybean futures rebounded moderately in early trading today. Analysts said the buying was a reaction to a government report released late Wednesday that indicated spring soybean plantings were below expectations. Exchange spokesman <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmichael </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> order was issued late Tuesday to correct a wide disparity between the number of contracts outstanding and the actual supply of soybeans available. In a statement released Wednesday in <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ferruzi </PERSON> said its `` accumulation of beans was undertaken so that the group could assure the uninterrupted operation of its processing plants ... and to satisfy export commitments, particularly to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>.'' `` All actions taken by the group were within accepted practices, and the emergency order ... was taken in disregard to the true economics of the marketplace,'' the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s leading grain trader, said it had been accumulating soybeans openly in compliance with CBOT rules because last year's drought could have caused a shortage, but it did not say how much it had bought. The statement also said the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> action would `` undermine the reliability of the contracts'' of the Board of Trade. In <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>, the state agriculture commissioner on Wednesday asked the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to investigate whether any Board of Trade officials benefited from the emergency order. Commissioner <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said a drop in soybean prices would benefit those holding `` short'' positions, or obligations to sell soybeans. `` It is possible that some of the members of the board of directors who made this order held short positions and benefited greatly from this order,'' <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sessions </PERSON>. Soybeans are used for products ranging from tofu and cooking oil to cosmetics and animal feed. Activity in the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> soybean pit, the world's largest for that commodity, was heaviest at the beginning and end of the session Wednesday as traders tried to sort rumors from facts. A <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> soybean trader said the late sale Wednesday of 3 million to 4 million bushels by a large brokerage near the close of trading helped soybeans close 39 -LCB- cents down on the day at $ 6.86 -LCB- a bushel. The trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said that sale had all the earmarks of a foreign firm moving to comply with the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION>'s emergency liquidation order. One of the reasons for the midday trading lull, according to several traders, was a report that a <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary in <LOCATION> Belle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Chasse </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La. </LOCATION>, planned to ask a federal court for a restraining order against the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> action. Spokesman <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary declined to comment on the report. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>'s holdings in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> include <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION>, a grain elevator and land. <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmichael </PERSON> said the exchange's board of directors issued the order to liquidate large soybean positions to correct a wide disparity between the number of contracts being held for deliverable supplies of the product and the actual supply of soybeans available. <PERSON> Carmichael </PERSON> refused to comment on whether the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION>'s effort was designed to break up any firm's attempt to corner the market. A number of traders and analysts compared the soybean market situation to an alleged effort by the Hunt brothers of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> a decade ago to corner the world silver market. But others doubted such extensive manipulation of the soybean market had taken place. The exchange ordered all traders holding commitments to buy or sell more than 3 million bushels of soybeans for delivery this month to reduce those positions by at least 20 percent each trading day through July 20, when the July contract expires. The emergency resolution said no trader may control more than 3 million bushels of July soybeans at the close of trading Tuesday, and no trader may control more than 1 million bushels by the contract's expiration two days later. Futures are binding contracts to buy or sell a set amount of a commodity at an agreed-upon price at a later date. A typical corner occurs when a trader holding a large number of buy contracts also owns so much of the commodity that sellers can not acquire enough to honor their delivery commitments. The artificial supply squeeze causes the commodity's price to soar until the trader working the corner sells out at a huge profit. The <ORGANIZATION> Sun-Times </ORGANIZATION> also quoted unidentified sources saying the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> action stemmed in part from complaints by <PERSON> Archer </PERSON> <PERSON> Daniels </PERSON> <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, Ill.-based agribusiness giant. <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Burket </PERSON> said the company had no comment Wednesday. A trading source who insisted on anonymity told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> that the situation began as a battle between <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> for export business. `` <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> was smart enough to cover itself by getting supplies from the cash market and the futures market,'' he said. `` ADM relied almost entirely on the futures market. When supplies got tight, <ORGANIZATION> ADM </ORGANIZATION> had to go to the cash market to satisfy export demands and the tighter the supply, the higher the premium they paid.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which regulates the futures industry, said Wednesday in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that it had been monitoring the soybean market for several months. But it would not comment on whether an investigation was under way into any attempt to corner the soybean market.
