<HEAD>Japanese Pessimistic About Business in China, But Will Stay</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Stands for AM-China-Japan Business on Business News Digest.
Also moving on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Japanese businessmen and trade officials see dismal prospects for investment in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the coming year, and dispute suggestions <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> may profit from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s current political maladies. Fears that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> will take advantage of the flight of other foreign businesses to tighten its grip on the <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> market are unfounded, said one Japanese trade office manager. `` It's a big misunderstanding'' said the official, who like other Japanese interviewed spoke on condition he not be identified. He said that since the June 3-4 military assault on pro-democracy protesters in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, not one trade delegation from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has passed through his office. After the attack, there was a mass exodus of foreigners, including the Japanese. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> warned its businessmen against a quick return, saying it would give the impression of a `` thief at a fire'' _ someone profiting from another's misfortune. About half the 1,000 Japanese based in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> have returned and more are expected back in the coming week. Most however, have come mainly to settle accounts or fulfill existing contracts, one of them said. A few companies may eventually reduce their staff here, he said. `` No one will increase'' their Japanese employees. <ORGANIZATION> Matsushita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Naomi </PERSON> <PERSON> Haga </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> that an official opening planned for late July for a joint venture that has begun producing color TV sets was now `` impossible.'' `` <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> is under martial law, and the Japanese government urged Japanese to leave the country,'' he said. `` We ca n't give the project up ... It would violate the contract. But it's dangerous to be there now, and we do n't have enough Japanese at the site to keep it on schedule.'' <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s Prime Minister Sousuke Uno has said economic sanctions wo n't be imposed on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> has stopped high-level contacts and put off discussions on $ 5.8 billion in official development loans <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is to provide <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for the 1990-95 period. More important, said an embassy official in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, Japanese companies wo n't be investing in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in the near future because of an erosion of trust in the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> government. `` Even if martial law is lifted, the government has already lost too much credibility,'' he said. He said Chinese companies will have increasing difficulties borrowing money on the world market. One Japanese securities firm has put off lending $ 100 million to southern <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Guangdong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The embassy official said Japanese companies, much criticized by <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for their reluctance to invest in projects, had finally decided the time was right after former Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> signed an investment protection agreement in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in August. Since then, more than $ 100 million in investment had been pledged. But <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s recent crackdown on political dissent, and fears the arbitrary use of force could some day be applied to the foreign business community, `` have thrown cold water'' on future investment plans, he said. So far, no one is talking about leaving. `` It's too early for such a decision,'' said <PERSON> Kazuhiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeda </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Japan-China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> and Trade in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. `` Most companies are watching the conditions, seeing what direction the Chinese government takes.'' Those already in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> wo n't give up, he said, but for at least a year there will be few newcomers, he said. Short-term prospects also were poor for trade between <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and its biggest trading partner outside <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>. Last year trade volume reached a nearly balanced $ 19.3 billion, and expectations were it would top $ 20 billion this year. In the first five months of 1989, trade was up 15 percent to $ 8.2 billion. But the political chaos, coming on top of a faltering economy, has put many Chinese companies in a serious economic pinch. Japanese steelmakers temporarily suspended shipments to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> because they could n't get letters of credit from Chinese banks. Chinese companies ca n't get funds for raw materials because of the government's tough austerity policies that have dried up credit. The diplomat said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> can finally produce the quality light industrial goods and silk that <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> demands, but now ca n't deliver the goods because of transportation, supply and energy problems. He said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s trade surplus is likely to grow again, although <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> may move to cut back imports as its exports tail off. He said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> has exhausted most of its investment possibilities in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and other <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> countries, and Japanese companies looking for ways to spend their money still consider <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> the top candidate in the long run. But every Japanese interviewed stressed that `` caution'' will be the guiding principle. `` The Chinese say there will be no change in their open-door policy but at the same time they are criticizing capitalism,'' the trade official said. `` For the time being, we'll have to wait and watch.
