<FIRST>a f BC-HormelBooks Adv17 1stLd-Writethru 07-13 1016</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hormel Books, Adv 17, 1st Ld-Writethru,1043</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday July 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Books Recount Bitter Hormel Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS `this month' to June in 6th graf</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BAENEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Geo </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> A. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hormel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> meatpackers were threatening to strike nearly four years ago, two reporters bet on how long the strike would last. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Klauda </PERSON> said more than 10 days. <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Hage </PERSON> said one day or less, thinking the strike would never happen. `` I thought they would realize before they came to the brink that the strike would be a failure and that they would n't strike,'' <PERSON> Hage </PERSON> said. He was wrong. The bitter strike in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Minn. </LOCATION>, lasted for months and provided <PERSON> Hage </PERSON> and <PERSON> Klauda </PERSON>, both reporters for the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>, with enough drama to fill a nearly 400-page book. `` No Retreat, No Surrender: Labor's War at <ORGANIZATION> Hormel </ORGANIZATION>,'' published in June by <ORGANIZATION> William </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morrow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is one of several books about the strike due on the market this year `` There were so many strands that went beyond just a normal labor-management fight. It was n't just another strike,'' said <PERSON> Klauda </PERSON>, who teamed with <PERSON> Hage </PERSON> to follow the battle for the <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION>. The walkout's intriguing ingredients included the presence of a Fortune 500 company in a small southern <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> town; the half-century of labor peace <PERSON> Hormel </PERSON> had enjoyed; the benign history of the <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> union, which struck for three days in 1933; and the local's hiring of flamboyant union consultant <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, known for organizing <PERSON> J.P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> textile mills in the South and, more recently, helping <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> strikers in their battle with management. `` You just stumbled across one great story after another,'' said <PERSON> Hage </PERSON>. `` And there just was n't time to go back and revisit those people to explore a certain accusation or to get to know a certain person better, because tomorrow or Sunday there's always another news story to write.'' For a time, the strike was one of the nation's top labor stories. While other plants in the <ORGANIZATION> Hormel </ORGANIZATION> chain agreed to wage concessions, workers in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> decided to fight a proposed wage cut. More than 1,400 union members walked off their jobs on Aug. 17, 1985. Local P-9 of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commercial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> objected to a profitable company imposing a wage cut; <PERSON> Hormel </PERSON> said the cut was needed for the company to stay competitive. Since the strike ended, the maker of Spam luncheon meat, Cure 81 ham and <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Label </ORGANIZATION> bacon has reported two consecutive years of record earnings, continuing a five-year stretch of increasing profits. Hage and <PERSON> Klauda </PERSON> said the strike symbolized worker anxiety about concessions in the 1980s. But they concluded it failed to turn the tide, partly because events in a town of 23,000 were n't going to reverse nationwide economic forces. `` You're not going to overturn the high unemployment rate,'' <PERSON> Hage </PERSON> said. `` You're not going to overturn all these trends in the meatpacking industry that involve non-union competitors and falling red-meat consumption.'' In their book, <PERSON> Hage </PERSON> and <PERSON> Klauda </PERSON> trace the roots of the strike, the first against <PERSON> Hormel </PERSON> since the <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> walkout 52 years before. The reporters found it ironic that <PERSON> Hormel </PERSON>, with a history of good labor relations and innovations such as profit-sharing dating to the 1930s, was the target of such bitterness. They also were fascinated by <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON>, the young P-9 president elected on a no-concessions platform. <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON> and other local officers were suspended by the <ORGANIZATION> UFCW </ORGANIZATION> international union, which took control of P-9 for refusing to end the strike and negotiated a settlement ratified in September 1986. The trusteeship has since been lifted and new local officers elected. In <LOCATION> Klauda </LOCATION>'s view, the uncompromising <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON> was driven `` the same way someone would be driven to go serve in a Third World country, -LRB- in -RRB- some kind of humanitarian way.'' <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON> now works for a hospital and health-care workers union in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>. `` I was after a fair and decent contract that people could work under,'' said in an interview. `` A safe place to work. A place where you did n't have to raise your hand to go to the bathroom. That's all I was after.'' Five months after the strike began, <PERSON> Hormel </PERSON> reopened the plant and began hiring replacement workers. The company was flooded by applicants and former strikers who crossed the picket line. Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON> called out the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to maintain order at the plant. One of those hired as a replacement worker was <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fahey </PERSON>, whose book on the strike, `` Packing It In! The Hormel Strike 1985-86,'' was published in April by <ORGANIZATION> Kirwin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paul </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Fahey </PERSON> concludes <PERSON> Hormel </PERSON> was the wrong target for a meatpackers strike and that <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON> was on an `` ego trip.'' `` <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON> had a very strong ego, and he ran into another ego just as strong: <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Knowlton </PERSON> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Hormel </ORGANIZATION>'s president, board chairman and chief executive officer -RRB-,'' <PERSON> Fahey </PERSON> said. `` Thing was, <PERSON> Knowlton </PERSON> had more horses.'' Another book, `` On Strike at <ORGANIZATION> Hormel </ORGANIZATION>,'' takes a pro-strike side and offers an insider's account, according to its author, <PERSON> Hardy </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>. The book will be published this fall by <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Green </PERSON> worked for <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>' New York-based Corporate Campaign and was in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> for much of the strike. He disputes claims that <PERSON> Guyette </PERSON> was on a `` power trip.'' `` Anyone who was in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> could see this was not the strike of one person,'' he said. `` It could never be the strike of one person leading a bunch of zombies, because these people went all over the country.'' Three years since the strike ended, there are signs that wounds are healing in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Hormel </PERSON> has notified 35 of 442 former strikers on a preferential hiring list that they will be called back to work by July 24. The company also held an employee appreciation picnic in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION> that attracted more than 5,000. But some scars remain. `` You almost wonder whether some day grandkids are going to look back and say, ` Which side were you on?''' <PERSON> Hage </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
