<SECOND>BC-Earns-Banks,0583</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chemical, Bank of New York Report 2nd Quarter Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday reported static earnings for the second quarter while profits at the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> more than doubled as the result of its acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> late last year. At <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION>, income gains were offset by higher expenses and a slump in bond trading profits. For the quarter ended June 30, <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> reported net income of $ 128.6 million, up 0.7 percent from $ 127.7 million in the year-ago period. Earnings per share fell 16.7 percent from $ 1.98 a year ago to $ 1.65 in the second quarter because of an increase in the number of common shares outstanding. Chemical issued 7 million shares in December. Net interest income totaled $ 565 million, down 5 percent from $ 595.1 million. Chemical attributed the decrease to $ 4.4 billion lower average earning assets resulting from the divestiture of certain businesses and assets. Non-interest income, including fees for trust and other banking services, totaled $ 252.2 million, up 12.6 percent from $ 223.9 million a year ago. Provision for loan losses totaled $ 90.9 million, which includes $ 45 million loaned to countries that are rescheduling their debt. A year ago, <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION>'s loan-loss provision amounted to $ 95.8 million. Chemical said profits from foreign exchange trading totaled a record $ 51.5 million during the quarter, but trading account activities lost $ 1.8 million, compared with a $ 25.7 million profit a year ago. For the first six months, <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> said net income totaled $ 246.5 million, down 3 percent from $ 253.2 million in the first half of 1988. Earnings per share totaled $ 3.14, down from $ 3.93. Net interest income totaled $ 1.16 billion for the first two quarters, down from $ 1.17 billion a year ago. Non-interest income rose 14.4 percent to $ 497.8 million from $ 435 million a year ago. Total assets amounted to $ 75.9 billion at the end of the second quarter, compared with $ 75.8 billion a year ago. At the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, net income for the second quarter totaled $ 114.3 million, up 130 percent from $ 49.7 million a year ago. The jump reflects the November 1988 acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Irving </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Earnings per share on a fully diluted basis amounted to $ 1.55, up from $ 1.30 a year ago. Chairman <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> <PERSON> Bacot </PERSON> noted in a statement that the bank experienced strong growth in all major commercial lending areas during the second quarter. He also noted that `` cost savings arising from the merger are being realized sooner than anticipated.'' Net interest income totaled $ 327.5 million, up 84 percent from $ 177.8 million a year ago. Non-interest income, bolstered by loan syndication fees and credit card fees totaled $ 230.8 million, compared with $ 119.4 a year ago. Allowances for loan losses totaled $ 919.3 million at the end of the second quarter, compared with $ 31.9 million a year ago. The bank reported a $ 30.6 million charge-off related to its non-performing Argentine debt. For the first six months, net income totaled $ 215.4 million, or $ 2.92 a share, up 107 percent from $ 104.1 million, or $ 2.77 a share a year ago. Net interest earnings totaled $ 653.2 million, up from $ 360.7 million in the first six months of 1988. Non-interest income totaled $ 469.9 million, up from $ 233.9 million a year ago. Total assets at the end of the quarter amounted to $ 49.59 billion, up 109 percent from $ 23.62 billion a year ago.
