<HEAD>Actor Settles Suit Over Spokesman Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Actor <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> settled his lawsuit Thursday against <ORGANIZATION> Sperry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which dropped him as spokesman two years ago when it merged with <ORGANIZATION> Burroughs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to form <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The settlement, for an undisclosed amount, occurred just as jury selection was to begin in federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` I've never been in a courtroom before except in a movie _ and then I always knew my lines,'' <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> said after the settlement. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> had filed a breach of contract suit two years ago against <PERSON> Sperry </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION>, claiming termination of the contract wrecked his chances of getting a `` similarly prestigious and rewarding contract with any other major <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. corporation.'' The $ 17.8 million suit was later amended to $ 1.25 million. Terms of the settlement were n't revealed, but <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> said, `` Everyone is satisfied, I'm happy. ... I'm pleased it was amicably settled.'' <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> was <PERSON> Sperry </PERSON>'s corporate spokesman from October 1985 until it was acquired by <PERSON> Burroughs </PERSON> on Sept. 16, 1986. The company told <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> in a letter that it was assuming `` a new company name and corporate identity,'' and refused to take on <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' contract. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, star of `` Spartacus,'' `` Lust for Life'' and more than 70 other films, had claimed that the contract was supposed to continue if the Sperry product line or corporate identity survived a merger. The suit cited the continued marketing of some products with the Sperry logo. <ORGANIZATION> Unisys </ORGANIZATION> maintained that a clause in <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>' contract said that in the event of a merger, the contract would not continue unless both parties agreed, said <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Hynes </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, Pa.-based information systems company. `` I am grateful to go back to the world of make believe,'' said <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON>, who was accompanied in court by his wife, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON>. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> made personal appearances, television commercials and said he interrupted filming of `` Tough Guys'' with <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Lancaster </PERSON> to make a promotional film for <LOCATION> Sperry </LOCATION>. He said he has n't worked for any other companies as a spokesman, but would consider doing it again.
