<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices closed slightly higher Thursday in choppy, light trading, recouping some of the losses of the previous session. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the August contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, which dropped 38 cents on Wednesday, rose 20 cents to settle at $ 20.35 per 42-gallon barrel. Other contract months of the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> grade of crude posted even stronger gains. Refined petroleum products traded on the exchange also rose. The August contract for home heating oil was up 0.50 cent to settle at 49.44 cents a gallon after sliding 0.34 cent on Wednesday. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for August delivery was up 0.05 cent to settle at 57.46 cents a gallon. The gain added to Wednesday's increase of 0.79 cent a gallon <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Redoglia </PERSON>, vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>, noted that the market came back after Wednesday's technical selloff on fears that maintenance and platform workers on <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> rigs might go on strike. `` The reports of a further work slowdown ... seemed to hold the market,'' he said, noting that the impact was felt particularly among crude prices. On the whole, however, <PERSON> Redoglia </PERSON> characterized trading as `` relatively choppy on very light volume. The market had no momentum and no direction.''
