<HEAD>Car and Truck Sales Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table,f0160</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Early-July sales of North American-made cars and light trucks jumped 8.9 percent over the same period last year, the companies reported Thursday. The eight major U.S.-based automakers reported they sold vehicles at an average rate of 35,614 a day during the July 1-10 period this year compared with a rate of 32,696 during the same time last year. Car sales were up 9.3 percent and truck sales rose 8.3 percent. `` It's got to be surprising that they were up that much,'' said analyst <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nikko </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> But <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said he had expected sales to be a bit stronger because <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> had been advertising in incentive programs to take delivery by July 10. `` Early-July sales were inflated by that artificial July 10 deadline,'' he said, adding he expected slower mid-July sales. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s early-July car sales were up 11.3 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales rose 16.9 percent. Car sales by <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> fell 5.8 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is plagued with product availability problems, <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> said. The company is getting production and marketing for its <ORGANIZATION> Dodge </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Spirit </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acclaim </ORGANIZATION> in line as it phases out its K-cars, the Reliant and Aries. `` It's a phasing out and a phasing in and that's combined with an overall weak market,'' <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> said. The industry's early-July increases are compared with a period last year that worked out to be just about on trend for the entire year, the second-best in the industry's history. But for 1989 as a whole, sales this year are lagging behind last year's pace. The eight companies reported their combined car and light truck sales ran 4.4 percent behind last year's pace through July 10. So far this yea, the automakers have sold vehicles at a daily rate of 38,100 compared with a rate of 39,835 a day last year. Car sales were down 5.6 percent and truck sales were off 2.1 percent. One of the surprises in the early-July sales figures was a 31.8 percent drop in sales of U.S.-made Hondas. Demand for the cars has been tapering off and the company has offered its dealers incentives to get customers in showrooms. <PERSON> Heaney </PERSON> said there may be another problem. `` There's going to be a new Accord launched in the fall and when you know that, why do you want to buy last year's model?'' she said. Among the Big Three, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> sold cars at a daily rate of 6,923 during early July this year, up from a 5,919 car-a-day rate during the same time last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales so far this year were running 2.5 percent behind last year's pace. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> truck dealers were selling 3.6 percent more vehicles in early July this year than last year, but 3.8 percent fewer so far this year. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales went at a daily rate of 10,615 during early July this year compared with a rate of 9,534 during the same time last year. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales for the year were down 9 percent from last year. The company's truck sales ran 13.2 percent ahead of last year's pace in early July but were down 2.8 percent for the entire year <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales fell to a daily rate of 2,921 this year from the 3,100 daily rate of a year ago. For the calendar year, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s car sales were down 14.6 percent. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s trucks sold at a rate 1.6 percent higher in early July this year than they did a year ago. For the year, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s truck sales were down 0.7 percent.
