<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported a 27 percent drop in its second-quarter earnings and blamed much of the fall on the costs of three aircraft programs. The aerospace company said its after-tax earnings in the second quarter fell to $ 77 million, or $ 1.20 a share, from $ 106 million, or $ 1.77 a share, in 1988's second quarter. Revenue declined 3 percent to $ 2.45 billion from $ 2.53 billion a year earlier. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Tellep </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, said the deterioration in profit reflected $ 27 million in costs involving three aircraft programs. One of the programs included a phase-out of <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s P-3 aircraft production. The plane designed for hunting submarines had no customer prospects. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> last year selected <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> for development of the P-7A, a new generation anti-sub plane. The other two programs on which cost adjustments were made involve fixed-price development contracts for modifications to two <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> C-5As to transport space cargo and modification of a C-141 for an advance radar test bed. The overall decline in 1989 revenue and earnings was largely due to the cost of completing the new generation C-5B, <PERSON> Tellep </PERSON> said in a news release, which called the outlook for new defense contracts `` flat to declining.'' `` We remain confident that <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s strong core business programs will provide the basis for resumed earnings growth in 1990,'' <PERSON> Tellep </PERSON> said, pointing to continuing projects such as the stealth fighter plane and the P-7A. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> in April issued 10.7 million shares for the <ORGANIZATION> ESOP </ORGANIZATION> plan and successfully thwarted <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>' effort to take over the aerospace company. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION>'s move put 17 percent of the company's stock in employee hands, making it impossible for <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> to acquire the 85 percent needed for buyout approval. <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> acted before <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> made a tender offer. For the first half of the year, <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> earned $ 139 million, or $ 2.25 a share, down 37 percent from earnings of $ 220 million, or $ 3.61 a share, in 1988's first six months. Revenue amounted to $ 4.45 billion, down from $ 4.92 billion.
