<HEAD>Lawsuit Says Buyout was Attempt to Shirk Asbestos Claims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawyers seeking to represent more than 80,000 people filed suit Thursday against the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and leveraged buyout specialist <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> seeking to reverse the $ 2.4 billion takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Jim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Walter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> two years ago. The lawsuit, filed in state court in <LOCATION> Beaumont </LOCATION>, claims the buyout was a fraudulent attempt to escape more than $ 3 billion in liabilities stemming from asbestos claims against <ORGANIZATION> Celotex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, Fla.-based home-builder <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, also named as a defendant. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> last year sold <ORGANIZATION> Celotex </ORGANIZATION>, a long-time producer of asbestos, which has been proven to cause cancer and other health problems. `` I think this will prove to be a landmark case in this country,'' <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Susman </PERSON> said after the lawsuit was filed. However, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> said the claims were similar to those in a suit already in federal court and were without merit. The suit, which asks for class action status, seeks no monetary damages for three named plaintiffs or for the thousands of others it says have similar, separate lawsuits pending in courts around the country. Instead, it attempts to prevent the further sale of any <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> assets and to hold <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> and the remaining corporate structure responsible for any judgments related to asbestos-related lawsuits. `` We want to undo this transaction,'' <PERSON> Susman </PERSON> said. `` We want the people responsible for this transaction to be liable for any judgments in favor of more than 80,000 people who are seeking justice.'' The suit alleges <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION>' 1987 buyout of <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> was part of a scheme by <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> to evade its liability in the growing number of lawsuits being filed against <ORGANIZATION> Celotex </ORGANIZATION>. `` The intended effect of these transactions was to strip <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> of virtually all of its valuable assets and, as a necessary consequence, to limit the resources available to satisfy asbestos judgments against <ORGANIZATION> Celotex </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>,'' the lawsuit states. About $ 2 billion of the buyout was financed by bank loans, and the investment group led by <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> later sold bonds through <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> to replace the bank debt. Selected <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> assets have since been sold to help pay for the deal. `` This was a standard, garden-variety leveraged buyout,'' <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Townsend </PERSON> said Thursday. `` Consequently, our position has been and continues to be that the allegations set forth in the previous -LRB- federal -RRB- complaint and in this complaint are totally without merit and we intend to defend ourselves vigorously.'' The federal suit is similar, but names neither <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> as defendants and is limited to those plaintiffs who filed their asbestos lawsuits within the <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Susman </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Daly </PERSON> said the lawsuit addressed `` the same substantive issues that are already in federal court. That suit is without merit, and we think we'll win it.'' <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Anreder </PERSON> said the firm declined comment on the suit since it had not seen it.
