<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar started higher at the start of Friday's trading, while share prices on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> rebounded slightly from Thursday's close. The dollar opened at 139.60 yen, up 0.55 yen from Thursday's close of 139.05 yen In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it ended at 139.50 yen overnight. Trading was quiet as dealers waited for the release of major <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> economic indicators later Friday, including the nation's wholesale price index for June, traders said. The market expects the index to be only slighty lower than the previous month, said a Bank of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> trader, speaking on condition of anonymity. A lower figure would mean inflation is slowing. `` If the figure is larger than our expectation, it could be a major dollar-buying incentive,'' he said. `` Considering the dollar is not declining now despite our expectation for quite some time over the possible relaxation of monetary policy, I see little incentive for further dollar-selling,'' the trader added. On the stock exchange, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Average </ORGANIZATION> of 225 selected issues, which shed 70.36 points Thuarsday, inched up within the first 15 minutes of morning trading to 33,660.00, up 24.84 points, or 0.07 percent. The index's rise in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> followed a rise in the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> industrial average of 30 major issues in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> overnight, dealers said.
