<HEAD>First Skyscraper in Years Planned For Dallas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The developer of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>' upscale Galleria shopping and office complex announced plans Thursday to build a signature office tower for <ORGANIZATION> Oryx </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the city's first major skyscraper construction in several years. The announcement of the 26 - to 28-story building does not necessarily mean the city's lagging real estate market has recovered, analysts said, but nevertheless is welcome `` I do n't think it signals a turnaround; it signals a situation where you had a large user with a specific need,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Katopody </PERSON>, a partner in the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> office of <ORGANIZATION> Kenneth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leventhal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> accountants. He said there is a two-year supply of office space already built, with about a one-year inventory of Class A space. Neither will the tower add to downtown's distinctive skyline, as it will be built about seven miles north of the central business district near the intersection of two major highways. The building will be part of the Galleria complex, which includes two office towers _ one of 24 stories and one of 25 _ a <LOCATION> Westin </LOCATION> hotel and a four-story shopping mall. The complex was built by <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hines </PERSON> Interests. Nearby is the 24-story Occidental Tower, headquarters of <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Staman </PERSON> <PERSON> Ogilvie </PERSON>, executive vice president o