<FIRST>u f AM-SoybeanCorner 2ndLd-Writethru f0294 07-13 1016</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soybean Corner, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0294,1045</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses to Block Soybean Futures Liquidation Order</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 5th graf pvs, ``The preservation ...,''
to UPDATE with CBOT news conference, comments from Ferruzzi attorney and
court testimony. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `Board of ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Thursday denied a request by an Italian company to block a <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> order that is forcing the firm to sell a huge quantity of soybean futures. The lawsuit filed by <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, both subsidiaries of <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finanziara </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>, sought the restraining order and a permanent injunction against the exchange's directive. Published reports have said the firm was the object of the directive because it was trying to corner the soybean market _ something <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> spokesmen deny. The lawsuit claimed <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> had been irreparably injured by the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s order, which it said would diminish confidence in the market and hurt <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farmers. But <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>, who denied the request for a temporary injunction, said blocking the <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION>'s order could cause harm to the public. `` The preservation of procedures adopted by the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> is in the interest of the public,'' <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON> said in issuing his late-afternoon decision. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>'s attorney, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Fox </PERSON>, said he did not know whether the Italian firm would pursue the lawsuit or seek monetary damages. <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> praised the decision. He told a news conference late Thursday that there were over 40 million July soybean contracts open and abnormally low levels of stocks available to satisfy the contracts _ which would have resulted in a number of defaults without the exchange's order. He said the exchange's business conduct committee tried to promote the orderly liquidation of the contracts, but not enough market participants responded. During the hearing before <PERSON> Zagel </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fox </PERSON> said the emergency order forced the Italian firm to reduce its holdings of July soybean contracts by 20 percent on Wednesday and another 20 percent Thursday. He said the order `` did irreparable damage to <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>.'' <ORGANIZATION> CBOT </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Angle </PERSON> said the exchange had entered into discussions with <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> officials and had asked them to reduce their futures contracts, but they refused to comply. <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Carmichael </PERSON> said previously the exchange would `` vigorously'' fight the lawsuit. Soybean futures prices rose sharply Thursday in reaction to news of the lawsuit. Soybeans for delivery in July settled at $ 6.97 -LCB- a bushel, 11 cents above the previous day's settlement. The July contract skidded 39 -LCB- cents on Wednesday. In two related developments, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> called for an investigation of the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s directive and the <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> agriculture commissioner asked the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to check whether <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> officials may have benefited from the effects of the order. The Board of Trade, the world's largest market for grain and soybean futures, issued the emergency order Tuesday requiring any player holding obligations to receive or deliver more than 3 million bushels of soybeans for July delivery to reduce those holdings to 1 million bushels by the end of trading Thursday, when the July contract expires. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>'s lawsuit said the company holds obligations to take delivery of 23 million bushels of soybeans. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> also is believed to own a large quantity of physical soybeans. If it does not reduce its position in the futures market, <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> theoretically could force those on the other end of its futures contracts to deliver, possibly causing a scramble for supplies that would drive the price of its soybeans up sharply. <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> has said it accumulated large soybean supplies to keep its processing plants running and to meet export commitments, and that its large futures market position was a hedge against price fluctuations. <PERSON> Carmichael </PERSON> said the exchange's board of directors issued its order because it appeared there might not be enough deliverable soybeans available to satisfy all the contracts. The Board of Trade did not mention <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION> in its order and has refused to further explain the reasons for its decision. However, rumors among market watchers have pointed to <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>. In issuing the order, the exchange cited federal regulations that allow it take such action to ensure the orderly expiration of a futures contract. The <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soybean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> urged the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> to fully explain the reasons behind its order to soybean producers and processors, and saying failure to do so would be `` another blow to the credibility of the board.'' <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> Agriculture Commissioner <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> on Wednesday asked the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> to investigate whether any Board of Trade officials benefited from the emergency order. In a letter to <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sessions </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nichols </PERSON> said it was possible that some <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> board members who made the order held short positions _ obligations to sell soybeans _ and benefited from the price drop following the order. Exchange spokesmen would not comment on the developments. But an exchange official who spoke on the condition of anonymity dismissed as sour grapes the complaints of traders who ended up on the losing side of Wednesday's dizzying drop in soybean prices. `` Any time you have any sort of order affecting the market you're going to have someone complaining about it,'' he said `` Someone is always on the other side.'' Some traders said the exchange should have left the market alone to sort itself out. Others said the emergency order spawned confusion and public mistrust at time when the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s image has been tarnished by a federal investigation of suspected trading fraud Exchange member <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Merritt </PERSON>, a 22-year veteran of the grain pits, said soybean farmers _ a group the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> has been wooing for years _ felt betrayed. `` They feel like, why should they try to legitimately hedge when the sanctity of the contracts are being questioned,'' said <PERSON> Merritt </PERSON>, research director for <ORGANIZATION> Merchants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` They're having second thoughts about this right now and I think I probably speak for the entire brokerage community in saying that it's become quite an emotional issue.''
